[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction: The Sicilian O'Kelly"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ @@HeaderStart@@Introduction: The Sicilian O'Kelly@@HeaderEnd@@Hello and welcome to 100 Repertoires: The Sicilian O'Kelly!  This course provides a complete repertoire for Black against 1.e4,  based on the Sicilian Defence. We not only cover the namesake of the course, the O'Kelly Variation @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  @@EndBracket@@, but earlier sidelines, as well. Studying the less than 100 trainables of the course is enough to prepare you against White's most popular opening move, 1.e4.  Why play the Sicilian?  What to play against 1.e4? One of, if not THE most popular reply is the Sicilian Defence. Among top players, the Sicilian is usually the weapon of choice when aiming for a complicated fight and playing to win. It has an uncompromising reputation for good reason.   Let's consider the position after 1.e4 for a moment. White has placed a pawn in the centre and would certainly love to build the perfect pawn duo of e4 and d4. This would happen in the case of replies like  1...e6  ,  1...c6  , for example. Not the end of the world, of course @@StartBracket@@French and Caro-Kann are good openings!@@EndBracket@@, but you could argue that it must be desirable to stop White from building this strong centre.  This rationale is the reason for the popularity of  1...e5  and  1...c5  . These moves ensure that White can't build the perfect central pawn duo immediately. So both moves share a common strategic purpose – what is the key difference?  It comes down to 'symmetry versus asymmetry'. After 1.e4 e5,  Black tries to prove that being a tempo down in a symmetrical position does not matter. It is not uncommon to see both sides continue their development in a similar style, keeping the symmetry or staying close to it. A sequence like, for example, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.Bb5  Bb4  comes to mind to illustrate this point.  In the Sicilian, Black immediately unbalances the situation. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  , there is no similarity between both sides' development ideas. In fact, the move 1...c5 does not help much with piece development in the first place, while White can get closer to kingside castling with simple moves. The situation is non-symmetrical from the beginning, laying the foundation for the sharp Sicilian struggles. There is no way for White to simplify the position or trade many pieces early on.  Many openings have an 'Exchange Variation' @@StartBracket@@e.g @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  exd5  @@EndBracket@@, or 'Symmetrical Variation' @@StartBracket@@e.g. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  c5  @@EndBracket@@ – the Sicilian has neither. This makes it the ideal weapon to play to win with Black.  Why choose the O'Kelly?  Let's talk about the O'Kelly now. Whenever you consider playing the Sicilian, you need to decide what you'd like to play if White chooses the Open Sicilian. The Open Sicilian starts with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , followed by d2-d4,  opening the play in the centre of the board. Black has a wide choice on the second move, leading to popular and famous variations:  Very common is the Najdorf @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  a6  , the Dragon @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  g6  or the Sveshnikov @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  , to name just three of many.  We, however, don't go for one of these main lines but suggest playing the O'Kelly Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  , a fascinating sideline. Before we discuss the merits of our choice, a word about the origin of the opening.  Albéric O'Kelly de Galway, a Grandmaster and Correspondence World Champion from Belgium, invented our opening choice. He played it regularly and demonstrated some essential ideas in his games.  So what's the point of the early flank pawn move?  Isn't there something more urgent to do than playing a small pawn move? This claim has some logic, but concrete beats the abstract in chess. Let's consider what White can do against the O'Kelly and lay out the chapter structure of our course at the same time.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  the Open Mainline. This line is the most common in online play and games below master level. While the Open Sicilian is usually considered a critical try against other second moves @@StartBracket@@2...d6,  2...Nc6 etc.@@EndBracket@@, it is harmless against the O'Kelly. This is a huge practical incentive to play it, as you'll get a good game easily in many of your games.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.Nc3  , the Tricky Knights. White delays the move d2-d4,  which leads to a different type of Open Sicilian after  3...b5  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  . We have started an early queenside expansion and will reach a sharp Sicilian struggle with chances for both sides.  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c4  , the Maroczy Setup. White plays for a Maroczy Bind setup by playing the c-pawn first, followed by a later d2-d4. This variation is considered a critical try against the O'Kelly and we'll see that Black needs to be precise to gain fair chances.  D@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  . White opts for a delayed Alapin @@StartBracket@@ 2.c3 is the regular Alapin@@EndBracket@@, claiming that their extra move Nf3 must be more useful than our ...a6. This is undoubtedly correct, but it does not mean that White can prove an advantage. Our analysis shows that White can exert some pressure, but we hold our own nicely.  These four sections deal with White's main options after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  , but the course covers White's other tries against the Sicilian, too. These lines are covered as follows:  E@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nc3  leads to the Closed Sicilian and Grand Prix. We answer in style with  2...a6  , quickly expanding on the queenside.  F@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.d4  and  2.b4  . We cover White's gambits, the Morra and Wing Gambit, in a dedicated chapter. We take the pawn and show that Black has nothing to fear, quite the opposite. White is struggling to prove adequate compensation if we play precisely.  G@@EndBracket@@ Sidelines on move two and three. This chapter covers odds and ends, the rare lines that White may try early on. None of them is particularly dangerous, but it makes sense to study them briefly. Rare lines often rely on surprise value – better not be surprised.  All in all, we cover the Sicilian in these seven chapters. Should you start with them straight away? That's possible, but we suggest a different approach. In addition to the seven detailed chapters, we provide a Quickstarter Guide comprising the essential lines and a more profound overview of the most common ideas.  We recommend beginning with the Quickstarter and learning the fundamentals so you can quickly start employing the opening in your games. Next, you can deepen your knowledge by studying the dedicated chapters. You may use the order in which they are presented or elect to study lines you met in your games and want to know more about. There are different ways to learn, according to your needs and preferences.  We think the O'Kelly is a great way to enter the Sicilian adventure and hope you enjoy playing the opening as much as we enjoyed writing the course.  Good luck and great games! }
*

