1. e4 c5
{ Hello and welcome to the Quickstarter Guide for 100 Repertoires: The O'Kelly Sicilian!  The course covers a complete repertoire against 1.e4,  based on the Sicilian 1...c5. The Quickstarter will provide an overview of the essential lines to start playing the Sicilian in your games. We recommend studying it thoroughly and then proceeding with the dedicated chapters.  White has many options against the Sicilian. In the Quickstarter, we will focus on the lines you are most likely to face. We'll ignore most early sidelines and examine White's most popular lines.  1@@EndBracket@@ The Open Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  is White's most popular choice in games played below master level, where profound knowledge of theory is less common. Many players play 2.Nf3 and 3.d4,  more or less regardless of Black's second move. Against 2...a6,  however, 3.d4 is not a critical move and a welcome sight. More on the details later in the Quickstarter.  2@@EndBracket@@ The Tricky Knights line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.Nc3  . White avoids the immediate opening of the centre @@StartBracket@@line A@@EndBracket@@ but develops the b1-knight first. After  3...b5  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e6  , we reach a different type of Open Sicilian that leads to exciting play.  3@@EndBracket@@ The Maroczy Bind attempt @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c4  . Similar to line B, White delays the move d2-d4 to open the centre. After  3...Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e5  , we enter fun complications that will likely have great surprise value.  4@@EndBracket@@ The Alapin or 'c3-Sicilian'. The move c2-c3 intends to build a full centre and is possible after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  . We suggest an antidote that works in both instances and is covered in the Quickstarter via the first move order.  5@@EndBracket@@ White can go for a sideline on the second move. The most popular and covered in the Quickstarter are @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@Closed Sicilian or Grand Prix@@EndBracket@@ and the Morra Gambit, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.d4  cxd4  3.c3  , which we happily accept.  Let's get started with the Sicilian O'Kelly now! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "QS | 5B | Grand-Prix-Attack | 2.Nc3 a6 3.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ White develops their queen's knight first. This move does not yet reveal White's intentions, though. They have some choice of how to proceed afterwards. Here's an overview of possible ideas:  A@@EndBracket@@ Play a setup with g3, which is usually called Closed Sicilian.  B@@EndBracket@@ Play the pawn to f4 next, which is known as the Grand Prix Attack.  C@@EndBracket@@ They can still play Nf3 or Nge2, intending to transpose to an open Sicilian with d2-d4. This approach is common in master-level play but less so in amateur games.  We need to play in a way that makes sense in all three scenarios. }
2... a6
{ Well, if the move ...a6 works against 2.Nf3,  it will undoubtedly work against 2.Nc3,  as well!  Jokes aside, this is the most flexible move for us. If White continues with  3.Nf3  or  3.Nge2  , going for approach C mentioned before, we can still reach a typical O'Kelly position. Here are the common sequences to do that:   3.Nf3  or  3.Nge2  b5  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e6  transposes to the chapter Tricky Knights. You'll often meet this line if you play higher-level opposition, as they use 2.Nc3 sometimes as a move order device. They might have lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  d6  3.d4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  Nc6  3.Bb5  in mind, but against other second moves, they prefer to switch to an Open Sicilian.  Most of the time, White does not have a transposition to an open Sicilian in mind but rather goes for a setup with g3 @@StartBracket@@Closed Sicilian@@EndBracket@@ or f4 @@StartBracket@@Grand Prix@@EndBracket@@. In both cases, we'll play a quick ...b7-b5 advance and use ...Bb7 to put pressure on White's e-pawn.  From a conceptual point of view, it is instructive to note that we play a quick ...b7-b5 only after White has committed a knight to c3. Lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  a6  3.g3  b5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.Nc3  b5  are examples of this approach. Once a knight has appeared on c3,  the idea ...b5-b4 gains strength, in particular in reply to a2-a4 by White.  We can compare this to a sequence like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.d3  , when  3...b5?!  makes a lot less sense, as  4.a4  attacks the queenside, and the reply  4...b4  does not attack anything.  Alright, back to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  a6  . We have already learned that  3.f4  and  3.g3  are the major options that don't transpose to a different chapter. }
3. f4
{ The signal move for the Grand Prix Attack. The Grand Prix is one of the openings that benefits from its cool name but is not that dangerous if Black knows what to do.  It earned the name Grand Prix from a series of tournaments in the UK in the 1980s. Players like Mark Hebden and Julian Hodgson used it with great success, winning many events.  Our line 2...a6 is an excellent setup if White has the Grand Prix in mind. The Grand Prix usually involves a bishop development to b5 or c4,  which is clearly off the table after our natural reply  3...b5  . }
3... b5
{ It's also possible to play  3...e6  first and continue with ...b5 on the next move. We usually play a quick ...b5 against a knight on c3. Thus starting with  3...b5  is a bit more consistent and our choice. }
4. Nf3
{ White develops the knight to its natural square. White's general idea in the Grand Prix is to start play on the kingside, where White has more space at the moment.  We seek to play against White's centre, starting with  4...Bb7  . The bishop puts pressure on the e4-pawn. }
4... Bb7
{ White has to worry about ...b5-b4 now, pushing the crucial defender of the e4-pawn away. }
5. d3
{ The e-pawn needed protection. It's important to note that White initially intended to place their bishop outside the pawn chain, to c4 or b5. Our quick queenside expansion has prevented this, which will often catch White players wrong-footed, as they have to play a different setup compared to what they usually get on the board. }
5... e6
{ A good move, giving our bishop some scope. In most cases, we want to play ...d7-d5 soon, hitting White's centre again. Now, after  5...e6  , White has a choice.  The most common reply is  6.g3  , but this setup leads to very similar play as we examine via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  , when  3...b5  4.Bg2  Bb7  5.d3  e6  6.f4  is the main line. In this case, we play  6...Be7  , going for ...d5 next. The rationale behind this move order finesse is explained in the notes to this line.  Here, in a very similar spot, we can play in the same way, answering @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.f4  b5  4.Nf3  Bb7  5.d3  e6  6.g3  with  6...Be7  . A transposition to 3.g3 lines is very likely in this case.  We'll now examine a more aggressive option for White, pushing the g-pawn further. }
6. g4
{ White's most aggressive option, for sure.  As mentioned before, against  6.g3  , we advise you to play  6...Be7  first, delaying the move ...d5 for a while.   A similar answer is possible to  6.Be2  , which you'll also meet from time to time. }
6... b4
{ We recommend this move, planning to meet  7.Ne2  with  7...d5  . There are many alternatives for Black – let's look at why some are dubious, and some are possible, but not our choice.   A@@EndBracket@@  6...d5?!  is questionable due to  7.exd5  exd5  8.Qe2+  , when  8...Be7  9.g5!  takes advantage of the advanced g-pawn. We have no good way to develop our knight.   B@@EndBracket@@  6...Be7?!  7.g5!  is a similar story.   C@@EndBracket@@  6...Nf6  is the sharpest move and the best alternative. After  7.g5  Nh5  8.Ne5  g6  9.Be2  Black can play  9...d6  or  9...f6  , which leads to crazy complications that are not easy to master in practice. Objectively, Black is fine – but we felt it is not an economical solution to a variation as rare as 6.g4. Our solution is simpler to handle. }
7. Ne2 d5
{ We hit White's e-pawn, our normal approach against early f4-systems. We also thought about the move order  7...h5  , but after  8.g5!  White threatens the irritating move g5-g6. We can't play  8...g6?  , as the plan  9.Nh4  , followed by Bg2,  O-O and f4-f5 is crushing. }
8. e5 h5
{ Very important! We must play this preemptive strike on the kingside before White manages to organize their forces. }
9. gxh5
{ The only good move, as  9.g5?  gives up any hope on the kingside after  9...Ne7  . With the kingside locked, our advantage in the centre and queenside becomes even more valuable. }
9... Rxh5 10. Ng3 Rh8
{ Job done, return home! We have reached a fighting position with chances for both sides.  It's important to note that we can still, and often will, castle queenside. It does not matter much that we have moved the pawns on this side of the board. Our king will still be safe, as it is surrounded by many minor pieces.  Location in the Course    Chapter 5: Closed Sicilian and Grand-Prix-Attack  Variation 5B: Grand Prix with 3.f4 }
*

