[Black "QS | 5C | Closed Sicilian | 2.Nc3 a6 3.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ White develops their queen's knight first. This move does not yet reveal White's intentions, though. They have some choice of how to proceed afterwards. Here's an overview of possible ideas:  A@@EndBracket@@ Play a setup with g3, which is usually called Closed Sicilian.  B@@EndBracket@@ Play the pawn to f4 next, which is known as the Grand Prix Attack.  C@@EndBracket@@ They can still play Nf3 or Nge2, intending to transpose to an open Sicilian with d2-d4. This approach is common in master-level play but less so in amateur games.  We need to play in a way that makes sense in all three scenarios. }
2... a6
{ Well, if the move ...a6 works against 2.Nf3,  it will undoubtedly work against 2.Nc3,  as well!  Jokes aside, this is the most flexible move for us. If White continues with  3.Nf3  or  3.Nge2  , going for approach C mentioned before, we can still reach a typical O'Kelly position. Here are the common sequences to do that:   3.Nf3  or  3.Nge2  b5  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e6  transposes to the chapter Tricky Knights. You'll often meet this line if you play higher-level opposition, as they use 2.Nc3 sometimes as a move order device. They might have lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  d6  3.d4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  Nc6  3.Bb5  in mind, but against other second moves, they prefer to switch to an Open Sicilian.  Most of the time, White does not have a transposition to an open Sicilian in mind but rather goes for a setup with g3 @@StartBracket@@Closed Sicilian@@EndBracket@@ or f4 @@StartBracket@@Grand Prix@@EndBracket@@. In both cases, we'll play a quick ...b7-b5 advance and use ...Bb7 to put pressure on White's e-pawn.  From a conceptual point of view, it is instructive to note that we play a quick ...b7-b5 only after White has committed a knight to c3. Lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  a6  3.g3  b5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.Nc3  b5  are examples of this approach. Once a knight has appeared on c3,  the idea ...b5-b4 gains strength, in particular in reply to a2-a4 by White.  We can compare this to a sequence like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.d3  , when  3...b5?!  makes a lot less sense, as  4.a4  attacks the queenside, and the reply  4...b4  does not attack anything.  Alright, back to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  a6  . We have already learned that  3.f4  and  3.g3  are the major options that don't transpose to a different chapter. }
3. g3
{ White opts for the Closed Sicilian. They intend to fianchetto the bishop, which safely protects the e-pawn.  A common idea for White is a later kingside offensive, based on pushing the pawns forward. Often it starts with f2-f4, followed by the g-pawn. We'll see some of these ideas in the lines we are about to examine. }
3... b5
{ Here we go. We are playing multiple pawn moves on the queenside and neglecting development, but White's setup is also slow. Our general idea is playing ...Bb7 next to increase pressure on White's centre. }
4. Bg2 { White's natural continuation after 3.g3. } 4... Bb7
{ We challenge White's fianchettoed bishop and start to put some pressure on the e4-pawn. White usually continues with  5.d3  now, but there are some alternatives. The knight moves to e2 and f3 are possible but likely have little independent value. Let's have a look:  A@@EndBracket@@  5.Nge2  e6  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/1b1ppppp/p7/1pp5/4P3/2N3P1/PPPP1PBP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nge2  e6  6.O-O  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  b4  leads to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.Nc3  , the Tricky Knights chapter.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.Nf3  e6  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  is the same story.  Note that @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/1b1ppppp/p7/1pp5/4P3/2N2NP1/PPPP1PBP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b4?  6.Na4  is bad for Black, as the c5-pawn is attacked. In both cases, White does not need to continue with d2-d4 but may also play d2-d3,  which will be very similar to our main line 5.d3.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.f4  or  5.Nh3  has also been tried. Still, White can hardly do without playing d2-d3 in the long run, so again this will transpose to 5.d3-territory. }
5. d3
{ By far, White's most popular move. As mentioned in the notes to 4...Bb7, the alternatives are mostly transpositional. }
5... e6
{ Finally, we move a centre pawn!  It's important to note that we don't always intend to play ...d5 in the 3.g3 lines. This is different to our approach against the Grand Prix when this is commonplace. We will, however, play based on ...d5 against White's popular continuation  6.f4  .  This makes it easier to remember: If White plays an early f4,  going for ...d5 is a good reply.  Why is ...d5 a good idea versus f4-setups and not so much versus others? We are behind in development. If we play ...d5,  White may capture on d5 to open the game quickly.  This is far less of an issue after f4 is on the board. The pawn move did not help White's development and worsened our opponent's pieces. It blocks the c1-bishop and takes away f4 for a knight.  Think about this line:  6.Nge2  d5?  7.exd5  exd5  8.Nf4  Nf6  9.Qf3  and Black loses the d5-pawn! Once the move f4 is on the board, we don't need to worry about such a scenario.   What options does White have now? In the Quickstarter, we'll focus on White's most common move,  6.f4  . White may also play the g1-knight first and prefer  6.Nge2  ,  6.Nh3  or  6.Nf3  . In these cases, as demonstrated above, we should not play a quick ...d5 but stay flexible with moves like ...Be7 and ...Nc6. The knight moves are explored in more detail in the dedicated chapter. }
6. f4 { The most likely continuation to face. } 6... Be7
{ Similar to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/1b1p1ppp/p3p3/1pp5/4P3/2NP2P1/PPP2PBP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nh3  Be7  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/1b1p1ppp/p3p3/1pp5/4P3/2NP2P1/PPP2PBP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nge2  Be7  , we suggest playing the bishop move first.   Didn't we talk about playing ...d5 against f4-based setups? Yes, but we need to be careful about timing. The move  6...d5  is possible, but White has the annoying reply  7.f5!?  , which is difficult for Black to handle. A key idea for White is  7...b4  8.fxe6!  , which leads to a dangerous attack @@StartBracket@@at least@@EndBracket@@.   The critical point is to wait with ...d5 for a move. There are two good ways to do it:  6...Be7  or  6...Nc6  . We prefer ...Be7 against White's other options on move 6, which makes our decision easier. We'll just play  6...Be7  in all cases. }
7. Nf3
{ White's most logical move. They could play  7.Nge2  Nc6  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qk1nr/1b1pbppp/p3p3/1pp5/4PP2/2NP2P1/PPP3BP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nh3  Nc6  , which will likely transpose to 6.Nge2 or 6.Nh3. }
7... d5
{ Here we go! Now we'll examine  8.O-O  , which keeps the tension for the moment.  An alternative for White is  8.e5  , but after  8...g6!  and often ...h5 soon after, we stall White's kingside play. We have good chances in this line, as our queenside attack is already underway. }
8. O-O
{ Keeping the tension looks better than the pawn advance  8.e5  , which commits White prematurely.  It's not an easy decision, though – after  8.O-O  Black has  8...b4  , pushing away a defender of the e-pawn. Should we play this move? }
8... d4
{ We advise you to avoid the move  8...b4  , as there are two potential issues:  A@@EndBracket@@  9.exd5?!  is not objectively correct, but tricky to handle after  9...bxc3  10.dxe6  fxe6  11.bxc3  , when White has a simple target on e6,  and we are not well coordinated. The engine likes Black, but it's not a simple task.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qk1nr/1b2bppp/p3p3/2pp4/1p2PP2/2NP1NP1/PPP3BP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Na4  is the more severe problem when  9...dxe4  10.dxe4  Qxd1  11.Rxd1  Bxe4  12.Be3  gives White dangerous play for the pawn. Our queenside is weak, and we are behind in development.   We don't like our defensive task in these scenarios and prefer the space-gaining advance  8...d4  instead. }
9. Ne2 Nf6 { The most precise move, stopping g3-g4 for the moment. } 10. h3
{ White wants to play g3-g4 for two reasons: attacking the kingside and clearing a square for the e2-knight.  We want to highlight a point of our setup: we place our knights on c6 and d7, which is very flexible. }
10... Nc6 11. g4 Nd7
{ A prophylactic retreat, completing the mentioned knight setup. Also, note that we have not castled kingside yet! What's the point? Our knights are well-placed for both defence and offence. Here are some key points – White has to think twice about further kingside advances now.  A@@EndBracket@@ The move  12.f5  gives up control of e5 and is answered by  12...g5!  , stopping a knight jump to f4.   B@@EndBracket@@ What about  12.g5?  we play  12...h6!  13.h4  hxg5  14.hxg5  Qc7  and castle queenside! We are enjoying the open h-file now – White's play led nowhere.   C@@EndBracket@@ After  12.e5  , we suggest  12...Qc7  and ...c4 next, similar to our main line @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1b1nbppp/p1n1p3/1pp5/3pPPP1/3P1N1P/PPP1N1B1/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Ng3  Qc7  . }
12. Ng3
{ White transfers the knight to the kingside. This move is the most popular in online games and undoubtedly logical. }
12... Qc7
{ A strong move. Our queen helps prepare our play on the queenside. We want to advance the c-pawn next. At the same time, the queen connects to the e5 and g3 squares. White can't advance the f-pawn now, as the g3-knight is unprotected. }
13. Qe2
{ This move seems to prevent ...c5-c4,  but it falls short.  White has other ideas, of course. One could be  13.e5  when we'd also play  13...c4  , leading to the same structure. }
13... c4
{ It works anyway! As we will see, White can't grab the c-pawn. Before we look at this crucial line, we should discuss what happens in other cases.  We suggest keeping the king in the centre and focusing on the c-file instead. A sample line for this scenario is  14.e5  Rc8  15.g5  Nb4  , going for the invasion on c2. Both sides have many options in these closed positions: all pawns and pieces are still on the board. }
14. dxc4 { Going for the pawn grab is too risky. } 14... bxc4 15. Qxc4 a5
{ That's the big point. The threat ...Ba6 is extremely strong. After  16.Rd1  Ba6  17.Qb3  Rb8  18.Qa4  Nb6  , we trap the queen!   White's relatively best option is  16.Nxd4  Bc5  17.c3  Ba6  , 'only' losing the exchange.  As mentioned in the notes to the move 13...c4!,  White has to avoid the greedy pawn grab. If they do, the resulting positions are rich and exciting to play for both sides.  Location in the Course    Chapter 5: Closed Sicilian and Grand-Prix-Attack  Variation 5C: Closed Sicilian with 3.g3 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "QS | 6A | Morra Gambit | 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4
{ The Smith-Morra Gambit  2.d4  cxd4  3.c3  dxc3  4.Nxc3  is White's most popular gambit continuation against the Sicilian Defence. It is more or less never played on the professional level but quite frequently seen in online play or at the club level.  Is it a bad opening line for White, then? Well, it's unpopular amongst higher-rated players because Black has a wide range of promising options. White might still get reasonable compensation for the pawn, but it is not easy at all to prove and quite theoretically demanding for White.  At the club level, one attraction for White is that the setup Nc3,  Nf3,  Bc4,  O-O,  Qe2,  Be3/f4 and rooks to d1 and c1 is easy to learn and remember. The bad news for White is that ONLY knowing this setup is not enough.   We'll see that White needs to be precise and that 'auto-pilot' play will give us better chances. Before we continue, we'd like to add that  2.Nf3  a6  3.d4  cxd4  4.c3  dxc3  5.Nxc3  is an alternative route to the lines suggested in this chapter. The early ...a6 is a good move for Black anyway. }
2... cxd4 3. c3
{ You sometimes meet  3.Nf3  , when  3...a6!  is a fun way to stay within the realms of our repertoire. }
3... dxc3 4. Nxc3
{ What does White get in return for the pawn? In the Smith-Morra, White's compensation is mainly based on a lead in development. White is already a bit ahead and has an easy plan. They will almost invariably continue with Nf3,  Bc4 and O-O,  getting the kingside developed quickly.  This will increase the lead in development even more, as we still need to make some pawn moves to get the pieces out. We'll talk more about our specific setup in a moment.  Still, one general remark is appropriate here already: White's lead in development is significant, but the position is neither wide open nor can it be opened easily. This means that often White might have more pieces in play at the beginning, but there is no immediate clash in which that may matter. This is a difference to the position types after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  , when being behind in development may prove fatal.   Before we continue, a word about  4.Bc4  , which offers an additional pawn. It's a rare move, as White does not have enough play for two pawns after  4...cxb2  . As mentioned in the paragraph above, there is no direct clash of both sides, so the additional development does not matter much.  We are happy to grab the pawn and will go for the same setup as in the main line 4.Nxc3: we play ...e6,  ...a6,  ...b5 and so on. }
4... a6
{ We want to play ...e6 and ...a6 – it does not matter what move you play first. Let's discuss the merits of Black's setup once both are on the board. }
5. Nf3
{ This natural development move is played almost exclusively.  This position could also arise via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.d4  cxd4  4.c3  dxc3  5.Nxc3  , which occurs from time to time. }
5... e6
{ We complete the first stage of our setup against the Smith-Morra, starting with the moves ...a6 and ...e6. What's next?  The first important point is that we don't hurry with kingside development and castling. There are two reasons. First, it is not easy at all to develop the kingside actively. The move ...Nf6, for example, is not easy to play, as White has e4-e5 in reply. You could stop this by playing ...d6 first, but this means that the f8-bishop will remain passive for a while. Not a bad setup, by any means, but not particularly aggressive, either.  The second, more important point is: We don't need to emphasise kingside development in the first place. Our king is safe on e8, and we have many good options on the queenside, as we will discuss in a moment. The idea is to get in the active moves we can play easily, and only then complete kingside development and castle.  Usually, we'll later develop the f8-bishop to c5 or b4 and then continue with ...Ne7, rather than ...Nf6. This way, we avoid the often disturbing e4-e5 advance.  How do we start the queenside play?  We want to play ...b5 and develop the bishop to b7, but going ...Nc6-a5 is an important idea, too. Note that White will almost always play their bishop to b3, so ...Na5 is an attractive option. We either trade the important bishop or force it to a more passive square.  Once the bishop and knight are out, we can play ...Rc8, too. Let's have a look at some concrete lines now. }
6. Bc4
{ White's standard bishop placement in the Morra. It is played almost all the time. Does White have any good alternatives?  You rarely meet  6.a4?!  . It stops the move ...b5,  but it's very slow and weakens the queenside. We are in good shape against it in various ways, for example, by developing with ...Nc6,  ...Bc5 and ...Nge7.   A better option for White is  6.Bf4  , but it's extremely rare, too. We can choose between still playing with  6...b5  , similar to our main lines, or opting for a setup with ...Nc6 and ...Nge7.   If White does not develop their bishop to c4,  trying to play ...d5 is possible for Black. In any case, we should focus on  6.Bc4  , as this is the move you will be facing almost exclusively. }
6... b5 { Here we go, putting the move ...a6 to good use. } 7. Bb3 Nc6
{ We suggest starting with 7...Nc6,  aiming for a quick ...Na5 to fight White's bishop.  Of course, it's no mistake to start with  7...Bb7  , but the play is somewhat different. The quick ...Nc6-a5 is more direct, as White needs to answer the important question if they want to keep the bishop or lose time. }
8. O-O
{ White's most logical and popular move.  White may also start with a different slow move, like  8.Qe2  , when we can play the same setup, we suggest after 8.O-O. A sample line is  8...Na5  9.Bc2  Bb7  10.O-O  Rc8  11.Rd1  Bc5  , when we'd reach an even better version of our main line. }
8... Na5
{ A rare, but strong move.  More often than not, Black plays  8...Bb7  . This move is no mistake at all and a good alternative. In our mind,  8...Na5  is even stronger, though. White needs to move their bishop again or give up the bishop pair. We need to examine both options. }
9. Bc2
{ The bishop retreat is White's most popular move by a mile. It's an understandable decision, as White went for an ambitious opening setup and generally wants to keep pieces on for a later attack.  A closer look, however, reveals that it is quite unclear what White's target is going to be. Our king is currently safe in the centre, and White has no way to open this part of the board.  Instead of  9.Bc2  , White may also give up the bishop pair and play  9.Re1  , when we continue  9...Nxb3  10.Qxb3  Bc5  to develop our kingside. White has the scary move  11.Nd5?  , when  11...exd5?  12.Qxd5  leads to a nasty double attack. After @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/3p1ppp/p3p3/1pbN4/4P3/1Q3N2/PP3PPP/R1B1R1K1 b kq - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...d6!  , however, we are in great shape.  The move 9.Re1 is interesting and explored in more detail in the dedicated chapter. }
9... Bb7
{ The natural spot for our bishop. We also prepare ...Rc8,  using the open file. Now we'll check two moves for White.  The most common one is  10.Qe2  , continuing with the 'usual moves' that are on White's agenda. We'll see that Black is doing fine against it.  A more aggressive alternative for White is  10.e5  , which grabs some space and clears the e4-square for a piece. Knowing the best plan against this concept helps immensely, as the solution is not apparent.  Let's check both moves now. }
10. Qe2
{ White's usual spot for the queen in the Smith-Morra. It's the most popular move, as White often plays it regardless of Black's setup.  They could also try  10.e5  , when  10...Rc8  11.Ne4  Be7!  12.Re1  f5!  demonstrates a good way to fight the centralized e4-knight. }
10... Rc8 { According to plan, we develop the queenside first. } 11. Rd1
{ That's the move White prepared with 10.Qe2. The rook is certainly well placed on the half-open file, looking at our extra pawn on d7. }
11... Bc5
{ We have played all the good moves on the queenside. Now it's time to get the kingside organised. The way to go is ...Bc5 and ...Ne7. Our bishop is actively placed on c5, and playing the knight to e7 avoids the potential kick e4-e5 if we'd develop it to f6 instead. }
12. Bg5
{ A logical move, developing with tempo.  If White prefers  12.e5  , the move  12...f5!  takes control of e4,  a recurring idea of our recipe against the Morra. }
12... Qb6
{ We place the queen on an active square, a very natural move. The alternatives  12...Ne7  or  12...Be7  are fine, too. }
13. Nd5
{ This doesn't work, but it's good to know why!  A better move is  13.e5  , but after  13...h6  14.Bf4  Ne7  14.Ne4  Nd5  White has no compensation for the pawn. }
13... exd5 14. exd5+ Kf8 { The best move, avoiding a pin on the e-file. } 15.
Ne5 { White has to act quickly to make it somewhat interesting. } 15... Qd6
{ The only winning move! We needed to cover the d7-pawn.  The move  15...Qc7?  is worse, as  16.Nxf7!  is possible and forces a draw after  16...Kxf7  17.Qh5+  Kf8  18.Qf3+  .  After the correct queen move, White's attack is stopped.  Location in the Course    Chapter 6: Morra and Wing Gambit  Variation 6A: Morra Gambit with 2.d4 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "QS | 2D | Tricky Knights | 2.Nf3 a6 3.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. Nc3
{ White continues with their development, a natural and good choice. Is there a deeper concept behind the move? They might just want to play along with general principles, but a compelling idea is connected to the knight move.  Let's assume our opponent might usually play the Open Sicilian, for instance after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.d4  or after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.d4  , opening the game. However, they know that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  is fine for Black. By playing @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  3.Nc3  , White hopes for a transposition to a mainstream Open Sicilian, going for d2-d4 on the next move.  What to do with the black pieces? We have no chance to get to our favourite Open Sicilian, as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  3.Nc3  can't be answered by  3...Nf6?  due to  4.e5  , when there is no good reply.  The way to go is allowing a transposition to a different Open Sicilian, which leads to exciting play for both sides. }
3... b5
{ Here we go! We didn't play ...a6 for nothing, after all 😊. Still, there are good alternatives at this point that are worth mentioning.  A@@EndBracket@@ If you have some experience/knowledge of the Najdorf,  3...d6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nf6  is a good way to transpose to this popular opening.   B@@EndBracket@@ The continuation  3...e6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  is a second good option. Black could go  5...b5  now, which would transpose to the lines examined in this chapter. Besides 5...b5,  the moves  5...Qc7  ,  5...Nc6  or  5...d6  are possible, too.   Line B is very similar/transpositional to our suggestion. We decided to use the  3...b5  move order as it felt more natural and similar to lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  a6  3.g3  b5  , for example.  @@StartBlockQuote@@We play ...b5 if there is a knight on c3 to attack. @@EndBracket@@@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
4. d4
{ The only critical move.  White may also play the slow move  4.g3  , but this would transpose to play similar to the Closed Sicilian,  covered in our chapter on 2.Nc3 a6. }
4... cxd4 { We get an Open Sicilian after all. } 5. Nxd4
{ Black has two sound and logical moves here, 5...e6 and 5...Bb7. The difference between them is subtle. In most cases, we'd reach precisely the same positions, as Black usually needs both moves quickly. Let's examine the difference.  In both cases, the most critical reply is 6.Bd3 @@StartBracket@@more on that later@@EndBracket@@, when  5...e6  6.Bd3  Qb6  is our suggestion. We immediately attack the d4-knight and try to push it away from the centre. If White plays  7.Be3  , the reply  7...Bc5  gives us fair chances.   This idea does not work after  5...Bb7  6.Bd3  Qb6?  7.Be3  , when we can't play the bishop to c5. Black would need to play a different idea on move 6 in this line.  We, however, like the ...Qb6 idea and therefore need to play 5...e6 first. }
5... e6
{ We have already discussed why we prefer starting with this move instead of 5...Bb7. What's next? Our general idea and ideal development scheme to go for is the following:  ➤ Play ...Bb7  ➤ Play ...Nf6 next, if White can't favourably reply e4-e5  ➤ If e4-e5 is a problem, the move ...Qc7 is an excellent way to cover against it  It looks like these moves are very natural, increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn. We don't want to play ...b5-b4 quickly but rather pile up on the e4-pawn to make ...b5-b4 a more profound idea, ideally winning the centre pawn!  White needs to make up their mind about how to develop the pieces. Our idea is to attack the e4-pawn quickly. It is therefore not a surprise that 6.Bd3 is a sensible move for White. In fact, it is the only move that poses a severe theoretical challenge to our opening concept.  Why? The critical point is that after 6.Bd3,  we can't play our ideal moves so quickly. After  6.Bd3  Bb7  7.O-O  the move  7...Nf6?  is answered with  8.e5!  Nd5  9.Nxd5  Bxd5  , when White has many strong ideas, often involving Qg4.  If White does not play 6.Bd3,  however, we will obtain good chances without any particular problems, using a quick ...Bb7 and ...Nf6,  often prepared by ...Qc7.  We'll check some concrete moves in a moment, but we'd like to discuss an additional point first. Our queenside play is much faster than in many other Sicilian setups. We have already played ...a6 and ...b5,  gaining space on this side of the board. This renders a possible queenside castling by White less attractive than in other Sicilian lines, where it is commonplace.   As mentioned, it looks best for White to prioritize kingside castling and support the e4-pawn, which is why 6.Bd3 looks like the most dangerous move. Let's have an overview of White's options.  White's Options  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a way for White to play for queenside castling. The setup Be3/Qd2 and O-O-O,  often accompanied with f3,  is called English Attack and a popular approach in many Sicilian lines, particularly the Najdorf. As mentioned above, we are happy to see White's king on the side of the board where our play has already started.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  is an unpopular but reasonable line for White. Placing the bishop on g2 helps cover the e4-pawn and prepares kingside castling. In some cases, the play can become quite sharp. We exert intense pressure on the e-pawn, which might prompt White to sacrifice material to avoid a passive setup.  C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is similar to 6.g3. White prepares O-O and will often cover the e-pawn with Bf3 later.  D@@EndBracket@@  6.a3  is a move that we are happy to see. White spends a tempo on securing their knight but, in the process, loses valuable time. This move is the most popular at the amateur/club level and in online games. This statistic is a significant incentive to play our suggested quick ...b5-line. Many players on the white side will go for a non-critical reply like 6.a3,  making our life easy.  E@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  is the most dangerous move and slightly different to the alternatives above. We won't be able to generate quick play against e4,  as the pawn is better protected now. We suggest playing  6...Qb6  , trying to force the white knight back to a less active square. This idea gives this line a different feel to A-D above.  In the Quickstarter, we'll examine D and E. We focus on the most common move @@StartBracket@@D@@EndBracket@@, and most challenging one @@StartBracket@@E@@EndBracket@@. }
6. a3
{ White spends a tempo to stop ...b5-b4. We didn't threaten this move immediately, but White often feels annoyed enough by it to feel provoked to play the a-pawn.  The move 6.a3 is White's most popular move in online play and lower-level games, which makes it essential to study. Let's check how the game unfolds. After our natural reply, White has a choice again. }
6... Bb7
{ Now, White faces the same choice as on the move before. What bishop move to play? The most crucial move to check is  7.Bd3  , but we'll also discuss the alternatives in the notes. }
7. Bd3
{ This looks like the most exciting try for White.  You'll also meet  7.Be2  or  7.Be3  , but our setup will be the same as after 6.Be2 or 6.Be3. We'll just go for ...Qc7 and ...Nf6,  increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn. Sample lines are:  A@@EndBracket@@  7.Be2  Qc7  8.O-O  Nf6  9.Bf3  Nc6  gives Black a great game. We might play ...Ne5 next, aiming at the f3-bishop and the juicy c4-square. White's play is slower compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/3p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  Bb7  7.Bf3  , which allows us the more active ...Nf6 approach.   B@@EndBracket@@  7.Be3  Qc7  8.f3  Nf6  9.Qd2  d5  10.exd5  Nxd5  looks good for Black, too. The move a3 and the aggressive Be3 + f3 don't fit well. }
7... Qc7
{ This looks like the best solution.  Why not 7...Qb6?  The move  7...Qb6  looks logical and in line with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/3p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  Qb6  , but there is a somewhat strange tactical issue about it:   After  7...Qb6  8.Be3  Bc5  9.Nce2  Nc6  White has the fun move  10.b4!  when  10...Bxd4  11.Nxd4  Nxd4  12.c3  leads to complications that look promising for White.  Why 7...Qc7 is good in this position   Here, we can afford  7...Qc7  , as White doesn't manage a quick e4-e5,  which would be the issue about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/3p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  Bb7  7.O-O  Qc7  8.Re1  , when  8...Nf6  9.e5!  is great for White.  The move 6.a3 more or less loses a tempo, which makes a substantial difference. }
8. O-O { A natural move. } 8... Nf6
{ Here we go! We have completed our standard setup, which is not so easy to do against Bd3-setups.  How does this position compare to our line against 6.Bd3, by the way? We play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/3p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  Qb6  7.Nb3  Qc7  8.O-O  Bb7  in this line. We needed to spend a tempo @@StartBracket@@...Qb6-c7@@EndBracket@@ to enable a ...Nf6 setup.  Against 6.a3,  we accomplish our favoured piece placement one move faster, as we play ...Qc7 in one move. On the other hand, White still has the knight on d4 but has spent a tempo on the move a3. The nature of the play is still somewhat similar.  A key idea for White is again preparing the pawn push e4-e5,  sometimes even supported by the move f2-f4. We have a range of options regarding our setup. A critical decision is the placement of our b8-knight. It's possible to play ...d7-d6 and continue with ...Nb8-d7,  but developing it to c6 without playing the d-pawn is an option, too.  A fun idea is playing ...Bd6!?,  which comes into consideration if White can't favourably reply with e4-e5 @@StartBracket@@fork!@@EndBracket@@ or f2-f4,  which threatens the annoying fork.  We'll have a look at some lines now to illustrate ideas. }
9. Qe2
{ We'll examine this as the primary move, but White has many alternatives.  A@@EndBracket@@  9.Re1  is similar to 9.Qe2 and can be answered by  9...Bd6!?  , fighting for the dark squares.  10.h3  Nc6  11.Be3  Nxd4  12.Bxd4  Bh2+  13.Kh1  Be5  demonstrates this concept.   B@@EndBracket@@  9.Be3  should not be met with  9...Bd6  , as 10.f4 is possible. A good solution is switching to  9...d6  , with ...Nbd7 next. There is nothing wrong about  9...Nc6  , either. White's setup is not aggressive enough to limit our options.   C@@EndBracket@@  9.Bg5  can be met with  9...Be7  and ...d6/...Nbd7 next, Again, we have some leeway here due to White's slow play. }
9... Bd6
{ A cool idea, fighting for the dark squares in the centre. White can't reply with  10.f4??  , as  10...Bc5  11.Be3  Qb6  is an early end of White's hopes. They lose material and  12.Qf2  Ng4  does not help. }
10. h3 Nc6 11. Be3
{ After  11.Nxc6  , all recaptures are playable. Interesting lines are  11...dxc6  12.f4  e5  or  11...Qxc6  12.f4  e5  , with good play for Black in both cases. Our pieces are active and in the case of  11...dxc6  you could argue that Black even plays for an advantage in space. }
11... Bh2+
{ We argue that White's king is slightly worse on h1 than on g1 and insert this check. On h1 the king is further away from the centre @@StartBracket@@endgame@@EndBracket@@ but also on the diagonal of our b7-bishop. This could help with tactics later. }
12. Kh1 Bf4
{ We stop f2-f4 by simply occupying the square. Our position looks fine, as we don't have to worry about the central pawn-push e4-e5 for the moment.  White's position is certainly healthy, but they lack a clear plan. We will castle kingside next and have typical Sicilian ideas next, like playing on the c-file.  Location in the Course    Chapter 2: Tricky Knights  Variation 2D: Tricky Knights with 6.a3 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "QS | 2E | Tricky Knights | 2.Nf3 a6 3.Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. Nc3
{ White continues with their development, a natural and good choice. Is there a deeper concept behind the move? They might just want to play along with general principles, but a compelling idea is connected to the knight move.  Let's assume our opponent might usually play the Open Sicilian, for instance after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.d4  or after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.d4  , opening the game. However, they know that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  is fine for Black. By playing @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  3.Nc3  , White hopes for a transposition to a mainstream Open Sicilian, going for d2-d4 on the next move.  What to do with the black pieces? We have no chance to get to our favourite Open Sicilian, as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  3.Nc3  can't be answered by  3...Nf6?  due to  4.e5  , when there is no good reply.  The way to go is allowing a transposition to a different Open Sicilian, which leads to exciting play for both sides. }
3... b5
{ Here we go! We didn't play ...a6 for nothing, after all 😊. Still, there are good alternatives at this point that are worth mentioning.  A@@EndBracket@@ If you have some experience/knowledge of the Najdorf,  3...d6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nf6  is a good way to transpose to this popular opening.   B@@EndBracket@@ The continuation  3...e6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  is a second good option. Black could go  5...b5  now, which would transpose to the lines examined in this chapter. Besides 5...b5,  the moves  5...Qc7  ,  5...Nc6  or  5...d6  are possible, too.   Line B is very similar/transpositional to our suggestion. We decided to use the  3...b5  move order as it felt more natural and similar to lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  a6  3.g3  b5  , for example.  @@StartBlockQuote@@We play ...b5 if there is a knight on c3 to attack. @@EndBracket@@@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
4. d4
{ The only critical move.  White may also play the slow move  4.g3  , but this would transpose to play similar to the Closed Sicilian,  covered in our chapter on 2.Nc3 a6. }
4... cxd4 { We get an Open Sicilian after all. } 5. Nxd4
{ Black has two sound and logical moves here, 5...e6 and 5...Bb7. The difference between them is subtle. In most cases, we'd reach precisely the same positions, as Black usually needs both moves quickly. Let's examine the difference.  In both cases, the most critical reply is 6.Bd3 @@StartBracket@@more on that later@@EndBracket@@, when  5...e6  6.Bd3  Qb6  is our suggestion. We immediately attack the d4-knight and try to push it away from the centre. If White plays  7.Be3  , the reply  7...Bc5  gives us fair chances.   This idea does not work after  5...Bb7  6.Bd3  Qb6?  7.Be3  , when we can't play the bishop to c5. Black would need to play a different idea on move 6 in this line.  We, however, like the ...Qb6 idea and therefore need to play 5...e6 first. }
5... e6
{ We have already discussed why we prefer starting with this move instead of 5...Bb7. What's next? Our general idea and ideal development scheme to go for is the following:  ➤ Play ...Bb7  ➤ Play ...Nf6 next, if White can't favourably reply e4-e5  ➤ If e4-e5 is a problem, the move ...Qc7 is an excellent way to cover against it  It looks like these moves are very natural, increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn. We don't want to play ...b5-b4 quickly but rather pile up on the e4-pawn to make ...b5-b4 a more profound idea, ideally winning the centre pawn!  White needs to make up their mind about how to develop the pieces. Our idea is to attack the e4-pawn quickly. It is therefore not a surprise that 6.Bd3 is a sensible move for White. In fact, it is the only move that poses a severe theoretical challenge to our opening concept.  Why? The critical point is that after 6.Bd3,  we can't play our ideal moves so quickly. After  6.Bd3  Bb7  7.O-O  the move  7...Nf6?  is answered with  8.e5!  Nd5  9.Nxd5  Bxd5  , when White has many strong ideas, often involving Qg4.  If White does not play 6.Bd3,  however, we will obtain good chances without any particular problems, using a quick ...Bb7 and ...Nf6,  often prepared by ...Qc7.  We'll check some concrete moves in a moment, but we'd like to discuss an additional point first. Our queenside play is much faster than in many other Sicilian setups. We have already played ...a6 and ...b5,  gaining space on this side of the board. This renders a possible queenside castling by White less attractive than in other Sicilian lines, where it is commonplace.   As mentioned, it looks best for White to prioritize kingside castling and support the e4-pawn, which is why 6.Bd3 looks like the most dangerous move. Let's have an overview of White's options.  White's Options  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a way for White to play for queenside castling. The setup Be3/Qd2 and O-O-O,  often accompanied with f3,  is called English Attack and a popular approach in many Sicilian lines, particularly the Najdorf. As mentioned above, we are happy to see White's king on the side of the board where our play has already started.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  is an unpopular but reasonable line for White. Placing the bishop on g2 helps cover the e4-pawn and prepares kingside castling. In some cases, the play can become quite sharp. We exert intense pressure on the e-pawn, which might prompt White to sacrifice material to avoid a passive setup.  C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is similar to 6.g3. White prepares O-O and will often cover the e-pawn with Bf3 later.  D@@EndBracket@@  6.a3  is a move that we are happy to see. White spends a tempo on securing their knight but, in the process, loses valuable time. This move is the most popular at the amateur/club level and in online games. This statistic is a significant incentive to play our suggested quick ...b5-line. Many players on the white side will go for a non-critical reply like 6.a3,  making our life easy.  E@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  is the most dangerous move and slightly different to the alternatives above. We won't be able to generate quick play against e4,  as the pawn is better protected now. We suggest playing  6...Qb6  , trying to force the white knight back to a less active square. This idea gives this line a different feel to A-D above.  In the Quickstarter, we'll examine D and E. We focus on the most common move @@StartBracket@@D@@EndBracket@@, and most challenging one @@StartBracket@@E@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Bd3 { We think this is White's best bet for an advantage. } 6... Qb6
{ We already talked about the rationale behind this move. By attacking the d4-knight, we start direct play and try to kick it to a less attractive square. In the Quickstarter, we'll now focus on the most popular move  7.Nb3  . White has interesting alternatives, though.  The move  7.Nf3  is challenging and leads to sharp play. Similarly to  7.Nb3  , we need to play  7...Qc7  against it and then continue with ...Bb7.   White may keep the knight on d4 by playing  7.Be3  , when  7...Bc5  is the best reply. We put more pressure on the centralized knight. }
7. Nb3
{ White retreats to b3, a more common square than f3 for the knight in a Sicilian. Often, White wants to use the f-pawn later, as we will see in our main line. }
7... Qc7
{ It is essential to play this move first! If you start with  7...Bb7?  , White has  8.a4  b4  9.a5!  Qc7  10.Na4  , when Black's position is on the brink of collapse. }
8. O-O
{ Now  8.a4  b4  is fine for Black, as White has to move the knight to a passive square. }
8... Bb7
{ Our natural development of the bishop. White has a range of options now; let's get an overview.  A@@EndBracket@@  9.f4  is the most aggressive move, preparing the move e4-e5 in reply to ...Nf6. We suggest the move  9...b4  , followed by ...Nf6.   B@@EndBracket@@  9.Be3  completes White's development and is often combined with f2-f4,  usually played right on the next move. As 9.Be3 does not threaten e4-e5 in reply to our knight jump, we advise starting with  9...Nf6  against it.   C@@EndBracket@@  9.Re1  is a different way to prepare e4-e5 and discourage our knight development. We have a cool reply in  9...Bd6!?  , though, an idea we have already examined in the sideline 6.a3.   D@@EndBracket@@  9.Qe2  follows a similar idea as  9.Re1  , planning to answer  9...Nf6?  with 10.e5. We think it's best to play  9...b4  , as White can't retreat to e2 and needs to go to less attractive squares.  On a general note: All these lines are very sharp and promise an exciting fight. In many cases, White struggles to find the best moves in practice, which is underlined by Black's excellent score. If you play the Sicilian, you want an uncompromising fight!   Our focus in the Quickstarter is the move  9.f4  – it's the most popular and sharpest choice by our opponent. }
9. f4
{ Pushing the f-pawn immediately is White's most aggressive option. They anticipate the development of our king's knight to f6 and prepare the reply e4-e5, attacking our piece. }
9... b4
{ We recommend pushing the b-pawn first. The other logical option is  9...Nf6  , but after  10.e5  Nd5  11.Ne4!  White manages to centralize their knight. We prevent this idea by first attacking the knight. }
10. Ne2
{ White usually chooses this move, keeping the knight close to the centre.  Instead,  10.Na4??  is a huge blunder due to  10...Qc6  when the knight is trapped. For example,  11.Na5  Qxa4  12.Nxb7  Qc6  13.Na5  Qc5+  .   A much better move is  10.Nb1  , when Black has a choice of good replies that lead to equal chances. The engine likes  10...a5  , but  10...Nc6  or  10...Nf6  are fine, too.  The main move, 10.Ne2 poses more problems. }
10... Nf6
{ Now is a good time to attack the e-pawn. Compared to the earlier @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/1bqp1ppp/p3p3/1p6/4PP2/1NNB4/PPP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq f3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nf6  10.e5  Nd5  11.Ne4  , we have ensured that White can't get their knight to e4 easily. Now White needs to decide what to do about the attacked e-pawn. In practice, this question is not easy to answer, and often White goes wrong. }
11. e5
{ The only good move, but not an easy decision. White gains space but at the same time allows our knight to jump to the attractive d5-square. Our b7-bishop is looking strong, too.  Stockfish gives White a small advantage after 11.e5, but we'll see that this assessment means little – we're in for a complicated fight.   Before we continue, we need to discuss the move  11.Ng3?  , which is played far more often in practice. It is a huge mistake, though! After  11...Qb6+  12.Kh1  h5!  13.Qf3  h4  14.Ne2  h3  we can start a strong attack in no time and gain a substantial advantage. }
11... Nd5
{ We have reached a very complex position, typical of the non-symmetrical struggles of the Sicilian. Here White's most frequently played move is  12.Ng3  , which we'll examine as our main line.  However, this move does not seem to follow the best possible play, as indicated by Stockfish. In practice, the engine lines are less likely to happen, but we need to be ready. The engine suggestion is the unintuitive move  12.Kh1  , which is difficult to understand at first. We'll have a closer look here. }
12. Ng3
{ White connects their knight with the central square e4, a very logical move and by far the most popular. White intends to primarily play in the centre and on the kingside. }
12... Nc6
{ We suggest this move, but  12...a5  or  12...Be7  are reasonable alternatives. }
13. Ne4 { White completes the knight tour. } 13... a5
{ That's the most active move, directly going for ...a4. White has to figure out where to move the knight after this attack. At first, you might think that Nbc5 is possible, but we have a tactic after this move.  The most challenging continuation is a sacrificial line, suggested by the engine. Alright, let's have a look. }
14. c4
{ This move is unlikely to happen, but we need to consider it. Why is it unlikely? It involves a sacrifice, as  14...bxc3  15.bxc3  a4  16.Nbd2  Ne3  is a possible line! We'll check this in a moment. What else is there for White?   They could play  14.Kh1  , when  14...a4  15.Nbc5  Bxc5  16.Nxc5  Nxe5!  reveals that tactical idea we talked about earlier. After  17.fxe5  Qxc5  18.Qf3  f5  19.exf6  gxf6  20.Qh5+  Kd8  21.Rxf6  Rg8  , the position is a complete mess.  According to the comp, it's 'equal'. Well, 'equal' does not mean boring! }
14... bxc3 15. bxc3 { Here  15.Nxc3?  Ncb4  is great for Black. } 15... a4 16.
Nbd2 { White can't play  16.Nbc5  due to  16...Nxc3!  , winning a pawn. } 16...
Be7
{ We award the exclamation mark for practical reasons, not because  16...Ne3  would be a mistake. This move is possible but after  17.Qe2  Nxf1  18.Nc4  Be7  19.Ncd6+  Kf8  20.Ba3  White has a dangerous attack. Stockfish manages to defend, but it's not fun.   After our suggestion  16...Be7  it will likely continue with  17.Nc4  O-O  18.Ncd6  f5!  , which fights White's knight successfully.  We feel that @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/1bqp1ppp/p3p3/3nP3/1p3P2/1N1B4/PPP1N1PP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Ng3  Nc6  13.Ne4  a5  14.c4  is rather unlikely to happen in practice, but it is reassuring that Black has fair chances even against the best engine lines.  Location in the Course    Chapter 2: Tricky Knights  Variation 2E: Tricky Knights with 6.Bd3 }
