[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "QS | 3B | Maroczy Setup | 2.Nf3 a6 3.c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. c4
{ The move  3.c4  is one of the best replies to the O'Kelly. What is White's idea? In some way, they are after a maximalist setup. White wants to involve the c-pawn in the central struggle. They play to open the centre only after the c-pawn is in play.  If White plays  3.d4  immediately, they won't manage to get the move c2-c4 in. After  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  we attack the e-pawn when  5.Nc3  obstructs the c-pawn.   So what to play after  3.c4  – Black has two basic options. Let's have a look at the first one. Black can play a 'small move', like 3...d6 or 3...e6. In this case, White manages to realize their idea.  Here's a typical line.  3...e6  4.Nc3  Nc6  5.d4  cxd4  6.Nxd4  , when White has achieved their conceptual goal. They have built the 'Maroczy Bind', as it is called @@StartBracket@@e4 + e4,  with d-pawn traded for c-pawn@@EndBracket@@. Black can play this type of position, but we see two drawbacks:  The first is that White is objectively somewhat better due to the substantial space advantage. The second objection is more of a psychological nature: we don't like to allow White the type of game they aimed for. It's better to fight our opponents on less familiar grounds.   This leads to our recommendation, the move  3...Nc6  . Let's discuss the merits of this particular reply once it is on the board. }
3... Nc6
{ We recommend fighting White's Maroczy approach with 3...Nc6. Our idea is very concrete: if White avoids the critical move 4.d4 now, we'll play ...e5! and close the centre for the foreseeable future. This leads to two distinct scenarios:  A@@EndBracket@@  4.d4  is the only critical move. After  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  we'll play  5...e5!  , leading to sharp play.   B@@EndBracket@@ We play ...e5 after White plays a slow move, for example,  4.Nc3  e5!  , which is fine for Black. The blocked centre shifts focus to playing on the flanks. We are well positioned for this struggle, as ...a6 helps our ambitions on the queenside. White's f3-knight, however, blocks the f-pawn.  Pushing f2-f4 or ...f7-f5 are key ideas in this structure – again, we are well prepared, as our knight is not on f6 yet. Playing ...f5 is easier for us than for White. }
4. d4
{ The only challenging move. Otherwise, we push ...e5 and stop White from opening the centre. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5
{ That's the idea of playing 3...Nc6. We don't go for a slow setup but rather play a sharp central strike. White needs to move their central knight, but where?  It's interesting to compare this position to the Kalashnikov Sicilian, which occurs after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  . In the Kalashnikov, the only critical move is  5.Nb5  , trying to play ...Nd6+.   This idea is off the table in our O'Kelly version, as we have ...a6 already played. On the other hand, White has the move  6.Nf5  in our line, with similar ideas. This knight jump is the only critical line and the main focus of chapter 3.  If White plays a different move, we get the opportunity to develop our f8-bishop actively to c5 or b4. The position type after the various knight retreats @@StartBracket@@6.Nc2,  6.Nb3 and 6.Nf3@@EndBracket@@ is quite similar. We'll have a look at  6.Nc2  and  6.Nb3  , illustrating the key ideas. If White chooses one of these moves, it's enough to know a setup and general plans.  However, after the critical  6.Nf5  we have no good slow option and need to start concrete, tactical play. This is based on the move  6...d5!  , which will often catch your opponents by surprise. The complications after 6...d5 are less based on general considerations but tactics. Instead of 6...d5,  Black has also tried  6...d6  , but this move is too passive for our taste. }
6. Nc2
{ White retreats the knight and keeps the squares d4 and b4 covered. This move is popular but straightforward to handle for Black. Our target setup is as follows:  A@@EndBracket@@ Attack the e-pawn and prepare kingside castling with ...Nf6.  B@@EndBracket@@ Develop our bishop to c5.  C@@EndBracket@@ Play ...d6.  We suggest playing the moves in this order, but it is not a crucial issue if you start with  6...Nf6  or  6...Bc5  - it will very likely lead to the same positions.   This standard setup is also the way to go if White had opted for  6.Nf3  , a less frequently seen knight retreat. }
6... Nf6
{ We suggest starting with 6...Nf6,  but  6...Bc5  is not a mistake and likely just a different way to reach the same positions. }
7. Nc3
{ Very natural and almost always played.  White could cover the e-pawn with  7.f3  or  7.Bd3  , but  7...Bc5  is a simple and good reply. The resulting positions are very similar to our main line but a bit less challenging, as White gives up some flexibility – they don't need the move f3 urgently or benefit from putting a piece on the d-file.  In any case, we'd continue as we do against 7.Nc3: develop the bishop to c5,  ...O-O and ...d6. }
7... Bc5
{ A strong, active square for our bishop.  Now we examine two different approaches: White can try  8.Be3  , going for a trade of our bishop, or continue developing with  8.Be2  . }
8. Be3
{ White offers a trade, recognizing the strength of our bishop. Our response is important: to take or not to take, that's the question.  Instead of  8.Be3  , White may also develop the kingside with  8.Be2  . In this case, we have more control of the d4-square. After a sequence like  8...d6  9.O-O  O-O  10.a3  we can use this fact by playing  10...Nd4!  – this idea is stopped by White's Be3-move. }
8... d6
{ We think this move is a bit better than taking. We never fear the capture on c5, as this only helps us. The d6-pawn can't be attacked that easily but still may be a future weakness. After a trade on c5, this weakness is gone. It looks better for White to avoid the trade.  We want to keep the tension, as well. As long as our bishop sits on c5, our d-pawn is safely guarded. }
9. Qd2
{ White keeps the tension.  We'd be happy about  9.Bxc5?!  dxc5  10.Qxd8+  Nxd8  , as this pawn transformation can only be good for Black. Our potential d6-weakness is gone, and we have a better bishop. In the long run, White's f1-bishop may become a problem. }
9... O-O 10. Be2
{ White also could have started with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1p3ppp/p1np1n2/2b1p3/2P1P3/2N1B3/PPN2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Be2  , of course. Move orders are not that crucial here. It's most important to remember that we don't take on e3 but continue developing. }
10... Be6 { The natural spot for the bishop. } 11. O-O
{ White might think of the idea a3 and b4,  but  11.a3??  Na5!  is a cold shower!   After  11.O-O  Black has some options. We'll show a key idea and point out some general considerations. }
11... Nb4
{ We suggest this direct idea, but it is not the only option. Black could also play  11...Rc8  or  11...Qa5  . In all cases, we have some play on the queenside to pursue. }
12. Rac1
{ A logical reply. We threatened to capture on c2 and e3,  destroying White's pawn structure. A sample line is  12.Rfd1?  Nxc2  13.Qxc2  Bxe3  14.fxe3  Rc8  15.b3  b5  , when White is falling apart.   Better, but still uncritical, is  12.Nxb4  Bxb4  13.f3  Rc8  , which is comfortable for us. After the trade, it's easier for us to play on the queenside. }
12... Rc8
{ Here,  12...Qa5  is a good alternative. The only practical drawback is  13.Bg5  , when you must play  13...Qd8  , offering a repetition. }
13. b3
{ White stabilizes the queenside, a good move. Now  13...Qa5  is logical, but  14.Bg5  would force the retreat  14...Qd8  . We, therefore, suggest a different, more combative move. }
13... h6
{ We stop any Bg5 idea and want to play ...Qa5 next. All the pieces are still on the board, so both sides have many options.  A line that Stockfish now suggests is  14.Rfd1  Qa5  15.Bd3  Nxc2  16.Bxc5  dxc5  17.Qxc2  Nd7  , with a complicated struggle. Our knight ideally wants to transfer to d4 via b8-c6-d4 or f8-e6-d4. Chances are equal here.  Location in the Course    Chapter 3: Maroczy Setup  Variation 3B: Maroczy Setup with 4.d4 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "QS | 3B | Maroczy Setup | 2.Nf3 a6 3.c4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. c4
{ The move  3.c4  is one of the best replies to the O'Kelly. What is White's idea? In some way, they are after a maximalist setup. White wants to involve the c-pawn in the central struggle. They play to open the centre only after the c-pawn is in play.  If White plays  3.d4  immediately, they won't manage to get the move c2-c4 in. After  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  we attack the e-pawn when  5.Nc3  obstructs the c-pawn.   So what to play after  3.c4  – Black has two basic options. Let's have a look at the first one. Black can play a 'small move', like 3...d6 or 3...e6. In this case, White manages to realize their idea.  Here's a typical line.  3...e6  4.Nc3  Nc6  5.d4  cxd4  6.Nxd4  , when White has achieved their conceptual goal. They have built the 'Maroczy Bind', as it is called @@StartBracket@@e4 + e4,  with d-pawn traded for c-pawn@@EndBracket@@. Black can play this type of position, but we see two drawbacks:  The first is that White is objectively somewhat better due to the substantial space advantage. The second objection is more of a psychological nature: we don't like to allow White the type of game they aimed for. It's better to fight our opponents on less familiar grounds.   This leads to our recommendation, the move  3...Nc6  . Let's discuss the merits of this particular reply once it is on the board. }
3... Nc6
{ We recommend fighting White's Maroczy approach with 3...Nc6. Our idea is very concrete: if White avoids the critical move 4.d4 now, we'll play ...e5! and close the centre for the foreseeable future. This leads to two distinct scenarios:  A@@EndBracket@@  4.d4  is the only critical move. After  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  we'll play  5...e5!  , leading to sharp play.   B@@EndBracket@@ We play ...e5 after White plays a slow move, for example,  4.Nc3  e5!  , which is fine for Black. The blocked centre shifts focus to playing on the flanks. We are well positioned for this struggle, as ...a6 helps our ambitions on the queenside. White's f3-knight, however, blocks the f-pawn.  Pushing f2-f4 or ...f7-f5 are key ideas in this structure – again, we are well prepared, as our knight is not on f6 yet. Playing ...f5 is easier for us than for White. }
4. d4
{ The only challenging move. Otherwise, we push ...e5 and stop White from opening the centre. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5
{ That's the idea of playing 3...Nc6. We don't go for a slow setup but rather play a sharp central strike. White needs to move their central knight, but where?  It's interesting to compare this position to the Kalashnikov Sicilian, which occurs after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  . In the Kalashnikov, the only critical move is  5.Nb5  , trying to play ...Nd6+.   This idea is off the table in our O'Kelly version, as we have ...a6 already played. On the other hand, White has the move  6.Nf5  in our line, with similar ideas. This knight jump is the only critical line and the main focus of chapter 3.  If White plays a different move, we get the opportunity to develop our f8-bishop actively to c5 or b4. The position type after the various knight retreats @@StartBracket@@6.Nc2,  6.Nb3 and 6.Nf3@@EndBracket@@ is quite similar. We'll have a look at  6.Nc2  and  6.Nb3  , illustrating the key ideas. If White chooses one of these moves, it's enough to know a setup and general plans.  However, after the critical  6.Nf5  we have no good slow option and need to start concrete, tactical play. This is based on the move  6...d5!  , which will often catch your opponents by surprise. The complications after 6...d5 are less based on general considerations but tactics. Instead of 6...d5,  Black has also tried  6...d6  , but this move is too passive for our taste. }
6. Nf5
{ The knight jump forward is the only challenge. Just as in the Kalashnikov or Sveshnikov, White aims at the d6-square. }
6... d5
{ 'Yiehaaa!' In over the board Chess, you really should not shout during the game, but this is the kind of move that makes you want to!  This move might come as a shock to your opponent. It seems impossible, as White can capture the d5-pawn in three ways. However, only one is good and needs deeper investigation: the move  7.cxd5  , which is the subject of the rest of this chapter. What about the other captures?   A@@EndBracket@@  7.exd5?  is as bad as it looks after  7...Bxf5  8.dxc6  Qxd1+  9.Kxd1  bxc6  , when White's king is exposed and their position seriously weakened by the move of the c-pawn. We'll get a huge attack by simple development.   B@@EndBracket@@  7.Qxd5?!  is not as bad as A above, but still a welcome sight for us. After  7...Bxf5  8.Qxd8+  Rxd8  9.exf5  Nb4  , we are attacking White's king as early as move nine.  Let's examine White's best move now, taking with the c-pawn. }
7. cxd5 { The only good move for White and almost exclusively played. } 7...
Bxf5 { The idea of 6...d5! – we remove White's dangerous knight. } 8. exf5
{ Again, White's only good move, as  8.dxc6?  Qxd1+  9.Kxd1  Bxe4  10.cxb7  Bxb7  is great for Black. What is White's king doing on d1,  besides being an easy target for us? }
8... Nd4
{ We jump on this great central square and now attack the d-pawn. The next moves,  9.Nc3  Nf6  , are very natural for both sides. Once they are on the board, we'll investigate the details of our concept more closely. }
9. Nc3
{ White covers the d-pawn and develops the knight – by far White's most popular move. They have a good alternative in 9.Bd3,  though.  After  9.Bd3  , we recommend the simple solution  9...Nf6  , when  10.Nc3  transposes to our main line of  9.Nc3  Nf6  10.Bd3  , examined later in the current chapter.   There is an independent option  9.Bd3  Qxd5  , but it does not seem better than 9...Nf6 and thus only means an additional workload for little benefit.   A dubious move for White is  9.Bc4?!  , when the simple  9...Rc8  is annoying for White; our opponent likely must play  10.Bd3  now, losing a full tempo with the bishop. }
9... Nf6
{ We need to speed up our kingside development and get closer to castling. Now we examine three continuations for White, leading to different scenarios.  A@@EndBracket@@  10.Bd3  is by far the main move. White develop the bishop and prepares kingside castling – a very natural choice. In these lines, White keeps the bishop pair, and we need to be precise to get fair chances.  B@@EndBracket@@  10.Bg5  also makes a lot of sense. Whites pins our knight, trying to keep the d5-pawn. After  10...Be7  , they need to capture our knight to realize this idea, but in the resulting position, we'll have good play for the pawn. The opposite-coloured bishops are a vital factor, making the material deficit meaningless.   C@@EndBracket@@  10.g4!?  is a rarely played, fun move. Almost needless to say, it leads to sharp play! White gains massive space on the kingside but says 'Goodbye!' to a safe king position long-term.   In the Quickstarter, we will explore White's main continuation  10.Bd3  . }
10. Bd3
{ White develops and prepares kingside castling. According to 'classical' principles, this move is White's best bet for an advantage. }
10... Be7
{ It's crucial not to confuse the move order at this point. It looks logical to regain the pawn, but  10...Nxd5?  is a mistake. After  11.O-O  Be7  12.Be4!  we have no good reply.   It's much better to first get the king out of the middle of the board by starting with  10...Be7  and castling next. White can't keep the d5-pawn anyway, so we don't need to rush its capture. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Re1
{ What could be more logical? White develops the rook and attacks our pawn. You might also meet  12.Be3  , which is slightly less precise. After  12...Nxd5  13.Nxd5  Qxd5  14.Qg4  Bf6  , we reach a similar position as in the main line @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1p2bppp/p4n2/3PpP2/3n4/2NB4/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 7 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Re1  Nxd5  13.Nxd5  Qxd5  , but White has played the less useful move Be3 instead of Re1. }
12... Nxd5
{ We have regained our pawn, but what about the e5-pawn? White can indeed take it, but it's nothing to worry about, as we'll see in a minute. }
13. Rxe5
{ White takes our e-pawn, but after the correct reply, the capture leads nowhere. Still, the pawn grab is the move that you are most likely to encounter and featured in our Quickstarter.  The most challenging move from an analytical point of view is  13.Nxd5  , when  13...Qxd5  leads to a position in which we enjoy the strong d4-knight, but White has the bishop pair.  We analyze these positions in the dedicated chapter, but for the purpose of the Quickstarter it's more relevant to establish why the far more popular capture is harmless. }
13... Nxc3 { The start of a forced tactical sequence. } 14. bxc3 Bf6
{ We gain time by attacking the rook. White has no choice but to move it, as  15.cxd4??  Qxd4  wins on the spot. }
15. Re1
{ Going back to e1 looks best, coordinating White's pieces.  After  15.Re3  we just have  15...Nxf5!  , seeing that the white queen is unprotected. }
15... Nb5
{ Now we either win the c-pawn or force White to capture the knight, giving up the bishop pair. }
16. Bxb5 axb5
{ We have a comfortable position, with excellent compensation for the pawn. White can easily go wrong with moves like  17.Bb2?  @@StartBracket@@or  17.Bd2?  @@EndBracket@@ b4,  when White's position collapses.  White's best seems to be  17.Qb3  , when various queen moves are fine for Black, like  17...Qa5  or  17...Qd3  . White has to be careful, while our moves are easy to find.  Location in the Course    Chapter 3: Maroczy Setup  Variation 3B: Maroczy Setup with 4.d4 }
