[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "QS | 4B | Delayed Alapin | 2.Nf3 a6 3.c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. c3
{ This 'delayed Alapin' is recommended in many repertoire books, for example, in Christof's Keep It Simple: 1.e4 and Wesley So's Lifetime Repertoire.  As we show in this repertoire, the O'Kelly is by no means easy to play against. If you construct a repertoire for White, you need pragmatic solutions against rare lines. In the case of the O'Kelly, many lines for White are not attractive @@StartBracket@@  3.d4  @@EndBracket@@ or rather sophisticated @@StartBracket@@  3.c4  and  3.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@.  The line  3.c3  is a good solution for White, as it poses problems, but does not require that much work for White, in comparison to the mentioned alternatives. }
3... d5
{ We think this line gives Black the best chances against 3.c3.  The other satisfactory option is  3...e6  , but  4.d4  d5  5.e5  would transpose to a French Defence, which does not fit well with our repertoire concept. }
4. exd5
{ That's White's only challenging move. You sometimes meet  4.e5?!  , which is well answered with  4...Bg4  . This is best compared to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.e5?!  , when we recommend  3...Nc6  4.d4  Bf5  5.Be2  e6  6.O-O  cxd4  7.cxd4  Bg4  , leading to fine play for Black.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.e5?!  Bg4  we are likely to reach a similar scenario with the extra move ...a6,  as we managed to develop the bishop to g4 in one go. }
4... Qxd5
{ Well, you shouldn't move the queen too early in the opening – unless it's good 😝  Here, Black's play is justified, as White has already committed a pawn to c3. Therefore, the easy tempo-gain Nc3 is off the table @@StartBracket@@compare to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@.   Here, in the Alapin, our queen is not so easily chased around but still could be vulnerable in the middle of the board. We'll look closer at White's options on move six, as  5.d4  e6  is the almost universal continuation. We'll also briefly check if White can delay the move d4,  but it does not make a substantial difference. }
5. d4
{ White's most natural and best move. How to react? Let's have a look:  A@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4  looks active, but after  6.Be2  e6  7.O-O  Nf6  8.h3  Bh5  both  9.Be3  @@StartBracket@@as already covered in Keep It Simple: 1.e4@@EndBracket@@ and  9.c4  lead to an advantage for White.   B@@EndBracket@@  5...Nf6  looks natural, but  6.Be3!  is tough to meet. We don't want to trade on d4,  as after  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  White will play Nc3 next, chasing our queen. On the other hand, White attacks the c5-pawn after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/1p2pppp/p4n2/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , which turns  6...e6  7.dxc5!  into a problem.   C@@EndBracket@@  5...Nc6  6.Be3!  is a similar story to 5...Nf6. We don't want to take on d4,  but c5 is attacked. The line @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Be3  e6  7.dxc5  shows an issue of our position: the vulnerability of the c-pawn. This leads to our idea to start with @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  when  6.Be3  can be answered with  6...Nd7!  , which lends additional support to c5. }
5... e6
{ We think this move gives Black the best prospects, as the alternatives lead to problems @@StartBracket@@see the notes to 5.d4 for more information@@EndBracket@@.  After 5...e6,  White has a wide range of options. It is crucial to study these moves and appreciate their differences, as there is no general setup or concept we could apply. We must address each White option as an independent line and learn a specific response.  Of course, there are some common themes, but it is essential not to confuse our replies. Let's have an overview of White's ideas and discuss some of the key differences.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a critical move. White intends to win a pawn with dxc5,  which we stop with  6...Nd7  , as already discussed in the notes to move  5.   B@@EndBracket@@  6.c4  attacks our queen. We retreat to d8 and get fair chances.   C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is a popular choice for White. Against this move, the most straightforward recipe is  6...cxd4!  , immediately clarifying the central structure. It is the only case of the direct trade on d4,  as we don't mind fighting the IQP after White has committed the bishop to e2.   D@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  looks a bit more active than  6.Be2  , looking towards the kingside. It's crucial NOT to take on d4 early on against this move, as the arising IQP structure is much better for White than the situation after  6.Be2  cxd4!  . The difference between these two versions is discussed in more detail in the notes to these moves.   E@@EndBracket@@  6.Na3  is aimed at exploiting the weak b6-square, jumping to c4 next. We have not yet committed the b8-knight, which proves useful after  6...Nf6  7.Nc4  Nbd7  , when we safely cover our weakness. }
6. Be2
{ Surprisingly, this modest-looking move is White's most popular choice. A closer look reveals that it has a lot more bite than you might think at first glance. The first important decision for us is whether we want to trade on d4 or not. }
6... cxd4
{ Black has to be careful with the early trade on d4. We create an IQP @@StartBracket@@most of the time@@EndBracket@@, but also give White the option to play Nc3 quickly, gaining time on our queen. Against 6.Be2,  we recommend taking on d4. The exclamation mark is a bit strong, but we decided to award the exclam as it is the ONLY case when we advise to take on d4 on move  6.  It is crucial to understand the difference to 6.Bd3,  when we should NOT take on d4. Why? Let's compare:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@6.Be2  cxd4  7.cxd4  Nc6  8.Nc3  Qd6  9.O-O  Nf6   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  cxd4?  7.cxd4  Nc6  8.Nc3  Qd6  9.O-O  Nf6   In variation A @@StartBracket@@we'll get to this position in a minute@@EndBracket@@, White has nothing better than a standard development move, like @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1nqpn2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bg5  or  10.Re1  , while in variation B, the sequence @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1nqpn2/8/3P4/2NB1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne4!  Nxe4  11.Bxe4  is surprisingly strong. The e4-bishop is fantastically placed, and Black has to be careful to survive the next moves. Something like  11...Be7  12.Ne5  Nxe5  13.Bf4!  is even worse than it looks at first.  Long story short: the IQP position with a bishop on e2 is MUCH easier for Black to handle than with a bishop on d3. The difference is so significant that we recommend avoiding the IQP after 6.Bd3 in the first place.  We have established that taking on d4 is our concept against 6.Be2. Should we take it straightaway, or is it possible to delay the move for a while? We suggest taking it immediately for two reasons. The first one is that it is easier to remember if the defining action of a variation is played directly rather than later. The second reason is that waiting too long could prove annoying.  One example is @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  Nf6  7.O-O  Be7?!  , when  8.Ne5!  is surprisingly problematic for Black. White prepares Bf3,  attacking our queen. We can avoid these ideas by taking on d4 immediately. }
7. cxd4
{ White creates the IQP and is happy about gaining a tempo with Nc3 soon. Taking with a piece is entirely harmless, as we achieve the move ...e6-e5 effortlessly.  A@@EndBracket@@  7.Nxd4  e5!  8.Nf3  Qxd1+  9.Bxd1  f6   B@@EndBracket@@  7.Qxd4  Qxd4  8.Nxd4  e5  are both comfortable for Black. We develop quickly and enjoy the extra central e-pawn. }
7... Nc6
{ We'd like to play the knights to their natural squares f6 and c6. Both moves are possible, but we suggest starting with  7...Nc6  , as  7...Nf6  gives White the additional idea  8.Nc3  Qd6  9.Ne5  .   This wouldn't be the end of the world, but we can prevent it by going  7...Nc6  first. }
8. Nc3 Qd6
{ In such a scenario, Black always has the choice between ...Qd8 and ...Qd6. We suggest the more ambitious ...Qd6 here, as a typical drawback of ...Qd6 in other lines is no issue here: we have b5 covered, so the queen can't be attacked by Nb5. }
9. O-O
{ White gets nowhere with  9.d5  exd5  10.Nxd5  Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/1p3ppp/p1nqp3/8/3P4/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ne4  Qd8  , when ...Be7 and ...Nf6 will challenge the e4-knight quickly. }
9... Nf6
{ White has many possible moves after our standard development move. They can play  10.Bg5  ,  10.Re1  or  10.Be3  , for example. Our job is relatively simple, as we'll play ...Be7 and ...O-O in any case. Later, we need to decide if we continue with ...b5 and ...Bb7 or go for a different setup.  We'll have a look at 10.Bg5 and 10.Be3 to illustrate some possibilities. }
10. Bg5
{ White's most popular move at this point. White often combines Bg5 and Re1 and may also start with  10.Re1  Be7  11.Bg5  , which would lead to the same positions. }
10... Be7 { White has a wide range of options, again. } 11. Qd2
{ This is played most often, but many moves are regularly played here. In all cases, we can castle quickly and operate with ...Rd8,  ...b5 and often ...Nd5,  offering trades. Here are some examples.  A@@EndBracket@@  11.Bxf6  is harmless. After  11...Bxf6  12.Ne4  Qe7  White has accomplished nothing. We'll play ...O-O and ...Rd8 next.   B@@EndBracket@@  11.Rc1  O-O  12.Qd2  Nd5  or  12...Rd8  works well, too.   C@@EndBracket@@  11.Re1  O-O  12.Rc1  Rd8  , when we have good pressure on d4. }
11... O-O { Again, White has a wide choice. } 12. Rfd1
{ Other rook moves are possible, of course. We'd also answer  12.Rad1  with  12...b5  , but  12...Rd8  or  12...Nd5  would work, too. All in all, we are not under any pressure here and have some leeway. }
12... b5
{ We prepare the queenside fianchetto and gain some space. White has to play actively – if they play too passively, we might easily gain the upper hand, putting pressure on the IQP. }
13. a4 { As mentioned: active play is necessary for White. } 13... bxa4 14.
Rxa4
{ Or  14.Nxa4  Nd5  , which offers more trades and covers the b6-square. We welcome trades, as they make the weakness of the IQP more pronounced. }
14... Bb7
{ It's a good moment to stop the trainable line. We have completed our development and connected rooks, a good moment to take stock.  We assess chances as about equal. White has the IQP, a potential long-term liability. On the other hand, all white pieces are active. We are looking at a fine 'balance of imbalances', so to say.  Our general strategy is to trade more minor pieces and increase pressure on the pawn. We also need to think prophylactically and anticipate possible ideas of our opponent, in particular regarding the pawn-push d4-d5 or other tactical sequences.  Location in the Course    Chapter 4: Alapin Setups  Variation: Delayed Alapin with 3.c3 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "QS | 4B | Delayed Alapin | 2.Nf3 a6 3.c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. c3
{ This 'delayed Alapin' is recommended in many repertoire books, for example, in Christof's Keep It Simple: 1.e4 and Wesley So's Lifetime Repertoire.  As we show in this repertoire, the O'Kelly is by no means easy to play against. If you construct a repertoire for White, you need pragmatic solutions against rare lines. In the case of the O'Kelly, many lines for White are not attractive @@StartBracket@@  3.d4  @@EndBracket@@ or rather sophisticated @@StartBracket@@  3.c4  and  3.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@.  The line  3.c3  is a good solution for White, as it poses problems, but does not require that much work for White, in comparison to the mentioned alternatives. }
3... d5
{ We think this line gives Black the best chances against 3.c3.  The other satisfactory option is  3...e6  , but  4.d4  d5  5.e5  would transpose to a French Defence, which does not fit well with our repertoire concept. }
4. exd5
{ That's White's only challenging move. You sometimes meet  4.e5?!  , which is well answered with  4...Bg4  . This is best compared to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.e5?!  , when we recommend  3...Nc6  4.d4  Bf5  5.Be2  e6  6.O-O  cxd4  7.cxd4  Bg4  , leading to fine play for Black.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.e5?!  Bg4  we are likely to reach a similar scenario with the extra move ...a6,  as we managed to develop the bishop to g4 in one go. }
4... Qxd5
{ Well, you shouldn't move the queen too early in the opening – unless it's good 😝  Here, Black's play is justified, as White has already committed a pawn to c3. Therefore, the easy tempo-gain Nc3 is off the table @@StartBracket@@compare to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@  .   Here, in the Alapin, our queen is not so easily chased around but still could be vulnerable in the middle of the board. We'll look closer at White's options on move six, as  5.d4  e6  is the almost universal continuation. We'll also briefly check if White can delay the move d4,  but it does not make a substantial difference. }
5. d4
{ White's most natural and best move. How to react? Let's have a look:  A@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4  looks active, but after  6.Be2  e6  7.O-O  Nf6  8.h3  Bh5  both  9.Be3  @@StartBracket@@as already covered in Keep It Simple: 1.e4@@EndBracket@@ and  9.c4  lead to an advantage for White.   B@@EndBracket@@  5...Nf6  looks natural, but  6.Be3!  is tough to meet. We don't want to trade on d4,  as after  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  White will play Nc3 next, chasing our queen. On the other hand, White attacks the c5-pawn after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/1p2pppp/p4n2/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , which turns  6...e6  7.dxc5!  into a problem.   C@@EndBracket@@  5...Nc6  6.Be3!  is a similar story to 5...Nf6. We don't want to take on d4,  but c5 is attacked. The line @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Be3  e6  7.dxc5  shows an issue of our position: the vulnerability of the c-pawn. This leads to our idea to start with @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  when  6.Be3  can be answered with  6...Nd7!  , which lends additional support to c5. }
5... e6
{ We think this move gives Black the best prospects, as the alternatives lead to problems @@StartBracket@@see the notes to 5.d4 for more information@@EndBracket@@.  After 5...e6,  White has a wide range of options. It is crucial to study these moves and appreciate their differences, as there is no general setup or concept we could apply. We must address each White option as an independent line and learn a specific response.  Of course, there are some common themes, but it is essential not to confuse our replies. Let's have an overview of White's ideas and discuss some of the key differences.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a critical move. White intends to win a pawn with dxc5,  which we stop with  6...Nd7  , as already discussed in the notes to move  5.   B@@EndBracket@@  6.c4  attacks our queen. We retreat to d8 and get fair chances.   C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is a popular choice for White. Against this move, the most straightforward recipe is  6...cxd4!  , immediately clarifying the central structure. It is the only case of the direct trade on d4,  as we don't mind fighting the IQP after White has committed the bishop to e2.   D@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  looks a bit more active than  6.Be2  , looking towards the kingside. It's crucial NOT to take on d4 early on against this move, as the arising IQP structure is much better for White than the situation after  6.Be2  cxd4!  . The difference between these two versions is discussed in more detail in the notes to these moves.   E@@EndBracket@@  6.Na3  is aimed at exploiting the weak b6-square, jumping to c4 next. We have not yet committed the b8-knight, which proves useful after  6...Nf6  7.Nc4  Nbd7  , when we safely cover our weakness. }
6. Be3
{ This is White's most promising move. They increase the pressure on c5 and do not yet determine how the King's bishop will be developed. }
6... Nd7
{ We already mentioned this move before. The move 6...Nd7 is an important resource for Black and the reason why we suggest this system against the Alapin. What's the idea of 6...Nd7?  The main point is that White threatened to take on c5,  winning a pawn. We can't play  6...Nf6?  as  7.dxc5  just nets a pawn for White.   On the other hand, the capture on d4 is also undesirable, as  6...cxd4  8.cxd4  Nf6  9.Nc3  wins a useful tempo for White. They also still have the option to develop the king's bishop to d3 in the arising IQP position, a scenario we want to avoid. We can compare this to 6.Bd3,  when we avoid the capture as well.   Looking at the drawbacks of these alternatives,  6...Nd7  emerges as a serious option by the process of elimination. Now, c5 is safely covered and  7.dxc5?!  Qxd1+  8.Kxd1  Bxc5  regains the pawn with a good game.   The position after 6...Nd7 is still quite unexplored. In the Quickstarter, we'll check  7.Nbd2  , as it was played in most of the games that we found.  White has some alternatives, of course. Similarly to the choice on move six, they can develop the f1-bishop @@StartBracket@@  7.Be2  cxd4  is one line@@EndBracket@@ or play the c-pawn @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/1p1n1ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.c4  Qc6  @@EndBracket@@ to attack our queen. We take a more detailed look at these options in the dedicated chapter, of course. }
7. Nbd2
{ This is White's most popular reply to our fresh idea 6...Nd7. White develops the knight and might continue with either Nc4 or Bc4 next. In any case, our reply is natural – develop the kingside. }
7... Ngf6 { Alright, that was easy. We need to get our kingside developed. } 8.
Bc4
{ This is White's usual continuation, but it is not challenging for Black.  They could also play  8.c4  when  8...Qc6  9.Be2  b6  is undoubtedly fine for Black. White's knight is poorly placed in this structure, looking at the own c4-pawn. The pawn push c4 should be combined with Nc3,  as in multiple lines of the current chapter.   The move  8.Nc4  is unpopular, as it runs into  8...b5!  with tempo. We usually suggest playing the more restrained ...b6,  but here gaining a tempo is very attractive. }
8... Qc6
{ We have a setup with ...b6 and ...Bb7 in mind, setting up a battery on the long diagonal.  The move  8...Qd6  is not a mistake but less attractive in comparison. }
9. O-O b6
{ The move  9...b5  is also playable but somewhat risky. The sequence  10.Be2  Bb7  11.a4  c4  12.b3  shows a typical problem of the early queenside expansion. }
10. Re1
{ Here,  10.Ne5?!  Nxe5  11.dxe5  Bb7!  already looks slightly better for us. }
10... Bb7
{ It's a good moment to take stock already. White has developed their pieces quickly, but they don't put any pressure on us. We are ready to prepare kingside castling while White has no clear way forward.  A critical struggle will be about the central tension. Both sides need to consider if they want to capture on c5/d4. We must be cautious about the capture, as we are currently behind in development. We should first castle and connect rooks before considering any opening of the position.  Location in the Course    Chapter 4: Alapin Setups  Variation 4B: Delayed Alapin with 3.c3 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "QS | 1C | Open Mainline | 2.Nf3 a6 3.d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. d4
{ White goes for the so-called 'Open Sicilian', a very popular approach. Many players employ 2.Nf3 and continue with 3.d4 against more or less all moves that Black may play on the second turn. They will play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.d4  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.d4  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.d4  etc.  In all these popular continuations, the 'Open Variation' is considered a critical test, or even the only test of Black's opening. But what about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  , our move? As we'll see in the current chapter,  3.d4  is not dangerous at all! Black even reached a positive score in practice! This is a key attraction of the O'Kelly, as a natural continuation like 3.d4 is harmless.  We need to stress that Black does not reach a forced advantage after  3.d4  , but should equalize comfortably. The excellent score for Black @@StartBracket@@a substantial plus@@EndBracket@@ is a typical phenomenon that you can often observe in second-rate theoretical variations. Players who are unaware that  3.d4  is a second-rate move will often continue making wrong moves, which leads to further problems.  Let's briefly consider why we welcome the Open Variation of the O'Kelly. After 3.d4 we continue with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  when the centralized knight is pushed away from its post. After the most popular moves,  6.Nb3  or  6.Nf3  , we have the attractive move  6...Bb4  , pinning the knight and putting pressure on White's e-pawn.  As mentioned before, White has equal chances in these lines. In practice, however, White is often struggling with these positions. They will usually be unfamiliar to our opponents – if they know that 3.d4 is unpromising, there is little incentive to enter the line. Let's have a closer look at these essential variations now. }
3... cxd4
{ Trading our c-pawn for White's d-pawn is a small strategic gain, as we remain with two centre pawns against one – a vital concept of the Sicilian Defence.  White also has  4.c3  , when  4...dxc3  5.Nxc3  e6  leads to the Smith-Morra Gambit. We cover this line in the Quickstarter, using the more common move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.d4  . }
4. Nxd4 { The natural move and White's almost only choice at this point. } 4...
Nf6
{ We attack the unprotected e-pawn and hope for  5.e5?  Qa5+!  , a pawn blunder that still happens from time to time.   White needs to protect the e-pawn and usually accomplishes the task with  5.Nc3  .  The moves  5.Bd3  or  5.f3  are far less popular and answered with 5...e5,  too. }
5. Nc3 { White's most natural and popular move. } 5... e5
{ An excellent move! We attack White's knight and force a retreat. White can't go forward, as we have covered the b5-square and  6.Nf5?  d5!  is great for Black.  The early move ...e5 is a common theme in the Sicilian Defence. It's worth comparing our version with other popular ...e5-lines and see why ours is particularly attractive for Black:  A@@EndBracket@@ The Sveshnikov @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  allows  6.Ndb5  , when Black is forced to play  6...d6  , keeping the f8-bishop passive. The alternatives  6.Nb3?!  Bb4!  or  6.Nf3?!  Bb4!  are fine for Black.  B@@EndBracket@@ The Kalashnikov @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  is the same story after  5.Nb5  d6  .  C@@EndBracket@@ The Najdorf @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  a6  6.Be2  e5  is a different story. White can't go to b5 here, but Black is already committed to ...d6 anyway.  In the O'Kelly, we get the benefits of the lines above in one package. White has to retreat the knight, like in the Najdorf, but we can still develop our bishop actively to b4!  We now examine the most popular and important replies @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq e6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nb3  and  6.Nf3  . }
6. Nf3
{ A common and logical move. White returns to f3 and attacks our e5-pawn. It's important to not react passively to this move but continue with active play. }
6... Bb4
{ We don't defend the e5-pawn but rather develop quickly and pin our opponent's knight. This way, we also increase the pressure on the e4-pawn.  It's important to note that we are not threatening to take e4 right away, as the sample line  7.a3?!  Bxc3+  8.bxc3  Nxe4?  9.Qd5!  shows. Instead, it is much better to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/4P3/P1P2N2/2P2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qa5!  , which covers the e5-pawn and attacks c3. Black is much better in this scenario because  9.Qd3  Nxe4!  is a crucial tactic.   After 6...Bb4 White has tried many moves. In the Quickstarter, we'll have a closer look at the very common mistake  7.Bd3?  , which you'll meet regularly – it looks like a natural move but runs into problems, as we'll see.  White can try some other moves. Taking on e5 is risky and welcome, as after  7.Nxe5  O-O  8.Bd3  d5  we get a strong attack.   A better move is  7.Bc4  , when we need to avoid the bunder  7.Bc4  Nxe4??  8.Qd5  – a deadly double attack. Much better is @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/1bB1P3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...d6  , with the intention to later capture the knight and weaken White's structure. }
7. Bd3
{ A very natural move and extremely popular in Blitz. Black is in excellent shape, though! }
7... d5
{ Strike! Now White has to be very careful to avoid immediate disaster. } 8.
Bg5
{ This keeps White in the game, but often White fails to manage that – in particular in faster time controls. Here are some ways to the abyss...  A@@EndBracket@@  8.exd5??  e4  9.Qe2  Bxc3+  10.bxc3  O-O  11.Bxe4  Nxe4  12.Qxe4  Re8  13.Ne5  and now Black wins with many moves, like  13...f6  ,  13...Qc7  or  13...Nd7  .   B@@EndBracket@@  8.Nxe5??  loses to  8...d4  9.a3  Ba5  10.b4  Bc7  or  8...Qe7   C@@EndBracket@@  8.O-O??  or  8.Bd2??  lose to  8...Bxc3  , followed by ...dxe4. }
8... d4 9. a3
{ White manages to break the pin with a2-a3 and b2-b4 but is still worse. }
9... Ba5 10. b4 dxc3 11. bxa5 Nc6
{ Or  11...h6  , which is equally good. We have some advantage, as White can't save the a5-pawn.  7.Bd3? is a move that we are happy to face, as White has to be careful to limit the damage to their position.  Location in the Course    Chapter 1: Open Mainline  Variation 1C: Open Mainline with 5.Nc3 }
*

