{ An excellent move! We attack White's knight and force a retreat. White can't go forward, as we have covered the b5-square and  6.Nf5?  d5!  is great for Black.  The early move ...e5 is a common theme in the Sicilian Defence. It's worth comparing our version with other popular ...e5-lines and see why ours is particularly attractive for Black:  A@@EndBracket@@ The Sveshnikov @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  allows  6.Ndb5  , when Black is forced to play  6...d6  , keeping the f8-bishop passive. The alternatives  6.Nb3?!  Bb4!  or  6.Nf3?!  Bb4!  are fine for Black.  B@@EndBracket@@ The Kalashnikov @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  is the same story after  5.Nb5  d6  .  C@@EndBracket@@ The Najdorf @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  a6  6.Be2  e5  is a different story. White can't go to b5 here, but Black is already committed to ...d6 anyway.  In the O'Kelly, we get the benefits of the lines above in one package. White has to retreat the knight, like in the Najdorf, but we can still develop our bishop actively to b4!  We now examine the most popular and important replies @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq e6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nb3  and  6.Nf3  . }
6. Nb3 { A very likely move to face. } 6... Bb4
{ Pin and win! We develop our bishop and prepare kingside castling, but the move has a range of ideas. Here are some concepts to keep in mind.  Black's Options  1@@EndBracket@@ By pinning and usually capturing the c3-knight, we fight to control the d5-square. It is improbable that White establishes dominance over d5,  which often happens in other comparable Sicilian structures.  2@@EndBracket@@ We can often take on c3 and create a doubled pawn. White's pawn structure is severely weakened in such a scenario, but this also applies to our dark squares. We must carefully consider when to create the doubled pawn and when to avoid it. The key consideration is whether White can play Ba3 and quickly point toward our weak spot, d6. Two sample lines help to understand this issue.  After  7.f3  Bxc3+?  is wrong, as  8.bxc3  d6  9.Ba3  is terrible for Black. There is no good way to cover d6.   However, after  7.Bg5  , we happily play  7...Bxc3+  , as clearly Ba3 is off the table.  3@@EndBracket@@ We often have a choice between playing for the move ...d5 or going for a setup based on ...d6. In many cases, the choice between them is a matter of taste.  We generally advocate ...d6-based play, as it keeps more pieces on the board and usually leads to more combative play. Placing our pawns on dark squares is strategically very sound, as we almost always give up our dark-squared bishop, and the remaining light-squared one works well in this structure.   White's Options  Let's get an overview of White's options – our answer depends on them. Against some, taking on c3 is best. Against others, we need to avoid it:  1@@EndBracket@@ Against  7.Bd2  and  7.f3  we avoid the immediate capture, but rather develop with ...O-O and ...d6.  2@@EndBracket@@ If White plays  7.Bc4  ,  7.Bd3  or  7.Bg5  , the capture on c3 works well, and we recommend grabbing this opportunity to unbalance the game.   In the Quickstarter, we'll now have a look at  7.f3  and  7.Bd3  – they are the most popular moves and an example for both scenarios. }
7. f3
{ White is worried about the e-pawn and covers it reliably. This is not a bad line for White, but it is often misplayed in practice. The most important moment for Black comes right away. To take on c3 or not to take? }
7... O-O
{ We must remember that against 7.f3,  the capture is a huge mistake, as  7...Bxc3+?  8.bxc3  d6  9.Ba3  demonstrates. We have no good way to cover our weakness on d6.  Compared to 7.Bd3 it is helpful for White that the queen on d1 is not obstructed by a bishop on d3. This is the key difference from @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/1b2P3/1NN5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  , when we advise to play  7...Bxc3+!   Before we continue, a word about @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/1b2P3/1NN5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.f3  d6  – a fine alternative. The main reason to go for  7...O-O  is that White sometimes, usually in faster time controls, plays  8.Be3?  when  8...d5!  is excellent for Black. }
8. Bd2
{ This looks best and leads to similar play as 7.Bd2.  The alternatives are not great for White. We already talked about  8.Be3?  d5!  , which is nice for Black.   After  8.Bg5  h6  9.Bh4  , we can safely capture the knight:  9...Bxc3+  10.bxc3  d6  looks good, with ...Be6 and ...Nbd7 in mind. }
8... d6
{ As usual, we prefer a setup based on ...d6, unless there is a concrete, tactical reason to go for ...d5. The arising positions are very similar to 7.Bd2, but White has committed to the early f3, limiting our opponent's options. }
9. a3
{ After  9.Bd3  Nc6  , there is nothing concrete to know: we transpose to a good version of the 7.Bd2 line. }
9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Qc7
{ A small finesse. White might have a quick Qd2 and O-O-O in mind. 10...Qc7 is directed against this idea. }
11. Qd2
{ White can still play  11.Bd3  and O-O,  of course. This would be about equal, but let's check why the ambitious plan does not work well. }
11... Be6 12. O-O-O d5
{ It's instructive to see how ...Qc7 and ...Be6 work well together. The queen covers e5 and c5,  while the bishop move supports the central strike.  Black is already better, as  13.exd5  Nxd5  14.Bd3  Nd7  , followed by ...Rfc8,  demonstrates.  Location in the Course    Chapter 1: Open Mainline  Variation 1C: Open Mainline with 5.Nc3 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "QS | 1C | Open Mainline | 2.Nf3 a6 3.d4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. d4
{ White goes for the so-called 'Open Sicilian', a very popular approach. Many players employ 2.Nf3 and continue with 3.d4 against more or less all moves that Black may play on the second turn. They will play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.d4  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.d4  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.d4  etc.  In all these popular continuations, the 'Open Variation' is considered a critical test, or even the only test of Black's opening. But what about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  , our move? As we'll see in the current chapter,  3.d4  is not dangerous at all! Black even reached a positive score in practice! This is a key attraction of the O'Kelly, as a natural continuation like 3.d4 is harmless.  We need to stress that Black does not reach a forced advantage after  3.d4  , but should equalize comfortably. The excellent score for Black @@StartBracket@@a substantial plus@@EndBracket@@ is a typical phenomenon that you can often observe in second-rate theoretical variations. Players who are unaware that  3.d4  is a second-rate move will often continue making wrong moves, which leads to further problems.  Let's briefly consider why we welcome the Open Variation of the O'Kelly. After 3.d4 we continue with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  when the centralized knight is pushed away from its post. After the most popular moves,  6.Nb3  or  6.Nf3  , we have the attractive move  6...Bb4  , pinning the knight and putting pressure on White's e-pawn.  As mentioned before, White has equal chances in these lines. In practice, however, White is often struggling with these positions. They will usually be unfamiliar to our opponents – if they know that 3.d4 is unpromising, there is little incentive to enter the line. Let's have a closer look at these essential variations now. }
3... cxd4
{ Trading our c-pawn for White's d-pawn is a small strategic gain, as we remain with two centre pawns against one – a vital concept of the Sicilian Defence.  White also has  4.c3  , when  4...dxc3  5.Nxc3  e6  leads to the Smith-Morra Gambit. We cover this line in the Quickstarter, using the more common move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.d4  . }
4. Nxd4 { The natural move and White's almost only choice at this point. } 4...
Nf6
{ We attack the unprotected e-pawn and hope for  5.e5?  Qa5+!  , a pawn blunder that still happens from time to time.   White needs to protect the e-pawn and usually accomplishes the task with  5.Nc3  .  The moves  5.Bd3  or  5.f3  are far less popular and answered with 5...e5,  too. }
5. Nc3 { White's most natural and popular move. } 5... e5
{ An excellent move! We attack White's knight and force a retreat. White can't go forward, as we have covered the b5-square and  6.Nf5?  d5!  is great for Black.  The early move ...e5 is a common theme in the Sicilian Defence. It's worth comparing our version with other popular ...e5-lines and see why ours is particularly attractive for Black:  A@@EndBracket@@ The Sveshnikov @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  allows  6.Ndb5  , when Black is forced to play  6...d6  , keeping the f8-bishop passive. The alternatives  6.Nb3?!  Bb4!  or  6.Nf3?!  Bb4!  are fine for Black.  B@@EndBracket@@ The Kalashnikov @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  is the same story after  5.Nb5  d6  .  C@@EndBracket@@ The Najdorf @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  a6  6.Be2  e5  is a different story. White can't go to b5 here, but Black is already committed to ...d6 anyway.  In the O'Kelly, we get the benefits of the lines above in one package. White has to retreat the knight, like in the Najdorf, but we can still develop our bishop actively to b4!  We now examine the most popular and important replies @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq e6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nb3  and  6.Nf3  . }
6. Nb3 { A very likely move to face. } 6... Bb4
{ Pin and win! We develop our bishop and prepare kingside castling, but the move has a range of ideas. Here are some concepts to keep in mind.  Black's Options  1@@EndBracket@@ By pinning and usually capturing the c3-knight, we fight to control the d5-square. It is improbable that White establishes dominance over d5,  which often happens in other comparable Sicilian structures.  2@@EndBracket@@ We can often take on c3 and create a doubled pawn. White's pawn structure is severely weakened in such a scenario, but this also applies to our dark squares. We must carefully consider when to create the doubled pawn and when to avoid it. The key consideration is whether White can play Ba3 and quickly point toward our weak spot, d6. Two sample lines help to understand this issue.  After  7.f3  Bxc3+?  is wrong, as  8.bxc3  d6  9.Ba3  is terrible for Black. There is no good way to cover d6.   However, after  7.Bg5  , we happily play  7...Bxc3+  , as clearly Ba3 is off the table.  3@@EndBracket@@ We often have a choice between playing for the move ...d5 or going for a setup based on ...d6. In many cases, the choice between them is a matter of taste.  We generally advocate ...d6-based play, as it keeps more pieces on the board and usually leads to more combative play. Placing our pawns on dark squares is strategically very sound, as we almost always give up our dark-squared bishop, and the remaining light-squared one works well in this structure.   White's Options  Let's get an overview of White's options – our answer depends on them. Against some, taking on c3 is best. Against others, we need to avoid it:  1@@EndBracket@@ Against  7.Bd2  and  7.f3  we avoid the immediate capture, but rather develop with ...O-O and ...d6.  2@@EndBracket@@ If White plays  7.Bc4  ,  7.Bd3  or  7.Bg5  , the capture on c3 works well, and we recommend grabbing this opportunity to unbalance the game.   In the Quickstarter, we'll now have a look at  7.f3  and  7.Bd3  – they are the most popular moves and an example for both scenarios. }
7. Bd3
{ White's most popular move by far. They develop the bishop, cover e4 and prepare kingside castling. }
7... Bxc3+
{ Yet another case where we advise taking on c3 immediately. It is not the only good move, but certainly the most combative. To fight, you should create imbalances. }
8. bxc3 O-O
{ We suggest starting with kingside castling, but  8...d6  first is also fine. It will lead to the same positions. }
9. O-O
{ Very natural play by White.  It's important to note that White gets nowhere by playing  9.Ba3  when  9...d6  works well. White's d3-bishop obstructs the queen's scope on the d-file, a key difference from @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/1b2P3/1NN5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.f3  Bxc3+?  8.bxc3  O-O  9.Ba3  , when Black has no good reply. }
9... d6
{ Our standard formation after the trade on c3. Placing the pawns on dark squares is strategically well-founded. The pawns harmonize well with our remaining bishop.  Next, we'd like to play ...Be6, ...Nbd7 and start an attack along the c-file. White has two weak c-pawns, after all. }
10. Bg5
{ An active choice, as is  10.f4  . The move f4 weakens the e-pawn, which makes the response  10...Re8  11.f5  b5!  instructive. Placing the bishop on b7 increases pressure on the weak pawn. }
10... h6 { Gaining a valuable tempo. } 11. Bh4 Be6
{ We are still aiming for the harmonious ...Be6/Nbd7 formation. White should play a modest move, like  12.c4  , for example. Black's game is comfortable and easy to conduct, but White is not seriously worse yet.  We'll check a more aggressive option now: the pawn push  12.f4  . }
12. f4
{ We found many online games that featured this wrong move. Let's check why it is bad. }
12... exf4 13. Bxf6 { White can't play  13.Rxf4  g5  , when we win material. }
13... Qxf6 14. Qd2
{ White threatens to regain the f-pawn. This is still a critical moment to study. It is crucial NOT to play the risky  14...g5?!  , but play a solid move like  14...Rc8  or  14...Nd7  . }
14... Rc8 { We attack the c-pawn first. } 15. Nd4
{ White covers the c-pawn this way. We return the f-pawn and have a great position afterwards. }
15... Nd7 16. Rxf4 Qg5
{ A good moment to stop this line. Black is in excellent shape in this position. White has multiple pawn weaknesses, and we enjoy fine outposts on e5 and c5.  Location in the Course    Chapter 1: Open Mainline  Variation 1C: Open Mainline with 5.Nc3 }
