[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Open Mainline 2.Nf3 a6 3.d4"]
[Black "1A | Open Mainline | White plays 4.Qxd4 instead of 4.Nxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ Hang on, White loses time if we attack the queen, right? This is true, but White's move is not as stupid as it seems at first glance. There are similar lines that have a good reputation:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Qxd4   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nc3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Qxd4   As you see, in both lines, Black has already played the move ...d6. In our version, this is not the case. This difference works in our favour. We may play ...d7-d5 in one move or still get to develop the f8-bishop @@StartBracket@@...e6 or ...e5,  followed by ...Bb4 or ...Bc5@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Nc6 { We gain a tempo by attacking the queen, an easy move. } 5. Qe3
{ This looks like the most active choice. Going back to d1 can't be dangerous, but we should have a look at a little trick to be aware of: After  5.Qd1  Nf6  6.e5?  we have  6...Nxe5!  7.Nxe5  Qa5+  , winning the central pawn!  Of course, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1ppppp/p1n2n2/8/4P3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nc3  is a better choice to avoid this pawn loss. Black is in good shape after  6...e6  @@StartBracket@@idea ...Bb4@@EndBracket@@, though. It's a typical Sicilian position in which White has lost time with queen moves for no reason. }
5... Nf6
{ A good move that prepares ...d7-d5. We also set a trap, as now  6.e5?  Ng4  7.Qe4  Ngxe5!  8.Nxe5  Qa5+  wins a pawn for Black. }
6. c4 { White opts for the Maroczy Bind, stopping our ...d5-idea. } 6... e5
{ A strong move. Our plan involves ...Bb4, followed by ...d6 and finally ...Bc5, attacking the queen. Let's look at a possible line to illustrate the idea. }
7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Bd2
{ White is breaking the pin.  White may also play  8.Be2  , but  8...d6  9.O-O  O-O  is fine for Black, too. Our bishop may take on c3 at a good moment or play ...Bc5 to gain a useful tempo. }
8... Ng4 9. Qe2 { Here  9.Qd3?  Qb6  is even worse for White. } 9... Bc5
{ An annoying attack on f2. Black is in good shape now, as  10.Bg5  f6  11.Bh4  d6  demonstrates. White's position makes an unharmonious impression, while we enjoy active pieces and control of d4. }
