[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Open Mainline 2.Nf3 a6 3.d4"]
[Black "1B | Open Mainline with 5.Bd3 | White plays 6.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ The natural move and White's almost only choice at this point. } 4... Nf6
{ We attack the unprotected e-pawn and hope for  5.e5?  Qa5+!  , a pawn blunder that still happens from time to time.   White needs to protect the e-pawn and usually accomplishes the task with  5.Nc3  . We'll also briefly check  5.Bd3  , while  5.f3?!  already gives Black the better chances after the natural reply  5...e5  6.Nb3  d5  , when the move f3 only served as a weakening of White's camp. }
5. Bd3
{ A rare move, but not bad at all. A key difference to  5.Nc3  is that after  5.Bd3  e5  6.Nb3  , we can't play ...Bb4 to pin the knight. }
5... e5
{ We recommend this move, attacking White's knight. This way, we follow the same pattern as after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1ppppp/p4n2/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  e5  , which makes it easier to remember.   Black has a good but less exciting alternative in  5...Nc6  , when  6.Nxc6  dxc6  7.O-O  e5  leads to equal chances. The symmetrical nature of the position makes it more difficult to stir up a fight, though.   After our choice,  5...e5  , we'll consider  6.Nb3  and  6.Nf3  . The knight jump to f5 is bad, as  6.Nf5?!  d5  7.exd5??  e4!  demonstrates drastically. }
6. Nf3
{ White retreats the knight and sets a trap we need to avoid. Let's have a look. }
6... Nc6
{ Sound development.  What about the trap we mentioned? The move to avoid is  6...d5?!  , which looks tempting, as  7.exd5  e4  leads to an attractive-looking fork. The problem is  8.Qe2  when  8...Qe7  9.d6!  Qe6  10.Bc4  Qxd6  11.Ng5  is great for White. }
7. O-O Bc5
{ We'd play in the same way after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/4P3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.c4  Bc5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/4P3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nc3  Bc5  . In all cases, we'll continue with ...d6 and ...O-O and enjoy an active position. }
