[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Open Mainline 2.Nf3 a6 3.d4"]
[Black "1B | Open Mainline with 5.Bd3 | White plays 6.Nb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ The natural move and White's almost only choice at this point. } 4... Nf6
{ We attack the unprotected e-pawn and hope for  5.e5?  Qa5+!  , a pawn blunder that still happens from time to time.   White needs to protect the e-pawn and usually accomplishes the task with  5.Nc3  . We'll also briefly check  5.Bd3  , while  5.f3?!  already gives Black the better chances after the natural reply  5...e5  6.Nb3  d5  , when the move f3 only served as a weakening of White's camp. }
5. Bd3
{ A rare move, but not bad at all. A key difference to  5.Nc3  is that after  5.Bd3  e5  6.Nb3  , we can't play ...Bb4 to pin the knight. }
5... e5
{ We recommend this move, attacking White's knight. This way, we follow the same pattern as after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1ppppp/p4n2/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  e5  , which makes it easier to remember.   Black has a good but less exciting alternative in  5...Nc6  , when  6.Nxc6  dxc6  7.O-O  e5  leads to equal chances. The symmetrical nature of the position makes it more difficult to stir up a fight, though.   After our choice,  5...e5  , we'll consider  6.Nb3  and  6.Nf3  . The knight jump to f5 is bad, as  6.Nf5?!  d5  7.exd5??  e4!  demonstrates drastically. }
6. Nb3
{ Seems to be best. White hinders us from moving our dark-squared bishop to c5. }
6... d5
{ In comparison to 6.Nf3 we can push 6...d5 now under better conditions. } 7.
exd5 Nxd5
{ From a strategic point of view, our position is excellent. We have an extra centre pawn and a well-placed knight. However, our development is lacking a bit. Therefore we need to exert some caution. }
8. O-O
{ Played almost exclusively. But we get a decent position now.  An interesting alternative is  8.Be4  , but it is a rare choice in practice. After  8...Be6  9.O-O  f5  10.Bg5  Qd7  Black's position looks fine. }
8... Nb4
{ Much better than the normal-looking moves  8...Be7  or  8...Nc6  .  With  8...Nb4  we immediately challenge the light-squared bishop, White's strongest piece. They have no dangerous way to avoid the trade, which is a substantial achievement for us. }
9. Be4 { Against other moves, we'll happily take the bishop. } 9... Qxd1 10.
Rxd1 f5
{ Going for forcing play. We attack the bishop immediately, which has to cover c2. }
11. a3
{ White has to go for a counter-attack, as the bishop has no good square. }
11... fxe4 12. axb4 Bxb4
{ Black is in good shape here. We currently enjoy an extra pawn, but the doubled e-pawns are not counting as two full pawns. Chances are about equal. }
