[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Open Mainline 2.Nf3 a6 3.d4"]
[Black "1C | Open Mainline with 5.Nc3 | White plays 6.Nf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ The natural move and White's almost only choice at this point. } 4... Nf6
{ We attack the unprotected e-pawn and hope for  5.e5?  Qa5+!  , a pawn blunder that still happens from time to time.   White needs to protect the e-pawn and usually accomplishes the task with  5.Nc3  . We'll also briefly check  5.Bd3  , while  5.f3?!  already gives Black the better chances after the natural reply  5...e5  6.Nb3  d5  , when the move f3 only served as a weakening of White's camp. }
5. Nc3 { White's most natural and popular move. } 5... e5
{ An excellent move! We attack White's knight and force a retreat. White can't go forward, as we have covered the b5-square and  6.Nf5?  d5!  is great for Black, as we will see.  The early move ...e5 is a common theme in the Sicilian Defence. It's worth comparing our version with other popular ...e5-lines and see why ours is particularly attractive for Black:  A@@EndBracket@@ The Sveshnikov @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  allows  6.Ndb5  , when Black is forced to play  6...d6  , keeping the f8-bishop passive. The alternatives  6.Nb3?!  Bb4!  or  6.Nf3?!  Bb4!  are fine for Black.  B@@EndBracket@@ The Kalashnikov @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  is the same story after  5.Nb5  d6  .  C@@EndBracket@@ The Najdorf @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  a6  6.Be2  e5  is a different story. White can't go to b5 here, but Black is already committed to ...d6 anyway.  In the O'Kelly, we get the benefits of the lines above in one package. White has to retreat the knight, like in the Najdorf, but we can still develop our bishop actively to b4!  Let's have a look at the various knight moves now. Most important and popular is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq e6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nb3  , followed by  6.Nf3  . White rarely plays  6.Nde2  , but we'll check this briefly, too.  The move  6.Nf5?  is bad due to  6...d5!  , which is an important point to know. }
6. Nf5 { Jumping forward, but this move is a serious mistake. } 6... d5
{ That's the refutation. White's knight needs protection from the e-pawn, which allows the powerful central pawn to push. }
7. Bg5
{ This looks relatively best. White can't take on d5 and needs to do something about the threat ...d4,  too.  A line like  7.Ng3?  d4  8.Nb1  h5  is excellent for Black, of course. }
7... d4 8. Bxf6 { Here  8.Nd5??  Bxf5  wins on the spot for Black. } 8... gxf6
{ Taking with the queen is also possible and better for Black.  We still suggest the pawn capture, as now White can't jump to d5 and has to retreat the knight, compared to  8...Qxf6  9.Nd5  . }
9. Nb1 { Or  9.Ne2  Qb6  , with a similarly unattractive position for White. }
9... Be6 10. Bd3 Qb6
{ Black is in great shape. We have more space and the bishop pair and will be able to castle queenside quickly. Therefore the somewhat weakened kingside does not endanger our king's safety. }
