8. Bd3
{ White's most popular and logical move. It leads to a substantial advantage for Black, though. }
8... d5 { Let's open the position as quickly as possible. } 9. O-O
{ White needs to get the king out of the centre, pronto!  After  9.exd5?  Re8  10.f4  Bc5  , we have excellent chances to win the game quickly. Black has a strong attack and a much easier game. }
9... Qc7
{ A powerful and unexpected move! We attack White's e5-knight... and it turns out that White has no fully satisfactory reply. Let's have a look. }
10. Bf4
{ This is the most interesting move to check. What else for White? The knight can't move back to f3.  A@@EndBracket@@  10.Nf3??  Bxc3  11.bxc3  dxe4  wins a piece!   B@@EndBracket@@  10.f4  Bxc3  11.bxc3  dxe4  looks good for Black, as we have a much better pawn structure. White may go for tactics with  12.Bc4  Nc6  13.Ba3  Rd8  14.Bxf7+  Qxf7  15.Nxf7  Rxd1  16.Nh6+  gxh6  17.Raxd1  Kf7  , which leads to a better endgame for Black. Our minor pieces have plenty of pawn weaknesses to attack. }
10... Bd6
{ At first, it looks like White is losing the knight for not much, but there are some cool tactics ahead. }
11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Bxe5 13. Bxh7+
{ That's the reason why we need to check this line at all. } 13... Kh8
{ This cool move is stronger than  13...Kxh7  , after which  14.Qh5+  Kg8  15.Bxe5  Qxc2  16.Bd6  Rd8  17.Rfe1  is not easy to play for Black. The comp still likes Black, but our solution is simpler – given that you know the point on move 15! }
14. d6 Qc5 15. Qh5
{ This move looks very scary for Black, but we have a great reply! } 15... Bg4
{ The only move to be better, and the only move to not lose! } 16. Qxg4 Bxf4
{ We have managed to keep the extra piece and are much better. } *

