{ A common and logical move. White returns to f3 and attacks our e5-pawn. It's important to not react passively to this move but continue with active play. }
6... Bb4
{ We don't defend the e5-pawn but rather develop quickly and pin our opponent's knight. This way, we also increase the pressure on the e4-pawn.  It's important to note that we are not threatening to take e4 right away, as the sample line  7.a3?!  Bxc3+  8.bxc3  Nxe4?  9.Qd5!  shows. Instead, it is much better to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/4P3/P1P2N2/2P2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qa5!  , which covers the e5-pawn and attacks c3. Black is much better in this scenario because  9.Qd3  Nxe4!  is a crucial tactic.  Now we need to check various possibilities for White. }
7. Bc4
{ White's most interesting continuation in our view. We can't win the e4-pawn due to  7...Nxe4??  8.Qd5  with a double attack on e4 and f7.  How to continue? White has some control of the d5-square, so playing for a quick ...d7-d5 is difficult. The best option is aiming for a setup based on ...d6,  leading to a pawn structure frequently seen in many Sicilians, like the Najdorf or Sveshnikov.  In our case, the bishop is well-placed on b4. We'll take on c3 most of the time, which will lessen White's control of d5 considerably. We need to be careful about the timing, though. After creating the doubled c-pawns, White might have the powerful option to play Ba3 in some cases. }
7... d6
{ Black has a good choice between  7...Qc7  and  7...d6  here. We prefer the latter, as it leaves White a greater chance to go wrong. }
8. O-O { Castling kingside is White's most popular choice. } 8... Bxc3
{ We suggest the immediate capture, which makes sure that White gets doubled pawns.  The move  8...Qc7  is not bad, either, but there are some tricky lines. After  9.Qd3  Bxc3  10.Qxc3!  we can't take on e4,  as  10...Nxe4??  11.Bxf7+!  is winning for White. Black has to avoid the pawn grab in this line, but White has managed to keep their pawn structure tidy, at least. }
9. bxc3 Qc7
{ It's crucial to play this move immediately. We gain a tempo on the bishop and are ready to play ...Nd7-c5, which increases the pressure on e4 and defuses Ba3 ideas. Now White has to be careful not to get into a worse position quickly. }
10. Qd3
{ The best move, but White needs to be extremely precise to prove why. } 10...
Nbd7 { The move ...Qc7 also prepared ...Nbd7, so here we go. } 11. Rd1
{ This turns out to be OK for White, due to some concrete tactics. Let's have a look. }
11... Nc5 { We trade the d-pawn for the e-pawn. } 12. Qxd6 Qxd6 13. Rxd6 Nfxe4
14. Rd1 f6
{ We reliably cover the e-pawn. At first glance, Black's position looks to be much better. Stockfish, however, points out a way to equal chances that is unlikely ever to be played by a human. Let's have a look:   15.Re1!  Bd7  16.Nxe5!  fxe5  17.f3  and White regains the piece after  17...Bb5  18.Bxb5+  axb5  19.fxe4  Kd7  . This position is equal, as all White's pawns are weak.  This whole sequence is very computerish but good to know. Lines like these are good examples of why Black scores so well in the Open O'Kelly. White is often forced to play very precisely to hold the balance – Black's job is easier to handle in practice. }
*

