[White "1) Open Mainline 2.Nf3 a6 3.d4"]
[Black "1C | Open Mainline with 5.Nc3 | White plays 6.Nb3 / 7.Bd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ The natural move and White's almost only choice at this point. } 4... Nf6
{ We attack the unprotected e-pawn and hope for  5.e5?  Qa5+!  , a pawn blunder that still happens from time to time.   White needs to protect the e-pawn and usually accomplishes the task with  5.Nc3  . We'll also briefly check  5.Bd3  , while  5.f3?!  already gives Black the better chances after the natural reply  5...e5  6.Nb3  d5  , when the move f3 only served as a weakening of White's camp. }
5. Nc3 { White's most natural and popular move. } 5... e5
{ An excellent move! We attack White's knight and force a retreat. White can't go forward, as we have covered the b5-square and  6.Nf5?  d5!  is great for Black, as we will see.  The early move ...e5 is a common theme in the Sicilian Defence. It's worth comparing our version with other popular ...e5-lines and see why ours is particularly attractive for Black:  A@@EndBracket@@ The Sveshnikov @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  allows  6.Ndb5  , when Black is forced to play  6...d6  , keeping the f8-bishop passive. The alternatives  6.Nb3?!  Bb4!  or  6.Nf3?!  Bb4!  are fine for Black.  B@@EndBracket@@ The Kalashnikov @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  is the same story after  5.Nb5  d6  .  C@@EndBracket@@ The Najdorf @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  a6  6.Be2  e5  is a different story. White can't go to b5 here, but Black is already committed to ...d6 anyway.  In the O'Kelly, we get the benefits of the lines above in one package. White has to retreat the knight, like in the Najdorf, but we can still develop our bishop actively to b4!  Let's have a look at the various knight moves now. Most important and popular is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq e6 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nb3  , followed by  6.Nf3  . White rarely plays  6.Nde2  , but we'll check this briefly, too.  The move  6.Nf5?  is bad due to  6...d5!  , which is an important point to know. }
6. Nb3 { A very likely move to face. } 6... Bb4
{ Pin and win! We develop our bishop and prepare kingside castling, but the move has a range of ideas. Here are some concepts to keep in mind.  Black's Options  1@@EndBracket@@ By pinning and usually capturing the c3-knight, we fight to control the d5-square. It is improbable that White establishes dominance over d5,  which often happens in other comparable Sicilian structures.  2@@EndBracket@@ We can often take on c3 and create a doubled pawns. White's pawn structure is severely weakened in such a scenario, but this also applies to our dark squares. We must carefully consider when to create the doubled pawn and when to avoid it. The key consideration is whether White can play Ba3 and quickly point toward our weak spot, d6. Two sample lines help to understand this issue.  After  7.f3  Bxc3+?  is wrong, as  8.bxc3  d6  9.Ba3  is terrible for Black. There is no good way to cover d6.   However, after  7.Bg5  , we happily play  7...Bxc3+  , as clearly Ba3 is off the table.  3@@EndBracket@@ We often have a choice between playing for the move ...d5 or going for a setup based on ...d6. In many cases, the choice between them is a matter of taste.  We generally advocate ...d6-based play, as it keeps more pieces on the board and usually leads to more combative play. Placing our pawns on dark squares is strategically very sound, as we almost always give up our dark-squared bishop, and the remaining light-squared one works well in this structure.   White's Options  Let's get an overview over White's options – our answer depends on them. Against some, taking on c3 is best. Against others, we need to avoid it:  A@@EndBracket@@ Against  7.Bd2  and  7.f3  we avoid the immediate capture, but rather develop with ...O-O and ...d6.  B@@EndBracket@@ If White plays  7.Bc4  ,  7.Bd3  or  7.Bg5  , the capture on c3 works well, and we recommend grabbing this opportunity to unbalance the game. }
7. Bd2
{ White chooses a conservative, healthy move. They avoid doubled pawns and recognize that  7.Bd2  Bxc3  8.Bxc3  Nxe4  is punished by  9.Qg4  when Black is in bad shape.  There is no reason at all for Black to take on c3 immediately. We don't win the e-pawn or demolish White's pawn structure, so we should focus on our development. }
7... O-O
{ The move  7...d6  is also a fine choice. After castling, White now has to worry about the e-pawn and will likely cover it. }
8. Bd3
{ White usually goes for this move to cover the e-pawn. Of course,  8.f3  is also possible and could lead to a position that may also arise from @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/1b2P3/1NN5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.f3  O-O  8.Bd2  .   Against  8.f3  , we'd play similarly as after our main move  8.Bd3  . We develop with ...d6,  ...Nc6 and ...Be6. }
8... d6
{ A d6-based setup is our preference, as mentioned before.  There are alternatives here, like  8...Nc6  , when Black still does not commit the d-pawn. }
9. O-O
{ White can play  9.a3  Bxc3  10.Bxc3  Nc6  , of course. We'll discuss this scenario in a moment via a different move order. }
9... Nc6
{ Black may also play  9...Be6  here, but getting the knight out first is slightly more flexible. }
10. a3
{ White goes for the bishop pair. A different take on the position would be  10.f4  , when  10...exf4  11.Bxf4  Bxc3  12.bxc3  Qc7  leads to a controversial situation in which Black's structure is much better, but White has active pieces.  We have long team assets, like the square on e5. An idea worth noting in this line is ...Bg4-h5-g6,  defending the kingside. }
10... Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Be6
{ Black has a flexible and harmonious position. The important idea is that we can still play ...d5 at a favourable moment. This particularly applies to scenarios involving White's pawn push to f4, for example, in the following line. }
12. f4 Re8
{ You may also start with  12...Bxb3  13.cxb3  Re8  , which can lead to the same position. }
13. Kh1
{ A good prophylactic move. It would be naive to play  13.f5?  , when  13...Bxb3  14.cxb3  d5  is already much better for Black. }
13... Bxb3
{ You can also keep the tension with a move like  13...h6  , but this concrete sequence works well. }
14. cxb3 d5
{ We strike in the centre, which leads to some complications. Some tactical lines could end in a direct draw, like  15.exd5  Nxd5  16.fxe5  Nxc3  17.Bxh7+  Kxh7  18.Qh5+  Kg8  19.Qxf7+  Kh8  20.Rf5  Rxe5  21.Qh5+  Kg8  22.Qf7+  with a perpetual check. }
