7. Bg5
{ White goes for a 'counter-pin' on our knight. It is worth studying this line because it leads to unconventional positions that are good for Black. }
7... Bxc3+
{ We destroy White's pawn structure. Knowing when to take on c3 and when to avoid the capture is important. The key problem of the early ...Bxc3+ is White's idea of Ba3,  which hits our weakness on d6.  A good example is @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/1b2P3/1NN5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.f3  , when  7...Bxc3+?  is bad due to  8.bxc3  d6  9.Ba3  , which is awful for Black.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/1b2P3/1NN5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  White's bishop will not appear on a3,  obviously – green light for  7...Bxc3+!  .  It's also possible to play  7...h6  8.Bh4  Bxc3+  or even @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p1B1/1b2P3/1NN5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...d6  , but we like to be consistent with taking on c3 as early as possible @@StartBracket@@if it is good in the first place, of course!@@EndBracket@@. }
8. bxc3 d6
{ Our target setup ideally involves ...d6,  ...Be6,  ...Nbd7 and ...Qc7,  which looks very harmonious. We have easy targets on the c-file in the long run.  What move to start with? It's possible to flick in  8...h6  here, but  8...d6  looks most natural. Note that the move  8...Qc7  is less convincing here due to  9.Nd2!  Qxc3  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.Bc4  , which gives White too much play. }
9. Qd3
{ This rarely played move is the most interesting one to study. White plans a quick Rd1 or O-O-O,  attacking the d6-pawn.  You'll meet other moves far more often, but they are harmless, like  9.Bd3  , when the described standard setup of ...Be6 and ...Nbd7 is good for Black. White has weaknesses and nothing to show for them. }
9... Be6
{ Our normal move, as intended. Now we'll examine two moves. This is a relatively late split for a rare line, but the ensuing complications are interesting and instructive. We'll check  10.Bxf6  and  10.Rd1  , attacking our pawn directly. }
10. Rd1
{ White attacks our weak pawn immediately. This is possible with  10.O-O-O  , but the white king is not secure on the queenside. We would play in the same way as after 10.Rd1.  Here's a sample line:  10.O-O-O  Nbd7  11.f3  @@StartBracket@@  11.Qxd6  Nxe4  is fine for us@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1p1n1ppp/p2pbn2/4p1B1/4P3/1NPQ1P2/P1P3PP/2KR1B1R b kq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...O-O  12.Qxd6  Rc8  , when White is a pawn up, but all our pieces work well, and White won't find a secure spot for their king. }
10... Nbd7
{ We don't need to fear  11.Qxd6?  , as  11...Nxe4!  works beautifully. } 11.
f3
{ White covers the e-pawn. Now the d-pawn is hanging 'for real'.  As already mentioned,  11.Qxd6?  Nxe4!  leads nowhere for White. }
11... h6 12. Bxf6
{ This pawn grab @@StartBracket@@  12.Bxf6  Nxf6  13.Qxd6  @@EndBracket@@ is risky.   White should prefer  12.Bh4  , when  12...Qc7  13.Qxd6  Qxc3+  14.Qd2  Qc7  leads to about equal chances. Black enjoys the better pawn structure, but White is not in trouble due to the bishop pair and piece activity. }
12... Nxf6 13. Qxd6
{ Our weakness has fallen, but we don't mind. Let's take stock after the next two moves. }
13... Qxd6 14. Rxd6 Nd7
{ A precise move, stopping Nc5 and Rb6 ideas. We are a pawn down but already have slightly better chances. We'll play ...Ke7 and put pressure on the c-file soon, where White has two weak pawns.  White also suffers from a bad bishop because many pawns are already on light squares in their camp. }
