6. Nb3 { A very likely move to face. } 6... Bb4
{ Pin and win! We develop our bishop and prepare kingside castling, but the move has a range of ideas. Here are some concepts to keep in mind.  Black's Options  1@@EndBracket@@ By pinning and usually capturing the c3-knight, we fight to control the d5-square. It is improbable that White establishes dominance over d5,  which often happens in other comparable Sicilian structures.  2@@EndBracket@@ We can often take on c3 and create a doubled pawns. White's pawn structure is severely weakened in such a scenario, but this also applies to our dark squares. We must carefully consider when to create the doubled pawn and when to avoid it. The key consideration is whether White can play Ba3 and quickly point toward our weak spot, d6. Two sample lines help to understand this issue.  After  7.f3  Bxc3+?  is wrong, as  8.bxc3  d6  9.Ba3  is terrible for Black. There is no good way to cover d6.   However, after  7.Bg5  , we happily play  7...Bxc3+  , as clearly Ba3 is off the table.  3@@EndBracket@@ We often have a choice between playing for the move ...d5 or going for a setup based on ...d6. In many cases, the choice between them is a matter of taste.  We generally advocate ...d6-based play, as it keeps more pieces on the board and usually leads to more combative play. Placing our pawns on dark squares is strategically very sound, as we almost always give up our dark-squared bishop, and the remaining light-squared one works well in this structure.   White's Options  Let's get an overview over White's options – our answer depends on them. Against some, taking on c3 is best. Against others, we need to avoid it:  A@@EndBracket@@ Against  7.Bd2  and  7.f3  we avoid the immediate capture, but rather develop with ...O-O and ...d6.  B@@EndBracket@@ If White plays  7.Bc4  ,  7.Bd3  or  7.Bg5  , the capture on c3 works well, and we recommend grabbing this opportunity to unbalance the game. }
7. f3
{ White is worried about the e-pawn and covers it reliably. This is not a bad line for White, but it is often misplayed in practice. The most important moment for Black comes right away. To take on c3 or not to take? }
7... O-O
{ We must remember that against 7.f3,  the capture is a huge mistake, as  7...Bxc3+?  8.bxc3  d6  9.Ba3  demonstrates. We have no good way to cover our weakness on d6.  Compared to 7.Bd3 it is helpful for White that the queen on d1 is not obstructed by a bishop on d3. This is the key difference from @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/1b2P3/1NN5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  , when we advise to play  7...Bxc3+!   Before we continue, a word about @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p1p1ppp/p4n2/4p3/1b2P3/1NN5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.f3  d6  – a fine alternative. The main reason to go for  7...O-O  is that White sometimes, usually in faster time controls, plays  8.Be3?  when  8...d5!  is excellent for Black. }
8. Bd2
{ This looks best and leads to similar play as 7.Bd2.  The alternatives are not great for White. We already talked about  8.Be3?  d5!  , which is nice for Black.   After  8.Bg5  h6  9.Bh4  , we can safely capture the knight:  9...Bxc3+  10.bxc3  d6  looks good, with ...Be6 and ...Nbd7 in mind. }
8... d6
{ As usual, we prefer a setup based on ...d6, unless there is a concrete, tactical reason to go for ...d5. The arising positions are very similar to 7.Bd2, but White has committed to the early f3, limiting our opponent's options. }
9. a3
{ After  9.Bd3  Nc6  , there is nothing concrete to know: we transpose to a good version of the 7.Bd2 line. }
9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Qc7
{ A small finesse. White might have a quick Qd2 and O-O-O in mind. 10...Qc7 is directed against this idea. }
11. Qd2
{ White can still play  11.Bd3  and O-O,  of course. This would be about equal, but let's check why the ambitious plan does not work well. }
11... Be6 12. O-O-O d5
{ It's instructive to see how ...Qc7 and ...Be6 work well together. The queen covers e5 and c5,  while the bishop move supports the central strike.  Black is already better, as  13.exd5  Nxd5  14.Bd3  Nd7  , followed by ...Rfc8,  demonstrates. }
