[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Tricky Knights 2.Nf3 a6 3.Nc3"]
[Black "Introduction to the Tricky Knights"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. Nc3
{ White continues with their development, a natural and good choice. Is there a deeper concept behind the move? They might just want to play along with general principles, but a compelling idea is connected to the knight move.  Let's assume our opponent might usually play the Open Sicilian, for instance after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.d4  or after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.d4  , opening the game. However, they know that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  is fine for Black. By playing @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  3.Nc3  , White hopes for a transposition to a mainstream Open Sicilian, going for d2-d4 on the next move.  What to do with the black pieces? We have no chance to get to our favourite Open Sicilian, as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...a6  3.Nc3  can't be answered by  3...Nf6?  due to  4.e5  , when there is no good reply.  The way to go is allowing a transposition to a different Open Sicilian, which leads to exciting play for both sides. }
3... b5
{ Here we go! We didn't play ...a6 for nothing, after all 😊. Still, there are good alternatives at this point that are worth mentioning.  A@@EndBracket@@ If you have some experience/knowledge of the Najdorf,  3...d6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nf6  is a good way to transpose to this popular opening.   B@@EndBracket@@ The continuation  3...e6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  is a second good option. Black could go  5...b5  now, which would transpose to the lines examined in this chapter. Besides 5...b5,  the moves  5...Qc7  ,  5...Nc6  or  5...d6  are possible, too.   Line B is very similar/transpositional to our suggestion. We decided to use the  3...b5  move order as it felt more natural and similar to lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  a6  3.g3  b5  , for example.  @@StartBlockQuote@@We play ...b5 if there is a knight on c3 to attack.@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Tricky Knights 2.Nf3 a6 3.Nc3"]
[Black "2A | Tricky Knights with 6.Be3 |"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. Nc3 b5 4. d4
{ The only critical move.  White may also play the slow move  4.g3  , but this would transpose to play similar to the Closed Sicilian, covered in our chapter on 2.Nc3 a6. }
4... cxd4 { We get an Open Sicilian after all. } 5. Nxd4
{ Black has two sound and logical moves here, 5...e6 and 5...Bb7. The difference between them is subtle. In most cases, we'd reach precisely the same positions, as Black usually needs both moves quickly. Let's examine the difference.  In both cases, the most critical reply is 6.Bd3 @@StartBracket@@more on that later@@EndBracket@@, when  5...e6  6.Bd3  Qb6  is our suggestion. We immediately attack the d4-knight and try to push it away from the centre. If White plays  7.Be3  , the reply  7...Bc5  gives us fair chances.   This idea does not work after  5...Bb7  6.Bd3  Qb6?  7.Be3  , when we can't play the bishop to c5. Black would need to play a different idea on move 6 in this line.  We, however, like the ...Qb6 idea and therefore need to play 5...e6 first. }
5... e6
{ We have already discussed why we prefer starting with this move instead of 5...Bb7. What's next? Our general idea and ideal development scheme to go for is the following:  ➤ Play ...Bb7  ➤ Play ...Nf6 next, if White can't favourably reply e4-e5  ➤ If e4-e5 is a problem, the move ...Qc7 is an excellent way to cover against it  It looks like these moves are very natural, increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn. We don't want to play ...b5-b4 quickly but rather pile up on the e4-pawn to make ...b5-b4 a more profound idea, ideally winning the centre pawn!  White needs to make up their mind about how to develop the pieces. Our idea is to attack the e4-pawn quickly. It is therefore not a surprise that 6.Bd3 is a sensible move for White. In fact, it is the only move that poses a severe theoretical challenge to our opening concept.  Why? The critical point is that after 6.Bd3,  we can't play our ideal moves so quickly. After  6.Bd3  Bb7  7.O-O  the move  7...Nf6?  is answered with  8.e5!  Nd5  9.Nxd5  Bxd5  , when White has many strong ideas, often involving Qg4.  If White does not play 6.Bd3,  however, we will obtain good chances without any particular problems, using a quick ...Bb7 and ...Nf6,  often prepared by ...Qc7.  We'll check some concrete moves in a moment, but we'd like to discuss an additional point first. Our queenside play is much faster than in many other Sicilian setups. We have already played ...a6 and ...b5,  gaining space on this side of the board. This renders a possible queenside castling by White less attractive than in other Sicilian lines, where it is commonplace.   As mentioned, it looks best for White to prioritize kingside castling and support the e4-pawn, which is why 6.Bd3 looks like the most dangerous move. Let's have an overview of White's options.  White's Options  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a way for White to play for queenside castling. The setup Be3/Qd2 and O-O-O,  often accompanied with f3,  is called English Attack and a popular approach in many Sicilian lines, particularly the Najdorf. As mentioned above, we are happy to see White's king on the side of the board where our play has already started.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  is an unpopular but reasonable line for White. Placing the bishop on g2 helps cover the e4-pawn and prepares kingside castling. In some cases, the play can become quite sharp. We exert intense pressure on the e-pawn, which might prompt White to sacrifice material to avoid a passive setup.  C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is similar to 6.g3. White prepares O-O and will often cover the e-pawn with Bf3 later.  D@@EndBracket@@  6.a3  is a move that we are happy to see. White spends a tempo on securing their knight but, in the process, loses valuable time. This move is the most popular at the amateur/club level and in online games. This statistic is a significant incentive to play our suggested quick ...b5-line. Many players on the white side will go for a non-critical reply like 6.a3,  making our life easy.  E@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  is the most dangerous move and slightly different to the alternatives above. We won't be able to generate quick play against e4,  as the pawn is better protected now. We suggest playing  6...Qb6  , trying to force the white knight back to a less active square. This idea gives this line a different feel to A-D above. }
6. Be3
{ White often plays a setup with Be3 and Qd2 in the Sicilian, most notably against the Dragon and the Najdorf. White quickly develops the queenside and prepares castling on this side of the board. It is a playable option against our variation, but we certainly don't mind facing it.  Compared to other Sicilian lines, our queenside counterplay is faster. It's also important to note that we have not played the d-pawn yet, which often allows the pawn-push ...d7-d5 in one go. Realizing this pawn break often takes two moves in other Sicilian lines, like the Najdorf. }
6... Bb7 { Our normal move. Now we threaten ...b5-b4, winning the e-pawn. } 7.
f3
{ White lends additional cover to the e-pawn and prepares g2-g4 at a later stage if desired.  White also could have played  7.Bd3  to defend the e-pawn, but this move does not fit well with the queenside castling ambitions connected to 6.Be3. Black would be fine with standard moves, like  7...Qc7  8.O-O  Nf6  , when we again threaten ...b5-b4 to win the central pawn.  After  9.a3  , we'd have plenty of options, like playing with  9...d6  and ...Nb8-d7 next, or just  9...Nc6  to develop the queenside. }
7... Nf6
{ In this system, we can play ...Nf6 without preparing the move with ...Qc7,  as we don't need to fear the reply e4-e5. After  8.e5?!  Nd5  9.Nxd5  Bxd5  we enjoy a good position. White's pawn move f3 sticks out and keeps the White queen passive.  We can compare this to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/3p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  Bb7  @@StartBracket@@not our move@@EndBracket@@  7.O-O  Nf6?!  8.e5  Nd5  9.Nxd5  Bxd5  , when White often has the strong Qg4 sortie. }
8. Qd2
{ White continues with their castling preparation.  As mentioned,  8.e5?!  Nd5  is good for Black. Is there anything else for White?  They could go  8.a3  , but combining aggressive and slow moves is not scary. We can play  8...Qc7  and ...d5 next, solving our opening task with ease. }
8... b4
{ The most direct move, attacking White's knight. There is nothing wrong with  8...Qc7  , either. }
9. Na4
{ This is more testing than  9.Nce2  , when  9...e5  10.Nb3  d5  or  10...Qc7  gives us an easy game.   The knight jumps to a4 and looks at the weakened b6-square, which now prevents  9.Na4  e5??  10.Nb3  , when Nb6 is a terrible threat. }
9... d5
{ As already mentioned, we can't play  9...e5??  10.Nb3  , as Nb6 is impossible to defend against.   Instead,  9...d5  attacks White's e-pawn directly. }
10. e5
{ We can't be troubled by  10.exd5  Nxd5  , which gives our knight a great spot in the centre. }
10... Nfd7 11. f4 Nc6
{ All of a sudden, we have reached a position that looks a lot like a French Defence! That's not what we initially signed up for but hang on... it's a nice position for us! White's problem is the knight on a4, which helps us greatly. }
12. Nb3
{ This is probably White's most challenging try. Here are some alternatives that don't pose any problems:  A@@EndBracket@@  12.b3  gives the knight a retreat square, but  12...Nxd4  13.Bxd4  Bc6  looks fine for Black. White's knight will be passive on b2,  while we have the idea ...Nc5-e4 later.  B@@EndBracket@@  12.Nf3  Qa5  13.b3  Nc5  14.Nxc5  Bxc5  looks good for Black. A key idea is  15.Qf2  d4!  , which gives up a pawn to activate our bishop, making it the strongest piece on the board. }
12... Be7
{ Our king will be safe on the kingside – our opponent's knights are on the other side of the board. It's also important to note that White has difficulty getting f4-f5 on the board, as we have too much pressure on the e5-pawn. }
13. Bd3
{ A natural move, developing the bishop. White has various alternatives, but we can be happy with our prospects. Ideas like ...Rc8,  followed by ...Na5-c4,  look logical. Our b7-bishop can be activated via c6 and b5 in such a scenario.  After  13.Bd3  , we could employ such a plan, too... but we have something more exciting. }
13... d4
{ As mentioned, there is nothing wrong about castling and going for queenside play with ...Rc8 and ...Na5.  Instead, we'd like to take a look at this enterprising alternative – we push the d-pawn to open our bishop. }
14. Nxd4
{ White could also decline the pawn sacrifice and play  14.Bf2  , when  14...g5!  sets the board on fire! We attack the f4-pawn, trying to undermine and win e5. }
14... Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bh4+
{ The final move worth remembering. We have this annoying check, forcing White to move the king. They can't play  16.Bf2?  due to  16...Bxg2  .  White has various king moves, but it makes little sense to dig any deeper, as our compensation is compelling in all cases. Our pieces are much more active and coordinated, while White's king is insecure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Tricky Knights 2.Nf3 a6 3.Nc3"]
[Black "2B | Tricky Knights with 6.g3 | White plays 8.O-O / 9.Nd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. Nc3 b5 4. d4
{ The only critical move.  White may also play the slow move  4.g3  , but this would transpose to play similar to the Closed Sicilian, covered in our chapter on 2.Nc3 a6. }
4... cxd4 { We get an Open Sicilian after all. } 5. Nxd4
{ Black has two sound and logical moves here, 5...e6 and 5...Bb7. The difference between them is subtle. In most cases, we'd reach precisely the same positions, as Black usually needs both moves quickly. Let's examine the difference.  In both cases, the most critical reply is 6.Bd3 @@StartBracket@@more on that later@@EndBracket@@, when  5...e6  6.Bd3  Qb6  is our suggestion. We immediately attack the d4-knight and try to push it away from the centre. If White plays  7.Be3  , the reply  7...Bc5  gives us fair chances.   This idea does not work after  5...Bb7  6.Bd3  Qb6?  7.Be3  , when we can't play the bishop to c5. Black would need to play a different idea on move 6 in this line.  We, however, like the ...Qb6 idea and therefore need to play 5...e6 first. }
5... e6
{ We have already discussed why we prefer starting with this move instead of 5...Bb7. What's next? Our general idea and ideal development scheme to go for is the following:  ➤ Play ...Bb7  ➤ Play ...Nf6 next, if White can't favourably reply e4-e5  ➤ If e4-e5 is a problem, the move ...Qc7 is an excellent way to cover against it  It looks like these moves are very natural, increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn. We don't want to play ...b5-b4 quickly but rather pile up on the e4-pawn to make ...b5-b4 a more profound idea, ideally winning the centre pawn!  White needs to make up their mind about how to develop the pieces. Our idea is to attack the e4-pawn quickly. It is therefore not a surprise that 6.Bd3 is a sensible move for White. In fact, it is the only move that poses a severe theoretical challenge to our opening concept.  Why? The critical point is that after 6.Bd3,  we can't play our ideal moves so quickly. After  6.Bd3  Bb7  7.O-O  the move  7...Nf6?  is answered with  8.e5!  Nd5  9.Nxd5  Bxd5  , when White has many strong ideas, often involving Qg4.  If White does not play 6.Bd3,  however, we will obtain good chances without any particular problems, using a quick ...Bb7 and ...Nf6,  often prepared by ...Qc7.  We'll check some concrete moves in a moment, but we'd like to discuss an additional point first. Our queenside play is much faster than in many other Sicilian setups. We have already played ...a6 and ...b5,  gaining space on this side of the board. This renders a possible queenside castling by White less attractive than in other Sicilian lines, where it is commonplace.   As mentioned, it looks best for White to prioritize kingside castling and support the e4-pawn, which is why 6.Bd3 looks like the most dangerous move. Let's have an overview of White's options.  White's Options  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a way for White to play for queenside castling. The setup Be3/Qd2 and O-O-O,  often accompanied with f3,  is called English Attack and a popular approach in many Sicilian lines, particularly the Najdorf. As mentioned above, we are happy to see White's king on the side of the board where our play has already started.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  is an unpopular but reasonable line for White. Placing the bishop on g2 helps cover the e4-pawn and prepares kingside castling. In some cases, the play can become quite sharp. We exert intense pressure on the e-pawn, which might prompt White to sacrifice material to avoid a passive setup.  C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is similar to 6.g3. White prepares O-O and will often cover the e-pawn with Bf3 later.  D@@EndBracket@@  6.a3  is a move that we are happy to see. White spends a tempo on securing their knight but, in the process, loses valuable time. This move is the most popular at the amateur/club level and in online games. This statistic is a significant incentive to play our suggested quick ...b5-line. Many players on the white side will go for a non-critical reply like 6.a3,  making our life easy.  E@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  is the most dangerous move and slightly different to the alternatives above. We won't be able to generate quick play against e4,  as the pawn is better protected now. We suggest playing  6...Qb6  , trying to force the white knight back to a less active square. This idea gives this line a different feel to A-D above. }
6. g3
{ White wants to cover the e-pawn and prepares castling kingside. This line is not popular but a reasonable choice with some surprisingly sharp possibilities later. Let's have a look. }
6... Bb7
{ Our normal move.  It's also possible to start with the uncommon  6...Nf6  here, as  7.e5?!  Bb7!  shows that the pawn push to e5 is not to be feared. }
7. Bg2 Nf6
{ We increase the pressure on e4. White now has to reckon with ...b5-b4,  pushing the knight away from its defensive post.  We'll look at the conservative  8.a3  and  8.O-O  , which sacrifices material! }
8. O-O
{ This is White's aggressive option. They raise the stakes by ignoring our b5-b4 idea. }
8... b4
{ 'I call!' We threatened ...b5-b4,  and White ignored the idea, going for material sacrifices. We must accept White's challenge and push the b-pawn, seeing that something slow does not cut it.  You can't play  8...d6?  9.Re1  Qc7  for example, as  10.a4  b4  11.Nd5  is killing, amongst others. White is essentially a tempo up on the line 8.a3, which is too much to handle.   After the only good move,  8...b4  , White has two interesting options:  9.Na4  and the surprising piece sacrifice  9.Nd5!?  . Let's have a look. }
9. Nd5
{ This piece sacrifice leads to fun complications, but no advantage for White. }
9... exd5 10. exd5
{ White's concept is clear: attack on the open e-file. Our next move is crucial! }
10... Bc5
{ This looks logical, but it is also the only playable move.  Something like  10...d6??  11.Re1+  Kd7  12.c3  will likely end in a quick mate. }
11. Re1+ Kf8
{ Alright, we will not get mated quickly on f8. However, our development and piece coordination is lacking. Is this enough for White to justify the piece sacrifice?  A deeper computer analysis concludes that chances should be equal@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@. But it is clear that in practice, the situation is going to be difficult to navigate for both sides. The key to White's play seems to be not rushing with an attack but slowly opening the queenside instead. }
12. a3
{ This idea looks best, according to the engine. A similar @@StartBracket@@and most likely transpositional@@EndBracket@@ concept is  12.Nb3  Bb6  13.a3  , when  13...a5  14.axb4  axb4  15.Rxa8  Bxa8  16.Bd2  h5  leads to 12.a3 a5 below.   In some Blitz games, White has tried  12.Nf5?  , but it leads nowhere after the simple  12...d6  . White should rather play on the queenside, where our weaknesses are. }
12... a5 13. axb4
{ Here,  13.Nb3  Bb6  14.axb4  axb4  15.Rxa8  Bxa8  may lead to the same thing. }
13... axb4 { Taking with the bishop is also possible and of similar quality. }
14. Rxa8 Bxa8 15. Nb3 Bb6
{ 15...d6  is a playable alternative, which also seems to lead to equal chances. }
16. Bd2 h5
{ We like this active idea, trying to use the rook on its starting square. }
17. Bxb4+ d6
{ We decided to stop the long line here. The piece sacrifice 8.Nd5 is a fascinating idea, but we are happy with Black's chances. Our material advantage is significant, and there are some good alternatives along the way to the final position we have reached now. }
*

