9... Bxe4
{ Tasty! We happily grab the centre pawn and are ready to battle White's attack.  It's important to remember to take with the bishop, as  9...Nxe4??  10.Re1  leaves us in a nasty pin. }
10. Bxe4 Nxe4 11. Re1
{ White almost always plays this natural move.  Stockfish suggests the rare  11.c3  , opening the position after  11...bxc3  12.bxc3  Be7  . White does have some compensation for the pawn, but it looks simple for us to play. }
11... Nc5
{ An important move to remember. We have a much easier job compared to  11...d5  12.c4  , which opens the game more quickly. }
12. c3
{ A quick way for White to lose the thread is  12.Nxc5  Bxc5  and now  13.Qg4?  Qf6!  , when we start a winning counterattack. }
12... Nxa4 13. Qxa4
{ White has a massive lead in development, but we can catch up now. } 13... Qb6
{ We look at the d4-knight and thus prevent White's cxb4 threat. } 14. Be3 Bc5
{ Finally, we are ready to castle! White has to be precise now to keep their initiative going.  Stockfish suggests  15.Qd1  as best, which is far from obvious. After this move, both  15...O-O  and  15...bxc3  work for Black but seem to give White just about enough to justify the pawn sacrifice. }
