{ We increase the pressure on e4. White now has to reckon with ...b5-b4,  pushing the knight away from its defensive post.  We'll look at the conservative  8.a3  and  8.O-O  , which sacrifices material! }
8. a3 { Safe and sound, but not scary for Black. } 8... Qc7
{ Soon enough, White will threaten e4-e5. The queen move covers the b7-bishop and is part of our usual setup.  Please note that  8...Nc6  is terrible due to  9.e5!  and must be avoided.   A reasonable alternative is  8...d6  – it will likely transpose to our recommended line  8...Qc7  9.O-O  d6  . }
9. O-O d6
{ We make sure e4-e5 is stopped!  Here,  9...Nc6  is an option, but it's not easy to play for Black. White's best reply is  10.Nxc6  , when  10...Bxc6?  11.Nd5!  is a cold shower, leading to a decisive attack for White. We'll spare you the details, as we'd like to avoid 9...Nc6 anyway.   Of course,  9...Nc6  10.Nxc6  dxc6  is better in comparison but not attractive for Black, either. }
10. Re1 { White is lining up their rook against our king. Careful now! } 10...
Be7
{ It's sensible to castle kingside as soon as possible!  Lines like  10...Nc6?  11.Nxc6  Bxc6  12.Nd5!  or @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/1bq2ppp/p2ppn2/1p6/3NP3/P1N3P1/1PP2PBP/R1BQR1K1 b kq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nbd7  11.Bg5  Be7  12.Nd5!  are to be avoided! }
11. a4
{ It looks a bit odd to move the a-pawn a second time, but this is the only way to put some pressure on Black. Our job is easy if White just develops pieces without a clear plan.  Have a look at  11.Bg5  O-O  12.Qe2  Nbd7  13.Rad1  Rac8  , when it is tough to suggest an idea for White. We have play on the c-file and the queenside. We have ...Nd7-e5-c4,  for example. Other ideas are the queen manoeuvre to a8 or the exchange sacrifice on c3,  standard ideas of the Sicilian arsenal. }
11... bxa4
{ You have to avoid  11...b4?  12.Na2  a5  13.Nb5  , which gives White a smashing attack. }
12. Rxa4 Nbd7
{ White has the slightly better pawn structure now due to our isolated a-pawn. This is not a serious issue, though – there is much more going on in the position than the a-pawn.  We'll castle kingside and try to use the open files on the queenside. A typical idea is ...Nb6-c4, activating our knight. We assess the chances as about equal here. }
