{ Black has two sound and logical moves here, 5...e6 and 5...Bb7. The difference between them is subtle. In most cases, we'd reach precisely the same positions, as Black usually needs both moves quickly. Let's examine the difference.  In both cases, the most critical reply is 6.Bd3 @@StartBracket@@more on that later@@EndBracket@@, when  5...e6  6.Bd3  Qb6  is our suggestion. We immediately attack the d4-knight and try to push it away from the centre. If White plays  7.Be3  , the reply  7...Bc5  gives us fair chances.   This idea does not work after  5...Bb7  6.Bd3  Qb6?  7.Be3  , when we can't play the bishop to c5. Black would need to play a different idea on move 6 in this line.  We, however, like the ...Qb6 idea and therefore need to play 5...e6 first. }
5... e6
{ We have already discussed why we prefer starting with this move instead of 5...Bb7. What's next? Our general idea and ideal development scheme to go for is the following:  ➤ Play ...Bb7  ➤ Play ...Nf6 next, if White can't favourably reply e4-e5  ➤ If e4-e5 is a problem, the move ...Qc7 is an excellent way to cover against it  It looks like these moves are very natural, increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn. We don't want to play ...b5-b4 quickly but rather pile up on the e4-pawn to make ...b5-b4 a more profound idea, ideally winning the centre pawn!  White needs to make up their mind about how to develop the pieces. Our idea is to attack the e4-pawn quickly. It is therefore not a surprise that 6.Bd3 is a sensible move for White. In fact, it is the only move that poses a severe theoretical challenge to our opening concept.  Why? The critical point is that after 6.Bd3,  we can't play our ideal moves so quickly. After  6.Bd3  Bb7  7.O-O  the move  7...Nf6?  is answered with  8.e5!  Nd5  9.Nxd5  Bxd5  , when White has many strong ideas, often involving Qg4.  If White does not play 6.Bd3,  however, we will obtain good chances without any particular problems, using a quick ...Bb7 and ...Nf6,  often prepared by ...Qc7.  We'll check some concrete moves in a moment, but we'd like to discuss an additional point first. Our queenside play is much faster than in many other Sicilian setups. We have already played ...a6 and ...b5,  gaining space on this side of the board. This renders a possible queenside castling by White less attractive than in other Sicilian lines, where it is commonplace.   As mentioned, it looks best for White to prioritize kingside castling and support the e4-pawn, which is why 6.Bd3 looks like the most dangerous move. Let's have an overview of White's options.  White's Options  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a way for White to play for queenside castling. The setup Be3/Qd2 and O-O-O,  often accompanied with f3,  is called English Attack and a popular approach in many Sicilian lines, particularly the Najdorf. As mentioned above, we are happy to see White's king on the side of the board where our play has already started.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  is an unpopular but reasonable line for White. Placing the bishop on g2 helps cover the e4-pawn and prepares kingside castling. In some cases, the play can become quite sharp. We exert intense pressure on the e-pawn, which might prompt White to sacrifice material to avoid a passive setup.  C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is similar to 6.g3. White prepares O-O and will often cover the e-pawn with Bf3 later.  D@@EndBracket@@  6.a3  is a move that we are happy to see. White spends a tempo on securing their knight but, in the process, loses valuable time. This move is the most popular at the amateur/club level and in online games. This statistic is a significant incentive to play our suggested quick ...b5-line. Many players on the white side will go for a non-critical reply like 6.a3,  making our life easy.  E@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  is the most dangerous move and slightly different to the alternatives above. We won't be able to generate quick play against e4,  as the pawn is better protected now. We suggest playing  6...Qb6  , trying to force the white knight back to a less active square. This idea gives this line a different feel to A-D above. }
6. Be2
{ White develops and prepares kingside castling. This conservative approach is common in other Sicilian lines but rather toothless against our active setup. }
6... Bb7
{ We increase the pressure on e4 and now threaten b5-b4, winning the pawn. } 7.
Bf3
{ White covers the pawn, which is understandable. We have reached a position which is rather similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/3p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.g3  Bb7  7.Bg2  , but there is an important difference: on g2,  the bishop is unprotected, which allows us to play  7...Nf6  .  Here, after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/1b1p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bf3  , the move 7...Nf6 is bad due to the pawn advance, as  7...Nf6?  8.e5  demonstrates. Before we continue with our examination of 7.Bf3,  we look at alternatives:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/1b1p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  is an interesting pawn sacrifice. We play  7...b4  8.Na4  Bxe4  9.Bf3  Nf6  10.Bxe4  Nxe4  , when it's a good moment to think about the position. It turns out that it is almost identical to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/3p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.g3  Bb7  7.Bg2  Nf6  8.O-O  b4  9.Na4  Bxe4  10.Bxe4  Nxe4  , which we examine in the current chapter, too. The only difference is White's move g3,  which does not change the evaluation at all. White has some play for the pawn, but we are in good shape.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/1b1p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.a3  is a passive move, which leads to a situation we also discuss after the move order 6.a3. We have a good game with natural moves, like  7...Qc7  8.O-O  Nf6  9.Bf3  Nc6  shows. The knight tour ...Ne5-c4 is already looming. }
7... Ne7
{ A surprising and somewhat uncommon development of our knight, but it is well justified. Let's check why alternatives don't work well and what 7...Ne7 accomplishes.  A@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6?  is an apparent mistake due to  8.e5  , when we have no good reply.   B@@EndBracket@@  7...Qc7  8.O-O  did not help prepare the knight jump to f6. as  8...Nf6?  9.e5  is still terrible. You could play @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/1bqp1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N2B2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8...d6  , but White has the strong move  9.a4!  , when  9...b4  10.Na2  is good for White. They get to open the queenside quickly while our development is severely behind.   C@@EndBracket@@  7...Nc6  is better than A and B, but after  8.Nxc6  Bxc6  , it is still not obvious how to easily develop the knight.  The idea of our suggestion 7...Ne7 is playing ...Nbc6 next and meet White's Nxc6 with ...Ne7xc6,  getting this piece into the game more quickly. }
8. O-O
{ The natural move.  If White goes  8.e5  , we have  8...Nbc6  and no problems at all. White has gained some space, but we have chances to use the d5-square and attack the e5-pawn later. }
8... Nbc6
{ Following the idea described earlier. White now has to allow a knight to trade or retreat to the passive b3-square, which is unattractive. }
9. Be3
{ The capture on c6 could easily lead to similar or even the same positions after  9.Nxc6  Nxc6  10.Be3  Rc8  , when Black is already better – see the main line @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1b1pnppp/p1n1p3/1p6/3NP3/2N2B2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Be3  Nxd4  10.Bxd4  Nc6  11.Be3  Rc8  .   Retreating with  9.Nb3  is passive and can be answered with  9...Ng6  or the more direct  9...Ne5  , hunting the bishop pair. }
9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Nc6
{ We have accomplished our goal of developing the kingside without getting punished by e4-e5. Now White needs to decide about their d4-bishop. }
11. Be3
{ Preserving the bishop looks natural, but Black is in good shape after this move.  Stockfish recommends  11.Re1  with equal chances after  11...Nxd4  12.Qxd4  Rc8  or moves like  11...Qb8  or  11...Rc8  . There is some room for creativity in these positions. }
11... Rc8
{ Not the only good move here, the direct  11...Ne5  also works well.  Black's chances are already preferable here. We have ...Ne5-c4 ideas and White's pieces are in rather passive positions. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Tricky Knights 2.Nf3 a6 3.Nc3"]
[Black "2D | Tricky Knights with 6.a3 |"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. Nc3 b5 4. d4
{ The only critical move.  White may also play the slow move  4.g3  , but this would transpose to play similar to the Closed Sicilian, covered in our chapter on 2.Nc3 a6. }
4... cxd4 { We get an Open Sicilian after all. } 5. Nxd4
{ Black has two sound and logical moves here, 5...e6 and 5...Bb7. The difference between them is subtle. In most cases, we'd reach precisely the same positions, as Black usually needs both moves quickly. Let's examine the difference.  In both cases, the most critical reply is 6.Bd3 @@StartBracket@@more on that later@@EndBracket@@, when  5...e6  6.Bd3  Qb6  is our suggestion. We immediately attack the d4-knight and try to push it away from the centre. If White plays  7.Be3  , the reply  7...Bc5  gives us fair chances.   This idea does not work after  5...Bb7  6.Bd3  Qb6?  7.Be3  , when we can't play the bishop to c5. Black would need to play a different idea on move 6 in this line.  We, however, like the ...Qb6 idea and therefore need to play 5...e6 first. }
5... e6
{ We have already discussed why we prefer starting with this move instead of 5...Bb7. What's next? Our general idea and ideal development scheme to go for is the following:  ➤ Play ...Bb7  ➤ Play ...Nf6 next, if White can't favourably reply e4-e5  ➤ If e4-e5 is a problem, the move ...Qc7 is an excellent way to cover against it  It looks like these moves are very natural, increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn. We don't want to play ...b5-b4 quickly but rather pile up on the e4-pawn to make ...b5-b4 a more profound idea, ideally winning the centre pawn!  White needs to make up their mind about how to develop the pieces. Our idea is to attack the e4-pawn quickly. It is therefore not a surprise that 6.Bd3 is a sensible move for White. In fact, it is the only move that poses a severe theoretical challenge to our opening concept.  Why? The critical point is that after 6.Bd3,  we can't play our ideal moves so quickly. After  6.Bd3  Bb7  7.O-O  the move  7...Nf6?  is answered with  8.e5!  Nd5  9.Nxd5  Bxd5  , when White has many strong ideas, often involving Qg4.  If White does not play 6.Bd3,  however, we will obtain good chances without any particular problems, using a quick ...Bb7 and ...Nf6,  often prepared by ...Qc7.  We'll check some concrete moves in a moment, but we'd like to discuss an additional point first. Our queenside play is much faster than in many other Sicilian setups. We have already played ...a6 and ...b5,  gaining space on this side of the board. This renders a possible queenside castling by White less attractive than in other Sicilian lines, where it is commonplace.   As mentioned, it looks best for White to prioritize kingside castling and support the e4-pawn, which is why 6.Bd3 looks like the most dangerous move. Let's have an overview of White's options.  White's Options  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a way for White to play for queenside castling. The setup Be3/Qd2 and O-O-O,  often accompanied with f3,  is called English Attack and a popular approach in many Sicilian lines, particularly the Najdorf. As mentioned above, we are happy to see White's king on the side of the board where our play has already started.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  is an unpopular but reasonable line for White. Placing the bishop on g2 helps cover the e4-pawn and prepares kingside castling. In some cases, the play can become quite sharp. We exert intense pressure on the e-pawn, which might prompt White to sacrifice material to avoid a passive setup.  C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is similar to 6.g3. White prepares O-O and will often cover the e-pawn with Bf3 later.  D@@EndBracket@@  6.a3  is a move that we are happy to see. White spends a tempo on securing their knight but, in the process, loses valuable time. This move is the most popular at the amateur/club level and in online games. This statistic is a significant incentive to play our suggested quick ...b5-line. Many players on the white side will go for a non-critical reply like 6.a3,  making our life easy.  E@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  is the most dangerous move and slightly different to the alternatives above. We won't be able to generate quick play against e4,  as the pawn is better protected now. We suggest playing  6...Qb6  , trying to force the white knight back to a less active square. This idea gives this line a different feel to A-D above. }
6. a3
{ White spends a tempo to stop ...b5-b4. We didn't threaten this move immediately, but White often feels annoyed enough by it to feel provoked to play the a-pawn.  The move 6.a3 is White's most popular move in online play and lower-level games, which makes it essential to study. Let's check how the game unfolds. After our natural reply, White has a choice again. }
6... Bb7
{ Now, White faces the same choice as on the move before. What bishop move to play? The most crucial move to check is  7.Bd3  , but we'll also discuss the alternatives in the notes. }
7. Bd3
{ This looks like the most exciting try for White.  You'll also meet  7.Be2  or  7.Be3  , but our setup will be the same as after 6.Be2 or 6.Be3. We'll just go for ...Qc7 and ...Nf6,  increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn. Sample lines are:  A@@EndBracket@@  7.Be2  Qc7  8.O-O  Nf6  9.Bf3  Nc6  gives Black a great game. We might play ...Ne5 next, aiming at the f3-bishop and the juicy c4-square. White's play is slower compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/3p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  Bb7  7.Bf3  , which allows us the more active ...Nf6 approach.   B@@EndBracket@@  7.Be3  Qc7  8.f3  Nf6  9.Qd2  d5  10.exd5  Nxd5  looks good for Black, too. The move a3 and the aggressive Be3 + f3 don't fit well. }
7... Qc7
{ This looks like the best solution.  Why not 7...Qb6?  The move  7...Qb6  looks logical and in line with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/3p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  Qb6  , but there is a somewhat strange tactical issue about it:   After  7...Qb6  8.Be3  Bc5  9.Nce2  Nc6  White has the fun move  10.b4!  when  10...Bxd4  11.Nxd4  Nxd4  12.c3  leads to complications that look promising for White.  Why 7...Qc7 is good in this position   Here, we can afford  7...Qc7  , as White doesn't manage a quick e4-e5,  which would be the issue about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/3p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  Bb7  7.O-O  Qc7  8.Re1  , when  8...Nf6  9.e5!  is great for White.  The move 6.a3 more or less loses a tempo, which makes a substantial difference. }
8. O-O { A natural move. } 8... Nf6
{ Here we go! We have completed our standard setup, which is not so easy to do against Bd3-setups.  How does this position compare to our line against 6.Bd3, by the way? We play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/3p1ppp/p3p3/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  Qb6  7.Nb3  Qc7  8.O-O  Bb7  in this line. We needed to spend a tempo @@StartBracket@@...Qb6-c7@@EndBracket@@ to enable a ...Nf6 setup.  Against 6.a3,  we accomplish our favoured piece placement one move faster, as we play ...Qc7 in one move. On the other hand, White still has the knight on d4 but has spent a tempo on the move a3. The nature of the play is still somewhat similar.  A key idea for White is again preparing the pawn push e4-e5,  sometimes even supported by the move f2-f4. We have a range of options regarding our setup. A critical decision is the placement of our b8-knight. It's possible to play ...d7-d6 and continue with ...Nb8-d7,  but developing it to c6 without playing the d-pawn is an option, too.  A fun idea is playing ...Bd6!?,  which comes into consideration if White can't favourably reply with e4-e5 @@StartBracket@@fork!@@EndBracket@@ or f2-f4,  which threatens the annoying fork.  We'll have a look at some lines now to illustrate ideas. }
9. Qe2
{ We'll examine this as the primary move, but White has many alternatives.  A@@EndBracket@@  9.Re1  is similar to 9.Qe2 and can be answered by  9...Bd6!?  , fighting for the dark squares.  10.h3  Nc6  11.Be3  Nxd4  12.Bxd4  Bh2+  13.Kh1  Be5  demonstrates this concept.   B@@EndBracket@@  9.Be3  should not be met with  9...Bd6  , as 10.f4 is possible. A good solution is switching to  9...d6  , with ...Nbd7 next. There is nothing wrong about  9...Nc6  , either. White's setup is not aggressive enough to limit our options.   C@@EndBracket@@  9.Bg5  can be met with  9...Be7  and ...d6/...Nbd7 next, Again, we have some leeway here due to White's slow play. }
9... Bd6
{ A cool idea, fighting for the dark squares in the centre. White can't reply with  10.f4??  , as  10...Bc5  11.Be3  Qb6  is an early end of White's hopes. They lose material and  12.Qf2  Ng4  does not help. }
10. h3 Nc6 11. Be3
{ After  11.Nxc6  , all recaptures are playable. Interesting lines are  11...dxc6  12.f4  e5  or  11...Qxc6  12.f4  e5  , with good play for Black in both cases. Our pieces are active and in the case of  11...dxc6  you could argue that Black even plays for an advantage in space. }
11... Bh2+
{ We argue that White's king is slightly worse on h1 than on g1 and insert this check. On h1 the king is further away from the centre @@StartBracket@@endgame@@EndBracket@@ but also on the diagonal of our b7-bishop. This could help with tactics later. }
12. Kh1 Bf4
{ We stop f2-f4 by simply occupying the square. Our position looks fine, as we don't have to worry about the central pawn-push e4-e5 for the moment.  White's position is certainly healthy, but they lack a clear plan. We will castle kingside next and have typical Sicilian ideas next, like playing on the c-file. }
