h in many Sicilian lines, particularly the Najdorf. As mentioned above, we are happy to see White's king on the side of the board where our play has already started.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  is an unpopular but reasonable line for White. Placing the bishop on g2 helps cover the e4-pawn and prepares kingside castling. In some cases, the play can become quite sharp. We exert intense pressure on the e-pawn, which might prompt White to sacrifice material to avoid a passive setup.  C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is similar to 6.g3. White prepares O-O and will often cover the e-pawn with Bf3 later.  D@@EndBracket@@  6.a3  is a move that we are happy to see. White spends a tempo on securing their knight but, in the process, loses valuable time. This move is the most popular at the amateur/club level and in online games. This statistic is a significant incentive to play our suggested quick ...b5-line. Many players on the white side will go for a non-critical reply like 6.a3,  making our life easy.  E@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  is the most dangerous move and slightly different to the alternatives above. We won't be able to generate quick play against e4,  as the pawn is better protected now. We suggest playing  6...Qb6  , trying to force the white knight back to a less active square. This idea gives this line a different feel to A-D above. }
6. Bd3 { We think this is White's best bet for an advantage. } 6... Qb6
{ We already talked about the rationale behind this move. By attacking the d4-knight, we start direct play and try to kick it to a less attractive square. We'll now examine the retreats to b3 and f3,  but also  7.Be3  .  It looks like  7.Nf3  might be the most challenging, but this move is not very popular in practice, and the arising positions are interesting to play.  The most popular moves are  7.Be3  and  7.Nb3  , a more standard retreat square for the d4-knight in a Sicilian. }
7. Nf3 { This move is less popular than the alternatives but challenging. }
7... Qc7
{ Our queen move to b6 was solely motivated by the desire to worsen the position of White's knight. We need to get it back to a safer square and play  7...Qc7  right away.  An interesting alternative is  7...Nc6  , though. }
8. O-O Bb7 9. Re1
{ White develops quickly while our king is still in the middle of the board. }
9... Be7
{ An important move to remember. There are plenty of ways to go wrong here, like  9...Nf6?  10.e5  or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/1bqp1ppp/p3p3/1p6/4P3/2NB1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 b kq - 7 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nc6?  10.a4  b4  11.Nd5!  , when we won't reach move 20, most likely.  The bishop's move to e7 prepares further development and helps to shield our king from knight jumps to d5. }
10. e5
{ White goes for this move most of the time. By advancing the e-pawn, they control the crucial squares d6 and f6,  making our development more difficult.  Instead of the aggressive 10.e5,  White could also play a slower move like  10.Bd2  , when  10...Nc6  is our reply. An interesting point worth mentioning is that  11.a4  b4  12.Nd5  exd5  13.exd5  Nd8  is fine for Black, as we always have Nd8-e6 to plug the e-file.  White does not have to go for 11.a4,  though. Against something slow, ...Be7-c5 and ...Ng8-e7 is a good plan. }
10... f5
{ A surprising move, leading to very unusual positions. We push the f-pawn to control the important central square e4. White can take en passant, but we are happy to see our development speed up after  11.exf6  Nxf6  . We have removed the annoying e-pawn and are ready to castle kingside.  What is the most critical move White can play? }
11. Nd4
{ The best move, according to Stockfish. We think the following line is improbable unless White is extraordinarily well-prepared. }
11... b4 12. Na4
{ After  12.Nce2?  Nc6  , Black is in great shape. Here,  13.c3?  Nxe5  is just good for Black – compared to @@StartFEN@@rn2k1nr/1bqpb1pp/p3p3/4Pp2/1p1N4/2NB4/PPP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 w kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Na4  Nc6  13.c3!  , when we can't take on e5. }
12... Nc6 13. c3
{ Again the strongest move. It's very easy for White to go astray. Here are two examples:  A@@EndBracket@@  13.Nxc6??  Qxc6  is a simple one. We threaten mate, and the knight on a4 is attacked.   B@@EndBracket@@  13.Nf3  is possible but makes less sense in connection with 11.Nd4. When White plays 11.Nd4,  they more or less need to know 13.c3 beforehand. Alright, what happens after 13.Nf3? We play  13...Nh6  , intending ...Nf7. This puts more pressure on e5 and prepares g7-g5. If White takes the h6-knight, we get the open g-file for an attack! }
13... Nh6
{ We suggest this new/untested move, which puts more fuel into the fire. } 14.
Bxh6 gxh6 15. Qh5+ Kd8
{ Wow, what a mess! We decided to stop the trainable here and continue with some sample lines to illustrate the possibilities.  A@@EndBracket@@  16.Qxh6?!  Qa5  17.Qg7  Re8  18.Bc2  bxc3  19.bxc3  Nxd4  20.cxd4  Bc6  is nice for Black, as White's pieces are badly coordinated.   B@@EndBracket@@  16.Rad1  Nxd4  17.cxd4  Rg8  is a razor-sharp position in which the engine suggests the inhuman  18.Bf1  Qc6  19.d5!  Qxa4  20.b3!  Qxa2  21.d6  Rg6  22.dxe7+  Kxe7  , with a small edge for White in this still messy situation. If someone blitzes all these moves out in an online game, you know your cheating complaint will be successful!   C@@EndBracket@@  16.Bf1  is another engine suggestion, based on  16...Nxd4  17.cxd4  Qc6  18.Qd1  , which does not feel very intuitive. After  18...Rg8  Stockfish wants to continue with  19.d5!  , when  19...Qxd5  20.Qxd5  exd5  21.Nb6  Rb8  22.Red1  d4!  looks best. White has the better pawn structure, but our bishops are strong. The comp gives White a small edge, but it took more than twenty perfect moves to get there.  We can conclude that 7.Nf3 is a challenging line. White might be slightly better with perfect play, but we have an exciting and unconventional game. It feels unlikely that White will navigate the complications well, in particular, if they are unprepared. }
