[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Tricky Knights 2.Nf3 a6 3.Nc3"]
[Black "2E | Tricky Knights with 6.Bd3 | White plays 7.Be3 / 8.Qg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. Nc3 b5 4. d4
{ The only critical move.  White may also play the slow move  4.g3  , but this would transpose to play similar to the Closed Sicilian, covered in our chapter on 2.Nc3 a6. }
4... cxd4 { We get an Open Sicilian after all. } 5. Nxd4
{ Black has two sound and logical moves here, 5...e6 and 5...Bb7. The difference between them is subtle. In most cases, we'd reach precisely the same positions, as Black usually needs both moves quickly. Let's examine the difference.  In both cases, the most critical reply is 6.Bd3 @@StartBracket@@more on that later@@EndBracket@@, when  5...e6  6.Bd3  Qb6  is our suggestion. We immediately attack the d4-knight and try to push it away from the centre. If White plays  7.Be3  , the reply  7...Bc5  gives us fair chances.   This idea does not work after  5...Bb7  6.Bd3  Qb6?  7.Be3  , when we can't play the bishop to c5. Black would need to play a different idea on move 6 in this line.  We, however, like the ...Qb6 idea and therefore need to play 5...e6 first. }
5... e6
{ We have already discussed why we prefer starting with this move instead of 5...Bb7. What's next? Our general idea and ideal development scheme to go for is the following:  ➤ Play ...Bb7  ➤ Play ...Nf6 next, if White can't favourably reply e4-e5  ➤ If e4-e5 is a problem, the move ...Qc7 is an excellent way to cover against it  It looks like these moves are very natural, increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn. We don't want to play ...b5-b4 quickly but rather pile up on the e4-pawn to make ...b5-b4 a more profound idea, ideally winning the centre pawn!  White needs to make up their mind about how to develop the pieces. Our idea is to attack the e4-pawn quickly. It is therefore not a surprise that 6.Bd3 is a sensible move for White. In fact, it is the only move that poses a severe theoretical challenge to our opening concept.  Why? The critical point is that after 6.Bd3,  we can't play our ideal moves so quickly. After  6.Bd3  Bb7  7.O-O  the move  7...Nf6?  is answered with  8.e5!  Nd5  9.Nxd5  Bxd5  , when White has many strong ideas, often involving Qg4.  If White does not play 6.Bd3,  however, we will obtain good chances without any particular problems, using a quick ...Bb7 and ...Nf6,  often prepared by ...Qc7.  We'll check some concrete moves in a moment, but we'd like to discuss an additional point first. Our queenside play is much faster than in many other Sicilian setups. We have already played ...a6 and ...b5,  gaining space on this side of the board. This renders a possible queenside castling by White less attractive than in other Sicilian lines, where it is commonplace.   As mentioned, it looks best for White to prioritize kingside castling and support the e4-pawn, which is why 6.Bd3 looks like the most dangerous move. Let's have an overview of White's options.  White's Options  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a way for White to play for queenside castling. The setup Be3/Qd2 and O-O-O,  often accompanied with f3,  is called English Attack and a popular approach in many Sicilian lines, particularly the Najdorf. As mentioned above, we are happy to see White's king on the side of the board where our play has already started.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  is an unpopular but reasonable line for White. Placing the bishop on g2 helps cover the e4-pawn and prepares kingside castling. In some cases, the play can become quite sharp. We exert intense pressure on the e-pawn, which might prompt White to sacrifice material to avoid a passive setup.  C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is similar to 6.g3. White prepares O-O and will often cover the e-pawn with Bf3 later.  D@@EndBracket@@  6.a3  is a move that we are happy to see. White spends a tempo on securing their knight but, in the process, loses valuable time. This move is the most popular at the amateur/club level and in online games. This statistic is a significant incentive to play our suggested quick ...b5-line. Many players on the white side will go for a non-critical reply like 6.a3,  making our life easy.  E@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  is the most dangerous move and slightly different to the alternatives above. We won't be able to generate quick play against e4,  as the pawn is better protected now. We suggest playing  6...Qb6  , trying to force the white knight back to a less active square. This idea gives this line a different feel to A-D above. }
6. Bd3 { We think this is White's best bet for an advantage. } 6... Qb6
{ We already talked about the rationale behind this move. By attacking the d4-knight, we start direct play and try to kick it to a less attractive square. We'll now examine the retreats to b3 and f3,  but also  7.Be3  .  It looks like  7.Nf3  might be the most challenging, but this move is not very popular in practice, and the arising positions are interesting to play.  The most popular moves are  7.Be3  and  7.Nb3  , a more standard retreat square for the d4-knight in a Sicilian. }
7. Be3 { A natural move, covering the attacked knight. } 7... Bc5
{ We need to put more pressure on the d4-knight. It's the only move that makes sense in connection with 6...Qb6. Now White has some options we need to examine. }
8. Qg4
{ A shocking move, but it is a playable option for White. It was discovered in the pre-engine era but is now entirely de-fanged. }
8... Bxd4 { No alternative: we take the piece. } 9. e5
{ That's White's idea. now our bishop on d4 is attacked but at the same time, Qxg7 is threatened, which would win the h8-rook. Now we suggest the sharpest line, leading to crazy tactics.  Black has a simpler alternative in  9...Nc6  10.Qxg7  Bxe5  11.Qxe5  Nxe5  12.Bxb6  Bb7  , which leads to an endgame with equal chances. Our suggestion gives better winning chances but is riskier. }
9... Bxe3 10. Qxg7 Bxf2+
{ We recommend this move, but  10...Nc6  also works well. } 11. Kf1
{ White has to go to f1,  keeping g2 covered.  After  11.Kd1  Bb7  12.Qxh8  Kf8  White has no good move. A fun line is  13.Bxh7  Qd4+  14.Ke2  Qe3+  15.Kf1  Bh4  16.Qxg8+  Ke7  , when our mate threat is deadly. }
11... Bb7
{ A cool solution. We give up the whole kingside to start an attack on White's king! }
12. Qxh8 Kd8 { On the way to c7. } 13. Qxg8+ Kc7
{ After this crazy sequence, we are an exchange down. A key point, however, is that White's position is badly organized. The rooks don't matter now, while our bishops are mighty. }
14. Qxh7 Nc6
{ The move  14...Bd4  also works well. From here, both sides have many options, but our job looks much easier. We'll pick up the e5-pawn @@StartBracket@@...Bd4 is often a good idea@@EndBracket@@, too. }
