{ We need to put more pressure on the d4-knight. It's the only move that makes sense in connection with 6...Qb6. Now White has some options we need to examine. }
8. Be2
{ That's the most likely move to happen.  Sometimes White tries the passive  8.Nce2  , but  8...Nf6  is a good and natural reply. White needs to watch out for ideas like  9.f3??  e5  , when Black wins immediately. }
8... Nc6 { More pressure on d4. } 9. Nxc6
{ White has no choice and needs to take our knight. } 9... Qxc6
{ Not the only move at this point. If you don't mind transposing into an endgame,  9...Bxe3  10.fxe3  dxc6  11.Qd4  Qxd4  12.exd4  e5  is an alternative. White is probably slightly better, but it is not causing concern. Our recommended move is a bit more combative. }
10. Qd2
{ White has some alternatives here, of course. However, the type of position will be similar in most cases, for example, after  10.Bxc5  Qxc5  our development scheme is the same as after 10.Qd2 – the natural moves ...Bb7 and ...Ne7,  avoiding e4-e5 pawn pushes. }
10... Ne7 { We can't play  10...Nf6  due to e4-e5,  again. } 11. a3
{ White is worried about ...b5-b4 and stops it. } 11... Bxe3 12. Qxe3 O-O
{ We have reached an interesting and slightly unusual position. An idea worth noting is playing ...f5!? in some situations, which rarely happens in a Sicilian Defence. }
