h in many Sicilian lines, particularly the Najdorf. As mentioned above, we are happy to see White's king on the side of the board where our play has already started.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  is an unpopular but reasonable line for White. Placing the bishop on g2 helps cover the e4-pawn and prepares kingside castling. In some cases, the play can become quite sharp. We exert intense pressure on the e-pawn, which might prompt White to sacrifice material to avoid a passive setup.  C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is similar to 6.g3. White prepares O-O and will often cover the e-pawn with Bf3 later.  D@@EndBracket@@  6.a3  is a move that we are happy to see. White spends a tempo on securing their knight but, in the process, loses valuable time. This move is the most popular at the amateur/club level and in online games. This statistic is a significant incentive to play our suggested quick ...b5-line. Many players on the white side will go for a non-critical reply like 6.a3,  making our life easy.  E@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  is the most dangerous move and slightly different to the alternatives above. We won't be able to generate quick play against e4,  as the pawn is better protected now. We suggest playing  6...Qb6  , trying to force the white knight back to a less active square. This idea gives this line a different feel to A-D above. }
6. Bd3 { We think this is White's best bet for an advantage. } 6... Qb6
{ We already talked about the rationale behind this move. By attacking the d4-knight, we start direct play and try to kick it to a less attractive square. We'll now examine the retreats to b3 and f3,  but also  7.Be3  .  It looks like  7.Nf3  might be the most challenging, but this move is not very popular in practice, and the arising positions are interesting to play.  The most popular moves are  7.Be3  and  7.Nb3  , a more standard retreat square for the d4-knight in a Sicilian. }
7. Nb3
{ White retreats to b3, a more common square than f3 for the knight in a Sicilian. Often, White wants to use the f-pawn later, as we will see in our main line. }
7... Qc7
{ It is essential to play this move first! If you start with  7...Bb7?  , White has  8.a4  b4  9.a5!  Qc7  10.Na4  , when Black's position is on the brink of collapse. }
8. O-O
{ Now  8.a4  b4  is fine for Black, as White has to move the knight to a passive square. }
8... Bb7
{ Our natural development of the bishop. White has a range of options now; let's get an overview.  A@@EndBracket@@  9.f4  is the most aggressive move, preparing the move e4-e5 in reply to ...Nf6. We suggest the move  9...b4  , followed by ...Nf6.   B@@EndBracket@@  9.Be3  completes White's development and is often combined with f2-f4,  usually played right on the next move. As 9.Be3 does not threaten e4-e5 in reply to our knight jump, we advise starting with  9...Nf6  against it.   C@@EndBracket@@  9.Re1  is a different way to prepare e4-e5 and discourage our knight development. We have a cool reply in  9...Bd6!?  , though, an idea we have already examined in the sideline 6.a3.   D@@EndBracket@@  9.Qe2  follows a similar idea as  9.Re1  , planning to answer  9...Nf6?  with 10.e5. We think it's best to play  9...b4  , as White can't retreat to e2 and needs to go to less attractive squares.  On a general note: All these lines are very sharp and promise an exciting fight. In many cases, White struggles to find the best moves in practice, which is underlined by Black's excellent score. If you play the Sicilian, you want an uncompromising fight! }
9. Be3
{ White develops the last minor piece, which does not look too threatening. However, there is more to 9.Be3 than routinely mobilizing this piece. The idea will become clearer on the next move. }
9... Nf6
{ A natural move, developing and putting more pressure on the e-pawn. White now has to reckon with ...b4, attacking a crucial defender of the pawn. }
10. f4
{ This is the only critical move. White understands that after 10.f4 Black can't easily play  10...b4?!  , as  11.Na4  threatens Nb6,  which is extremely annoying. It turns out that Black has no fully satisfactory reply to the knight jump. Therefore, we need to avoid 10.f4 b4?! and go for a more inventive solution.   Before we continue, a word about moves other than 10.f4: There is not much to be concerned about. White could play a slow move like  10.a3  or  10.f3  , but without any e4-e5 ideas White's play lacks punch. We can continue with our development undisturbed, playing ...Be7,  and then decide about the b8-knight. Both ...Nc6 and ...d6,  followed by ...Nd7-c5 comes into consideration. }
10... h5
{ We like this aggressive move. White had e4-e5 in mind, which we can answer with ...Ng4 now. Before we look at 11...h5 more, let's look at some less convincing alternatives. It's helpful here, as we'll understand some key ideas better.  A@@EndBracket@@  10...b4?!  11.Na4  Nxe4  12.Nb6  or the more computerish  12.Qe2  is much better for White. Black can't play @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/1bqp1ppp/p3pn2/8/Np2PP2/1N1BB3/PPP3PP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bxe4  12.Bxe4  Nxe4  13.Qd4!  f5  14.Nb6  Ra7  15.Nd5  , either.   B@@EndBracket@@  10...d6?!  looks like a good move to stop White's pawn push, but a closer look reveals that it fails in that regard.  11.e5!  dxe5  12.fxe5  Qxe5  13.Bf4  Qh5  14.Be2  Qg6  15.Bf3  is great for White. There are some possible deviations along the way, but Black is much worse everywhere.   C@@EndBracket@@  10...Be7  is not bad, but White is somewhat better after  11.e5  Nd5  12.Nxd5  Bxd5  13.c4  , when the position opens up.   We suggest  10...h5  , which sets the most problems for White. We'll examine  11.h3  and  11.Qe2  now, which looks like the most challenging try. }
11. h3
{ White doesn't want to worry about ...Ng4, but inserting the moves ...h5 and h3 have changed some tactical details. We can now play a move that was dubious on move 10. }
11... b4
{ Why does this work now? A key tactic has changed compared to 10...b4?!, which was dubious. }
12. Na4 Bxe4
{ Here,  12...Nxe4?  still fails to  13.Nb6  , but the bishop capture works! }
13. Bxe4 Nxe4
{ This is the moment to show the key difference to @@StartFEN@@rn2kb1r/1bqp1ppp/p3pn2/1p6/4PP2/1NNBB3/PPP3PP/R2Q1RK1 b kq f3 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...b4?!  11.Na4  Bxe4  12.Bxe4  Nxe4  , when  13.Qd4!  is huge for White.   Here,  14.Qd4??  is a blunder due to  14...Ng3!  , highlighting the difference! }
14. Qf3 { This looks best. As mentioned,  14.Qd4??  Ng3!  wins for Black. }
14... f5
{ We cover the knight and stop White's f-pawn.  It's also possible to play  14...d5  , when  15.f5  Bd6  leads to a messy position. Stockfish slightly prefers White, but it's very messy.   After our suggestion  14...f5  , the situation remains complicated. White will probably play  15.Nac5  , getting the offside knight into the game. We suggest  15...Bxc5  16.Nxc5  Qc6  , when anything can happen. Stockfish evaluates the game as about equal, but we certainly can't call it drawish! }
