9. Re1
{ White does not move the f-pawn but rather wants to support a possible e4-e5 push with the rook. If you don't know the best reply, this move is surprisingly difficult to handle for Black. The only correct move is far from obvious. }
9... Bd6
{ A closer inspection shows that this is the only good move! We need to catch up in development, and the bishop move wins a crucial tempo on the h-pawn. At the same time, it prevents e4-e5.  Other moves don't work, as lines like  9...d6?  10.a4  b4  11.Na2  Nc6  12.Bd2  a5  13.c3  or @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/1bqp1ppp/p3p3/1p6/4P3/1NNB4/PPP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 b kq - 7 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nf6?  10.e5  Nd5  11.Nxd5  Bxd5  12.a4  demonstrate. In these scenarios, White is tearing down the queenside.   If we'd play  9...b4?  , the crushing  10.Nd5!  would hit us. }
