15... Rc8
{ We get the last piece into play and remove the rook from the long diagonal. This might be relevant in the tactical skirmishes that are ahead. We decided to cut the trainable here, as it's getting very deep. Here's an overview of some sample lines.  A@@EndBracket@@  16.Qe2  Ng6  17.e5?  hxg3  18.hxg3  Bxg2  19.Kxg2  Qb7+  20.f3  Bxe5  21.Bxe5  Ng4  is great for Black.   B@@EndBracket@@  16.Qe2  Ng6  17.Rad1  hxg3  18.hxg3  Bxg3!  19.fxg3  Qxg3  is tricky for White to defend. They can manage with perfect play but may easily stumble, for example, with  20.Qf2  Qh2+  21.Kf1  Ng4  22.Qd2  O-O!  when ...f5 is looming!  C@@EndBracket@@  16.Qe2  Ng6  17.Nd2  Be5  18.Bxe5  Nxe5  also gives Black enough compensation. The comp suggests the mysterious  19.Rac1!?  now, when  19...Nfg4  20.h3  hxg3!  21.hxg4  gxf2+  22.Kxf2  Rh4  gives us a strong attack. The engine eval is again 0.00, but the board is on fire.  The pawn sacrifice is fascinating to analyze but not very likely to occur in practice. If you like, you can go even deeper on your own. It's lots of fun to check the possibilities. }
