{ Black has two sound and logical moves here, 5...e6 and 5...Bb7. The difference between them is subtle. In most cases, we'd reach precisely the same positions, as Black usually needs both moves quickly. Let's examine the difference.  In both cases, the most critical reply is 6.Bd3 @@StartBracket@@more on that later@@EndBracket@@, when  5...e6  6.Bd3  Qb6  is our suggestion. We immediately attack the d4-knight and try to push it away from the centre. If White plays  7.Be3  , the reply  7...Bc5  gives us fair chances.   This idea does not work after  5...Bb7  6.Bd3  Qb6?  7.Be3  , when we can't play the bishop to c5. Black would need to play a different idea on move 6 in this line.  We, however, like the ...Qb6 idea and therefore need to play 5...e6 first. }
5... e6
{ We have already discussed why we prefer starting with this move instead of 5...Bb7. What's next? Our general idea and ideal development scheme to go for is the following:  ➤ Play ...Bb7  ➤ Play ...Nf6 next, if White can't favourably reply e4-e5  ➤ If e4-e5 is a problem, the move ...Qc7 is an excellent way to cover against it  It looks like these moves are very natural, increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn. We don't want to play ...b5-b4 quickly but rather pile up on the e4-pawn to make ...b5-b4 a more profound idea, ideally winning the centre pawn!  White needs to make up their mind about how to develop the pieces. Our idea is to attack the e4-pawn quickly. It is therefore not a surprise that 6.Bd3 is a sensible move for White. In fact, it is the only move that poses a severe theoretical challenge to our opening concept.  Why? The critical point is that after 6.Bd3,  we can't play our ideal moves so quickly. After  6.Bd3  Bb7  7.O-O  the move  7...Nf6?  is answered with  8.e5!  Nd5  9.Nxd5  Bxd5  , when White has many strong ideas, often involving Qg4.  If White does not play 6.Bd3,  however, we will obtain good chances without any particular problems, using a quick ...Bb7 and ...Nf6,  often prepared by ...Qc7.  We'll check some concrete moves in a moment, but we'd like to discuss an additional point first. Our queenside play is much faster than in many other Sicilian setups. We have already played ...a6 and ...b5,  gaining space on this side of the board. This renders a possible queenside castling by White less attractive than in other Sicilian lines, where it is commonplace.   As mentioned, it looks best for White to prioritize kingside castling and support the e4-pawn, which is why 6.Bd3 looks like the most dangerous move. Let's have an overview of White's options.  White's Options  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a way for White to play for queenside castling. The setup Be3/Qd2 and O-O-O,  often accompanied with f3,  is called English Attack and a popular approach in many Sicilian lines, particularly the Najdorf. As mentioned above, we are happy to see White's king on the side of the board where our play has already started.  B@@EndBracket@@  6.g3  is an unpopular but reasonable line for White. Placing the bishop on g2 helps cover the e4-pawn and prepares kingside castling. In some cases, the play can become quite sharp. We exert intense pressure on the e-pawn, which might prompt White to sacrifice material to avoid a passive setup.  C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is similar to 6.g3. White prepares O-O and will often cover the e-pawn with Bf3 later.  D@@EndBracket@@  6.a3  is a move that we are happy to see. White spends a tempo on securing their knight but, in the process, loses valuable time. This move is the most popular at the amateur/club level and in online games. This statistic is a significant incentive to play our suggested quick ...b5-line. Many players on the white side will go for a non-critical reply like 6.a3,  making our life easy.  E@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  is the most dangerous move and slightly different to the alternatives above. We won't be able to generate quick play against e4,  as the pawn is better protected now. We suggest playing  6...Qb6  , trying to force the white knight back to a less active square. This idea gives this line a different feel to A-D above. }
6. Bd3 { We think this is White's best bet for an advantage. } 6... Qb6
{ We already talked about the rationale behind this move. By attacking the d4-knight, we start direct play and try to kick it to a less attractive square. We'll now examine the retreats to b3 and f3,  but also  7.Be3  .  It looks like  7.Nf3  might be the most challenging, but this move is not very popular in practice, and the arising positions are interesting to play.  The most popular moves are  7.Be3  and  7.Nb3  , a more standard retreat square for the d4-knight in a Sicilian. }
7. Nb3
{ White retreats to b3, a more common square than f3 for the knight in a Sicilian. Often, White wants to use the f-pawn later, as we will see in our main line. }
7... Qc7
{ It is essential to play this move first! If you start with  7...Bb7?  , White has  8.a4  b4  9.a5!  Qc7  10.Na4  , when Black's position is on the brink of collapse. }
8. O-O
{ Now  8.a4  b4  is fine for Black, as White has to move the knight to a passive square. }
8... Bb7
{ Our natural development of the bishop. White has a range of options now; let's get an overview.  A@@EndBracket@@  9.f4  is the most aggressive move, preparing the move e4-e5 in reply to ...Nf6. We suggest the move  9...b4  , followed by ...Nf6.   B@@EndBracket@@  9.Be3  completes White's development and is often combined with f2-f4,  usually played right on the next move. As 9.Be3 does not threaten e4-e5 in reply to our knight jump, we advise starting with  9...Nf6  against it.   C@@EndBracket@@  9.Re1  is a different way to prepare e4-e5 and discourage our knight development. We have a cool reply in  9...Bd6!?  , though, an idea we have already examined in the sideline 6.a3.   D@@EndBracket@@  9.Qe2  follows a similar idea as  9.Re1  , planning to answer  9...Nf6?  with 10.e5. We think it's best to play  9...b4  , as White can't retreat to e2 and needs to go to less attractive squares.  On a general note: All these lines are very sharp and promise an exciting fight. In many cases, White struggles to find the best moves in practice, which is underlined by Black's excellent score. If you play the Sicilian, you want an uncompromising fight! }
9. Qe2
{ A flexible move that accomplishes two things.  1@@EndBracket@@ White is not yet committing to the f-pawn push but still keeps this option. This differs from  9.Re1  when White focuses on piece play.   2@@EndBracket@@ White prepares to answer  9...Nf6?  with  10.e5  Nd5  11.Nxd5  Bxd5  12.a4  , when our queenside falls apart.  How do you respond to the move? What is the drawback? }
9... b4
{ We suggest this reply, highlighting a weakness of 9.Qe2: the knight can't retreat to e2 but has to go to a less attractive square.  Black does not have many good alternatives. As already mentioned,  9...Nf6?  10.e5  has to be avoided.   Playing  9...d6?!  is also wrong due to  10.a4  b4  11.Na2  , when the b-pawn is vulnerable.   The only suitable alternative to 9...b4 we can see is the sophisticated move  9...Be7  , which delays the move ...b4 for a moment. The position is similar to our choice 9...b4. }
10. Nd1
{ White's main move here.  Against  10.Nb1  , we'd play similarly as against 10.Nd1: Place the knights on c6 and f6,  play ...Be7 and often ...a5. }
10... Nc6
{ We like this move order. White's d3-bishop only has a few squares available, which might encourage us to play ...Ne5. This is relevant if White plays  11.c3  now when  11...Ne5  12.Bc2?  a5  is excellent for us. }
11. f4
{ Very logical play. White stops any ...Ne5 ideas and opens the f2-square for the knight in some lines. Now we need to consider what move order to choose.  We want to develop our knight to f6, but is it the right moment to do it now? Other moves we'll likely need are ...Be7 and ...a5, which lend support to our pawn and prepare ...a4 to push White's knight back. }
11... a5
{ We think this is the best move to start with.  It's instructive to see that  11...Nf6?!  is imprecise due to  12.e5  Nd5  13.Ne3  , when White manages to activate their passive piece. We'd have nothing better than to trade on e3 when White happily goes for  13...Nxe3  14.Bxe3  to speed up development.   Better moves are  11...a5  , or  11...Be7  , which may lead to the same positions.  We think playing the a-pawn first is a bit more flexible, as we might be able to develop the bishop to a different square than e7. We'll examine a line that features ...a4,  followed by ...Bc5+,  which can be an attractive option. }
12. Be3
{ White not only develops the bishop but also takes note of our idea  12...a4  , which now can be answered with  13.Nc5  .   Instead of 12.Be3,  White has other options. One interesting idea is  12.c3  , when we suggest  12...bxc3  13.Nxc3  a4  14.Nb5  Qb8  15.Nd2  Bc5+  , showing a point of not playing ...Be7 earlier. The resulting position is very sharp – we have good play on the queenside, but are not castled yet. }
12... Nf6
{ A good moment for the knight move. We don't fear  13.e5  now, as  13...Nd5  hits White's bishop – compared to @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/1bqp1ppp/p1n1p3/8/1p2PP2/1N1B4/PPP1Q1PP/R1BN1RK1 b kq f3 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nf6?!  12.e5  Nd5  , when  13.Ne3  is annoying.   Now, after  12...Nf6  , White has a range of ideas. They can start playing on the queenside immediately or shift attention to the kingside, hoping that we'll castle soon. }
13. c3
{ White opens up the queenside.  A different approach is the engine suggestion of  13.a4!?  , which does not look very intuitive but is interesting. They stop our a-pawn and then focus on the kingside. The following line leads to complex play:   13...Be7  14.Rf3  e5!  @@StartBracket@@stopping e4-e5@@EndBracket@@  15.f5  d5  , when anything can happen. White has gained ground on the kingside, but we have play in the centre. }
13... Be7 { The move  13...a4  is a reasonable alternative. } 14. Rc1 O-O
{ It's a perfect moment to take stock. We have castled kingside and reached a position with exciting play and equal chances.  A way to continue is  15.Nc5  bxc3  16.Rxc3  Rfc8  17.Nf2  d5  18.e5  Nd7  , when we challenge White's intruder on c5. White can take the bishop, but we don't mind trading it for White's strongest piece. }
