{ White usually chooses this move, keeping the knight close to the centre.  Instead,  10.Na4??  is a huge blunder due to  10...Qc6  when the knight is trapped. For example,  11.Na5  Qxa4  12.Nxb7  Qc6  13.Na5  Qc5+  .   A much better move is  10.Nb1  , when Black has a choice of good replies that lead to equal chances. The engine likes  10...a5  , but  10...Nc6  or  10...Nf6  are fine, too.  The main move, 10.Ne2 poses more problems. }
10... Nf6
{ Now is a good time to attack the e-pawn. Compared to the earlier @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/1bqp1ppp/p3p3/1p6/4PP2/1NNB4/PPP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq f3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nf6  10.e5  Nd5  11.Ne4  , we have ensured that White can't get their knight to e4 easily. Now White needs to decide what to do about the attacked e-pawn. In practice, this question is not easy to answer, and often White goes wrong. }
11. e5
{ The only good move, but not an easy decision. White gains space but at the same time allows our knight to jump to the attractive d5-square. Our b7-bishop is looking strong, too.  Stockfish gives White a small advantage after 11.e5, but we'll see that this assessment means little – we're in for a complicated fight. }
11... Nd5
{ We have reached a very complex position, typical of the non-symmetrical struggles of the Sicilian. Here White's most frequently played move is  12.Ng3  , which we'll examine as our main line.  However, this move does not seem to follow the best possible play, as indicated by Stockfish. In practice, the engine lines are less likely to happen, but we need to be ready. The engine suggestion is the unintuitive move  12.Kh1  , which is difficult to understand at first. We'll have a closer look now. }
12. Kh1
{ This is best, according to Stockfish. We think the move is unlikely to happen in practice, but it is interesting to figure out what the engine is after. It is a waiting move to play c2-c4 next.  It was possible to play  12.c4  immediately when  12...bxc3  13.Nxc3  Nxc3  14.bxc3  Nc6  15.Rb1  Ne7!?  seems to be best. Black plans ...Bd5-c4 or ...Nf5,  according to circumstances. We'll see more of the ...Ne7 manoeuvre in a minute. }
12... Nc6 { A natural choice, developing the knight. } 13. c4 bxc3 14. bxc3
{ White has to avoid  14.Nxc3?  Ncb4  , which gives us great play.  Let's talk about the pawn structure for a moment. We mentioned that White rarely goes for a c4-based plan, but usually plays 12.Ng3. This preference is because assessing the current pawn structure is difficult. White's c-pawn is isolated, and moving it forward gives Black access to the b4-square.  A closer look, helped by the computer, reveals that Black's job is tough here. There only seems to be one good plan, which is not very obvious. }
14... Nce7
{ It looks odd to move the knight again, but the following line demonstrates a crucial point:  14...Be7?!  15.c4  Ndb4  16.Be4  , and now you see that our b4-knight has no square to retreat to. The threat a3 is impossible to meet satisfactorily, as  16...a5  17.a3  Na6  18.Nc3  shows – White is headed for b5,  invading our queenside.  The point of 14...Nce7 is regrouping the knight to g6 first. The knight is a good defender on the kingside and often gets active with ...Nh4 later. At the same time, we avoid the traffic jam on the queenside. }
15. c4
{ The alternative  15.Bd2  Ng6  16.Qe1  Rb8  also leads to complicated play. A crucial tactical point is  17.c4?!  Nb4!  , which demonstrates the point of 16...Rb8. }
15... Nb4 16. Bb1 Ng6
{ We complete our knight tour. Grabbing the pawn is far too risky:  16...Qxc4?  17.Na5  Qb5  18.Nxb7  Qxb7  19.Ng3  gives White a strong attack.   After our suggestion  16...Ng6  , the game is very complex. Stockfish assesses White's chances as slightly better, but a sample line like  17.Ng3  Nh4  18.Ne4  a5  gives Black chances, too. White's pawn structure remains compromised, and our h4-knight is an irritating piece for our opponent. }
