[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Maroczy Setup 2.Nf3 a6 3.c4"]
[Black "3A | Maroczy Setup with 4.Nc3 |"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. c4 Nc6 4. Nc3
{ White often plays this move in response to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq c3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  , but our third move makes a substantial difference. }
4... e5
{ A crucial point of our move order 3...Nc6. White only had one opportunity to open the centre @@StartBracket@@4.d4!@@EndBracket@@, and now it is stopped. We play 4...e5,  permanently blocking the centre.  Isn't this approach boring, leading to a closed and symmetrical game? Both sides have played the moves c4/e4 and ...c5/...e5,  so it looks like not much is going on. There is, however, an important difference: White has played the move Nf3,  while we have played ...a6.  What's more useful? At first, you may think the knight move should be more beneficial, but this is not the case. Why? Looking at the blocked centre, it becomes clear that progress needs to feature pawn play on the flanks. There are two possible pawn levers for both sides: playing the b-pawn or playing the f-pawn, trying to gain space and attack the opponent's centre.  Our move ...a6 is preparation for ...b5,  while White's knight move hinders their progress on the kingside. We can still prepare ...f5 by playing ...g6 and ...Nge7!,  while White's f-pawn is blocked by their knight. This drawback is enough to give Black an easy game and good chances in practice.  A fun fact to add: After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.c4  Nc6  4.Nc3  one of Black's best moves is  4...e5  – we are a full tempo up on this line 😊 }
5. d3
{ White's main decision is between playing their bishop to e2 or going for a kingside fianchetto. We'll talk about both options on the next move, but they could already go for  5.Be2  or  5.g3  here. Move orders are less relevant, as our setup will be the same: we play ...d6 next and then see how to continue. }
5... d6 6. g3
{ Or  6.Be2  , which does not make a fundamental difference. We have the same choice as after 6.g3: continue with kingside development or go for an early queenside play with  6...Rb8  . We suggest this approach, which does not yet commit to a setup on the kingside.  Let's look at a similar situation after 6.g3 now. }
6... Rb8
{ We suggest this rare but strong move. Why not try to make something out of the move ...a6 quickly? The centre is closed, so we don't need to hurry with kingside development.  That said,  6...g6  is a very reasonable alternative, as is a development scheme based on  6...Nf6  and ...Be7. The choice between them is mostly a matter of taste. }
7. Bg2
{ White could play  7.a4  to stop our plan but forfeited their own a3 and b4 pawn lever option. In this case, we happily switch to play on the kingside, starting with  7...g6  . Ideally, we'd like to play ...Bg7,  ...Nge7,  ...O-O and ...f5!,  gaining space. }
7... b5
{ Here we go. A nice accomplishment, putting the early ...a6 to good use. } 8.
O-O
{ Now we reach an important moment. How to develop the kingside? We spent some time on the queenside expansion, which led to a serious lag in development. Can we play the slow  8...g6  here, or should we rather play  8...Nf6  , intending ...Be7 and ...O-O next? }
8... Nf6
{ This is best. Here's why  8...g6?  is bad:  9.cxb5  axb5  10.b4!!  Nxb4  11.d4!  exd4  12.Nxd4  , when  12...cxd4  13.Qxd4  wins for White. Of course, this line is not easy to find for a human, but what a great tactical sequence!  It's interesting to return briefly to the line @@StartFEN@@1rbqkbnr/1p3ppp/p1np4/2p1p3/2P1P3/2NP1NP1/PP3P1P/R1BQKB1R w KQk - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.a4  , when  7...g6  is possible. The move a4 has robbed White of these tactical options.   We have to conclude that instead of 8...g6?,  emphasizing development with  8...Nf6  is much better. Now it's not easy to find a way forward for White. They are 'too late' on the queenside – preparing kingside play takes time and will often backfire. We'll check  9.Nh4  now to demonstrate this point.  It's probably best for White to play something modest instead, like  9.h3  , for example. We'll continue ...Be7,  ...O-O and often ...Nd4,  centralizing our knight. }
9. Nh4 { Going for the pawn push f2-f4, but also Nf5. } 9... g6
{ We stop Nf5 – do we need to worry about f2-f4, though? } 10. f4 exf4
{ Instructive! We don't allow further space gain and ensure that our bishop on g7 will enjoy an open diagonal. }
11. gxf4
{ Or  11.Bxf4  Bg7  , when we have excellent control of the central dark squares. }
11... Nd4
{ We have to avoid  11...Bg7??  12.e5!  .   After the much better move  11...Nd4  , we are in good shape, though. We'll complete our kingside development with ...Bg7 and ...O-O and have chances on the dark central squares and the queenside. }
