[Black "3B | Maroczy Setup with 4.d4 | White plays 6.Nxc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. c4 Nc6 4. d4
{ The only challenging move. Otherwise, we push ...e5 and stop White from opening the centre. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5
{ That's the idea of playing 3...Nc6. We don't go for a slow setup but rather play a sharp central strike. White needs to move their central knight, but where?  It's interesting to compare this position to the Kalashnikov Sicilian, which occurs after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  . In the Kalashnikov, the only critical move is  5.Nb5  , trying to play ...Nd6+.   This idea is off the table in our O'Kelly version, as we have ...a6 already played. On the other hand, White has the move  6.Nf5  in our line, with similar ideas. This knight jump is the only critical line and the main focus of the current chapter.  If White plays a different move, we get the opportunity to develop our f8-bishop actively to c5 or b4. The position type after the various knight retreats @@StartBracket@@6.Nc2,  6.Nb3 and 6.Nf3@@EndBracket@@ is quite similar. We'll have a look at  6.Nc2  and  6.Nb3  , illustrating the key ideas. If White chooses one of these moves, it's enough to know a setup and general plans.  However, after the critical  6.Nf5  we have no good slow option and need to start concrete, tactical play. This is based on the move  6...d5!  , which will often catch your opponents by surprise. The complications after 6...d5 are less based on general considerations but tactics. Instead of  6...d5  , Black has also tried  6...d6  , but this move is too passive for our taste.  Let's check all the knight moves, one by one. }
6. Nxc6
{ White takes our knight, a welcome sight. We are happy about the capture, as we no longer have to worry about the d5-square. But how to recapture? }
6... dxc6
{ We decided to cover the harmless move 6.Nxc6 because we wanted to discuss this instructive moment. Why do we allow the queen to trade and give up castling rights? There are two reasons:  Firstly, we have a good position after the queen trade, as we'll examine in a moment. Secondly, our job after  6...bxc6  7.Be3  is not so easy, as we don't manage to develop our bishop to c5. Black's position is not terrible but considerably more difficult to handle than after our suggestion 6...dxc6. }
7. Qxd8+
{ We can't castle after the queen trade, but it is only a minor issue. With queens off the board, our king is safe in the middle of the board. }
7... Kxd8
{ So, why is Black in good shape here? White's pawn structure is not ideal, as the square d4 is permanently weak. At the same time, the f1-bishop is looking at its pawns e4 and c4. In the long run, it is in danger of becoming a 'bad bishop'.  On the other hand, our bishop can still be developed to c5 or b4, using it actively. Here's a sample line to show this crucial idea. }
8. Be3
{ White stops ...Bc5, a very logical move. How do we get our bishop to c5 now? This won't be easy, but it is not the only way to develop this piece. }
8... Nf6 { We get the knight out first. } 9. Nc3
{ White will likely develop with Nc3, Be2 and f2-f3, the order may vary. After the queen trade, the focus shifts to correct piece placement instead of precise move orders. }
9... Kc7
{ We suggest this move, placing the king on a safe square on the seventh rank. This makes it easier to connect the rooks. The way to develop is to place the bishops on e6 and b4. }
10. Be2 Bb4 { A good move, but  10...Be6  is equally strong. } 11. f3
{ White covers the e-pawn. } 11... Be6
{ We have completed our setup. Note that we can take on c3 to double White's pawns, but the manoeuvre ...Nd7 and ...Bc5 is attractive, too.  A dream scenario for us: reach an endgame with our knight against White's light-square bishop. Our knight would be fantastic on d4, occupying the central square without any worry in the world of being attacked. }
