6. Nb3
{ Compared to the knight retreats to c2 and f3,  White keeps control of the c5-square. Thus we need a different spot for our bishop. The solution is simple: just go for the b4-square instead.  Checking now @@StartBracket@@  6...Bb4+  @@EndBracket@@ is possible, but starting with  6...Nf6  is a natural choice in line with our move order against 6.Nc2. }
6... Nf6
{ We attack e4 first. As mentioned, starting with  6...Bb4+  is a good alternative.   Now we examine  6...Nf6  7.Nc3  and  7.f3  – they need to be handled differently, as we'll see. }
7. f3
{ A less popular way of covering the e-pawn, compared to  7.Nc3  . We examine it because there is a crucial difference between White playing f3 and avoiding the move. The key point arises on move  8. }
7... Bb4+
{ Our bishop belongs to b4,  no doubt. That being said,  7...a5!?  is a good option, too. }
8. Nc3
{ We have reached a position that may also occur via the move order @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/2P1P3/1N6/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nc3  Bb4  8.f3  . White is not afraid of the doubled pawn and invites the capture on c3. Should we accept the invite?   Before we answer this crucial question, a word about  8.Bd2  . We should answer this move with  8...a5!  , when  9.Bxb4  axb4  gives us good chances. We'll see more of the ...a5 idea... now! }
8... a5
{ It is essential to avoid  8...Bxc3?  9.bxc3  , as White's threat of Ba3 is unstoppable. We have no good way to continue – we are dead on the dark squares! It sounds like the next Netflix banger @@StartBracket@@The Queen's Gambit 2 – Dead on the Dark Squares@@EndBracket@@, but please avoid getting it on the board!  A side note: There is the following line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  6.Nb3  Bb4  7.f3  , when we need to avoid the capture. This could help remember when to avoid the capture @@StartBracket@@the Nb3 and f3 combo is happening in both@@EndBracket@@.   OK, we have established what NOT to play. Much better than taking is the move  8...a5!  , directly starting an attack on the queenside. We plan ...a5-a4-a3,  destabilizing White's knight. }
9. a3
{ This is not great, but we'd like to establish why.  White's best move, according to the comp, is the extremely ugly  9.a4  – unlikely to happen in a game between humans. White weakens the dark squares by combining pawns on e4,  c4 and a4.  After 9.a4,  we should complete development with ...d6,  ...Be6 and ...O-O,  still avoiding the capture on c3. A better idea is a later ...Nf6-d7-c5,  transferring the knight to the queenside. }
9... Bxc3+
{ Now we must take the knight, but it's a different story now, compared to the situation on the previous move - Ba3 is off the table here. }
10. bxc3 a4
{ The final move to know. After White's reply  11.Nd2  we are fine with many moves, like  11...d6  ,  11...Qa5  or  11...O-O  .  The crucial point to remember about the line 6.Nb3 combined with f3 is: don't take on c3,  but play ...a5! instead. }
