{ We have regained our pawn, but what about the e5-pawn? White can indeed take it, but it's nothing to worry about, as we'll see in a minute.  There also is  13.Be4  to check, when  13...Nf6!  is leading to interesting complications. White wins b7 but we'll get good play for the material.   White's most challenging move is  13.Nxd5  , which will be our main focus. }
13. Be4 { This move is not popular but demands a precise response. } 13... Nf6
{ The only good reply. We give up the b-pawn, but get excellent compensation. }
14. Bxb7 Ra7
{ We want to keep the a-pawn and activate the rook along the seventh rank. }
15. Bf3 Rd7
{ We have good play for the pawn. It is difficult for White to coordinate their undeveloped pieces, as two sample variations show.  A@@EndBracket@@  16.Rxe5??  Nc6  is a simple affair.   B@@EndBracket@@  16.Bg5  returns the pawn for development after  16...Nxf5  17.Qa4  Nd4  , but White still needs to be careful, as our centralized knight is so strong. }
