[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Maroczy Setup 2.Nf3 a6 3.c4"]
[Black "3B | Maroczy Setup with 4.d4 | White plays 6.Nf5 / 10.Bd3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. c4 Nc6 4. d4
{ The only challenging move. Otherwise, we push ...e5 and stop White from opening the centre. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5
{ That's the idea of playing 3...Nc6. We don't go for a slow setup but rather play a sharp central strike. White needs to move their central knight, but where?  It's interesting to compare this position to the Kalashnikov Sicilian, which occurs after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  . In the Kalashnikov, the only critical move is  5.Nb5  , trying to play ...Nd6+.   This idea is off the table in our O'Kelly version, as we have ...a6 already played. On the other hand, White has the move  6.Nf5  in our line, with similar ideas. This knight jump is the only critical line and the main focus of the current chapter.  If White plays a different move, we get the opportunity to develop our f8-bishop actively to c5 or b4. The position type after the various knight retreats @@StartBracket@@6.Nc2,  6.Nb3 and 6.Nf3@@EndBracket@@ is quite similar. We'll have a look at  6.Nc2  and  6.Nb3  , illustrating the key ideas. If White chooses one of these moves, it's enough to know a setup and general plans.  However, after the critical  6.Nf5  we have no good slow option and need to start concrete, tactical play. This is based on the move  6...d5!  , which will often catch your opponents by surprise. The complications after 6...d5 are less based on general considerations but tactics. Instead of  6...d5  , Black has also tried  6...d6  , but this move is too passive for our taste.  Let's check all the knight moves, one by one. }
6. Nf5
{ The knight jump forward is the only challenge. Just as in the Kalashnikov or Sveshnikov, White aims at the d6-square. }
6... d5
{ 'Yiehaaa!' In over the board Chess, you really should not shout during the game, but this is the kind of move that makes you want to!  This move might come as a shock to your opponent. It seems impossible, as White can capture the d5-pawn in three ways. However, only one is good and needs deeper investigation: the move  7.cxd5  , which is the subject of the rest of this chapter. What about the other captures?   A@@EndBracket@@  7.exd5?  is as bad as it looks after  7...Bxf5  8.dxc6  Qxd1+  9.Kxd1  bxc6  , when White's king is exposed and their position seriously weakened by the move of the c-pawn. We'll get a huge attack by simple development.   B@@EndBracket@@  7.Qxd5?!  is not as bad as A above, but still a welcome sight for us. After  7...Bxf5  8.Qxd8+  Rxd8  9.exf5  Nb4  , we are attacking White's king as early as move nine.  Let's examine White's best move now, taking with the c-pawn. }
7. cxd5 { The only good move for White and almost exclusively played. } 7...
Bxf5 { The idea of 6...d5! – we remove White's dangerous knight. } 8. exf5
{ Again, White's only good move, as  8.dxc6?  Qxd1+  9.Kxd1  Bxe4  10.cxb7  Bxb7  is great for Black. What is White's king doing on d1,  besides being an easy target for us? }
8... Nd4
{ We jump on this great central square and now attack the d-pawn. The next moves,  9.Nc3  Nf6  , are very natural for both sides. Once they are on the board, we'll investigate the details of our concept more closely. }
9. Nc3
{ White covers the d-pawn and develops the knight – by far White's most popular move. They have a good alternative in 9.Bd3,  though.  After  9.Bd3  , we recommend the simple solution  9...Nf6  , when  10.Nc3  transposes to our main line of  9.Nc3  Nf6  10.Bd3  , examined later in the current chapter.   There is an independent option  9.Bd3  Qxd5  , but it does not seem better than 9...Nf6 and thus only means an additional workload for little benefit.   A dubious move for White is  9.Bc4?!  , when the simple  9...Rc8  is annoying for White; our opponent likely must play  10.Bd3  now, losing a full tempo with the bishop. }
9... Nf6
{ We need to speed up our kingside development and get closer to castling. Now we examine three continuations for White, leading to different scenarios.  A@@EndBracket@@  10.Bd3  is by far the main move. White develops the bishop and prepares kingside castling – a very natural choice. In these lines, White keeps the bishop pair, and we need to be precise to get fair chances.  B@@EndBracket@@  10.Bg5  also makes a lot of sense. White pins our knight, trying to keep the d5-pawn. After  10...Be7  , they need to capture our knight to realize this idea, but in the resulting position, we'll have good play for the pawn. The opposite-coloured bishops are a vital factor, making the material deficit meaningless.   C@@EndBracket@@  10.g4!?  is a rarely played, fun move. Almost needless to say, it leads to sharp play! White gains massive space on the kingside but says 'Goodbye!' to a safe king position long-term. }
10. Bd3
{ White develops and prepares kingside castling. According to 'classical' principles, this move is White's best bet for an advantage. }
10... Be7
{ It's crucial not to confuse the move order at this point. It looks logical to regain the pawn, but  10...Nxd5?  is a mistake. After  11.O-O  Be7  12.Be4!  we have no good reply.   It's much better to first get the king out of the middle of the board by starting with  10...Be7  and castling next. White can't keep the d5-pawn anyway, so we don't need to rush its capture. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Re1
{ What could be more logical? White develops the rook and attacks our pawn. You might also meet  12.Be3  , which is slightly less precise. After  12...Nxd5  13.Nxd5  Qxd5  14.Qg4  Bf6  , we reach a similar position as in the main line @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1p2bppp/p4n2/3PpP2/3n4/2NB4/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 7 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Re1  Nxd5  13.Nxd5  Qxd5  , but White has played the less useful move Be3 instead of Re1. }
12... Nxd5
{ We have regained our pawn, but what about the e5-pawn? White can indeed take it, but it's nothing to worry about, as we'll see in a minute.  There also is  13.Be4  to check, when  13...Nf6!  is leading to interesting complications. White wins b7 but we'll get good play for the material.   White's most challenging move is  13.Nxd5  , which will be our main focus. }
13. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ We have regained the pawn and a well-centralized position. Still, White has all the right to be happy about their chances, too. They have the bishop pair and control of the e4-square. On the other hand, our centralized knight provides compensation for these deficits.  We want to highlight a key idea: White's f5-pawn plays a crucial role in White's play. It secures the control of e4 and may be used to attack our king. We want to remove the pawn by playing ...g6 at the right moment. A trade on g6 is welcome, as we will see.  Now, after 13...Qxd5,  we'll have a split between two approaches by White. The first one is  14.Qg4  , when White plays for an attack on the kingside. The second one is  14.Be4  Qd7  15.Be3  , a slower setup by White. Our play will be similar in both cases. Our queen needs to retreat to d7; next, we aim for ...g6.   In the case of  14.Qg4  , this process takes longer or might not materialize – the play is more concrete and based on tactics/threats than after  14.Be4  . Let's have a closer look now. }
14. Be4 Qd7
{ The best square for our queen. We cover b7 and, more importantly, put pressure on f5. However, we are not threatening to take it due to the d-file pin.  The way to continue is going for the move ...g6 at the right time, trying to force White to capture on g6. }
15. Be3
{ A more quiet approach than the Qg4-based ideas. If White wants to play for an attack, they should start with 14.Qg4,  as here it is already less dangerous. After  15.Qg4  g6  , we'll ultimately manage to remove the f5-pawn.  Here's a sample line to illustrate:  15.Qg4  g6  16.Bh6  Rfe8  17.Rad1  Rad8  18.Rd3  Kh8  19.h3  Bf6  – this setup is very similar to the 14.Qg4 lines. Now White has nothing better than finally taking on g6.  After  20.fxg6  hxg6  21.Bd2  Qxg4  22.hxg4  b6  we have reached an endgame. White is slightly better, but the manoeuvre ...Ne6-c5 is a key defensive resource. Our pieces have stable outposts, and White can't easily create a passed pawn, which is a crucial idea for the side with the bishop pair. }
15... Rad8
{ An important moment. We cover our queen and further support the d4-knight.  That's one thing, but it's crucial to avoid  15...g6?  16.Bxd4  exd4  17.Qb3!  , when White attacks b7 and threatens to take twice on g6. We need to prepare the ...g7-g6 pawn move first. }
16. g3
{ Sticking with a slow approach.  Against  16.Qg4  , we'd also play  16...g6  . }
16... g6
{ Finally, we can play the desired move. It's a good moment to take stock and look at some possible lines to illustrate.  A@@EndBracket@@  17.fxg6  hxg6  18.Rc1  Bb4  19.Rf1  Qe6  looks fine. We are well coordinated and centralized. This leads to line B – White taking our strong knight.   B@@EndBracket@@  17.fxg6  hxg6  18.Bxd4  Qxd4!  19.Qxd4  Rxd4  20.Bxb7  Rb8  21.Bxa6  Rxb2  22.Rxe5  Bf6  23.Re8+  Kg7  24.a4  Rdd2  21.Rf1  Bd4  is a long line, but it shows that White gets nowhere with grabbing pawns.  All in all, it looks like we are OK with precise play. }
