[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Alapin Setups 2.Nf3 a6 3.c3 and 2.c3"]
[Black "Introduction to the Alapin"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello and welcome to our chapter on the Alapin Variation of the Sicilian, also frequently called the c3-Sicilian. This already hints that we are talking about the variations  2.c3  or  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  , which is a solid option for White if they want to avoid the complications of the Open Sicilian or other principled tries.  The Alapin follows a very healthy strategic idea. White would like to play the d-pawn to d4 and build the perfect pawn centre e4 + d4. How do we fight this idea? We need to think about our overall repertoire concept to answer this question satisfactorily. We must be aware of the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  , when White opts for the Alapin after we have already committed to the move ...a6.  Delayed Alapin with 3.c3  Playing 3.c3 has a good reputation for White, arguing that the move Nf3 must be more beneficial than ...a6 in the Alapin. This argument makes a lot of sense, but on the other hand, the Alapin is not considered particularly dangerous. Giving White a slightly better version of it after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  should not be the end of the world, as we will show in this chapter.  So what to do about White's idea to build a perfect pawn centre? It would work perfectly if Black went for a passive reply. A possible example for passive play is  3...d6  4.d4  when White has a comfortable central advantage. They keep the pawns on d4 and e4 for the foreseeable future.  The key concept for Black after 3.c3 is quick counterplay against the e-pawn. Our research led to the conclusion that Black has two good options: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.d4  d5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  . The choice between these two was easy for us, as the first option allows a transposition into a French Defense after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pp4/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e5  , which is not in the spirit of our repertoire. The latter option is the more dynamic and fighting choice and, therefore, our recommendation.  Alright, we have determined that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  is the way to go against the 'Delayed Alapin' – what about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3 ?   Alapin with 2.c3  Black has a wider range of options here, as we are not committed to ...a6.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  Nf6  are of about equal value but after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  our choice is  3...d5  , as discussed above.  Answering 2.c3 and 2.Nf3 a6 3.c3 with the same reply makes a lot of sense from a practical point of view. We save some workload and maximize the frequency of the positions we know well. White will rarely be prepared for an early ...a6 in the Alapin, which always helps.  Move Order  A word about the move order concept of this chapter. We decided to use @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  as the main move order, after which  3...d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  e6  leads to a central parting of the ways. The various options on move six comprise the majority of the chapter. We also have a look at the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  , when  2...d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  e6  5.Nf3  a6  leads to this key position, as well. Let's get to work! }
*

