[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Alapin Setups 2.Nf3 a6 3.c3 and 2.c3"]
[Black "4A | Alapin with 2.c3 | White plays 3.e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The starting move of the Alapin. We discussed White's general idea in the Introduction to the Alapin. They want to build a perfect pawn centre with e4 and d4. }
2... d5
{ An immediate attack against e4 is the way to go. We answer @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  with  3...d5  , so aiming for the same lines against 2.c3 is a practical solution. It's possible to play an entirely different system, like  2...Nf6  , but saving a bit of workload is welcome. }
3. e5
{ Advancing the pawn is a strategic mistake. You'll still meet it sometimes online or at club-level play. Let's look at why we don't need to worry about this line. }
3... Nc6
{ Attacking the e-pawn makes a lot of sense. Developing a piece with a gain of tempo is very natural. }
4. d4
{ White needs to support their central pawn, a very natural move. It's interesting to compare this position to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  c5  4.c3  Nc6  . It's the same position... but with White to move! In our line of the Sicilian, we pushed the c-pawn to c5 in one go, saving a tempo. This line of the Caro-Kann is recommended in Christof's course Keep It Simple for Black and comfortable for Black. Reaching it a full tempo up is excellent, of course. }
4... Bf5
{ We happily develop the bishop to f5 and want to continue with ...e6.  If White had played @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/2ppP3/8/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3?!  pinning the knight with  4...Bg4  is best.  Here, after 4.d4,  we don't have this option. }
5. Nf3 { This is White's most natural and popular move. } 5... e6
{ It's a good moment to take stock. Black already has slightly better chances, as our play is easy to conduct. We'll trade on d4 soon, after which the d-pawn will be a handy target. Let's look at a possible sequence to illustrate this concept. }
6. Be2
{ White could also play  6.Bd3  , when Black is fine after the simple trade on d3. A more exciting option, however, is  6...Be4!?  , which threatens to win the d-pawn by taking the knight.   The move  6.Bb5  is similarly harmless and can be answered with  6...Qb6  . We attack the bishop and put more pressure on d4. }
6... cxd4
{ Black has plenty of good alternatives, but we'd like to show the basic strategy with this straightforward approach. }
7. cxd4
{ White's d-pawn can only be protected by pieces now. We plan to put maximum pressure on it. }
7... Bg4
{ It looks odd to move the bishop again, but it fits well with our strategy of maximum pressure against d4. Our bishop obviously can't attack d4 directly, so we put pressure on a defender of the d-pawn instead. At the same time, we clear the f5-square for the g8-knight. The manouvre ...Ng8-e7-f5 is on the cards. }
8. O-O Nge7 { On the way to f5. } 9. Nc3 Nf5
{ Black's position makes a sound, harmonious impression. The key concepts to remember after 3.e5 are:  ➤ Develop the bishop outside the pawn chain, to f5 or g4, if allowed.  ➤ Put pressure on the d-pawn. Placing the knight on f5 is a good idea. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Alapin Setups 2.Nf3 a6 3.c3 and 2.c3"]
[Black "4A | Alapin with 2.c3 | White plays 3.exd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The starting move of the Alapin. We discussed White's general idea in the Introduction to the Alapin. They want to build a perfect pawn centre with e4 and d4. }
2... d5
{ An immediate attack against e4 is the way to go. We answer @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  with  3...d5  , so aiming for the same lines against 2.c3 is a practical solution. It's possible to play an entirely different system, like  2...Nf6  , but saving a bit of workload is welcome. }
3. exd5 { Taking the pawn is the only critical move. } 3... Qxd5
{ Are you concerned about moving the queen so early? We discuss this question more in the notes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  . }
4. d4
{ The point of 2.c3,  of course.  White could also play  4.Nf3  when  4...a6  would be a direct transposition to the main line of the current chapter. What to play after 4.d4,  though? }
4... e6
{ Why this move? Our choice against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  is  3...d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  e6  , which is the main line of the chapter. Our goal is to transpose to this line, so after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  the moves to consider are  4...a6  and  4...e6  .  Given that we never develop the bishop to g4 @@StartBracket@@more on this topic in the notes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  e6!  , when we avoid the bishop move@@EndBracket@@, starting with 4...e6 looks more natural than 4...a6. }
5. Nf3
{ White's almost exclusive choice here. What could be more natural? Other moves don't have any serious independent value, but they could transpose to lines that usually start with  5.Nf3  a6  .   One example is  5.Na3  a6  6.Nc4  Nd7  7.Nf3  Ngf6  , which we cover via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  e6  6.Na3  Nf6  7.Nc4  Nbd7  . }
5... a6
{ And we have transposed to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  e6  , the main line of the current chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Alapin Setups 2.Nf3 a6 3.c3 and 2.c3"]
[Black "4B | Delayed Alapin with 3.c3 | White plays 5.Na3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. c3
{ This 'delayed Alapin' is recommended in many repertoire books, for example, in Christof's Keep It Simple: 1.e4 and Wesley So's Lifetime Repertoire.  As we show in this repertoire, the O'Kelly is by no means easy to play against. If you construct a repertoire for White, you need pragmatic solutions against rare lines. In the case of the O'Kelly, many lines for White are not attractive @@StartBracket@@  3.d4  @@EndBracket@@ or rather sophisticated @@StartBracket@@  3.c4  and  3.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@.  The line  3.c3  is a good solution for White, as it poses problems, but does not require that much work for White, in comparison to the mentioned alternatives. }
3... d5
{ We think this line gives Black the best chances against 3.c3.  The other satisfactory option is  3...e6  , but  4.d4  d5  5.e5  would transpose to a French Defence, which does not fit well with our repertoire concept. }
4. exd5
{ That's White's only challenging move. You sometimes meet  4.e5?!  , which is well answered with  4...Bg4  . This is best compared to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.e5?!  , when we recommend  3...Nc6  4.d4  Bf5  5.Be2  e6  6.O-O  cxd4  7.cxd4  Bg4  , leading to fine play for Black.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.e5?!  Bg4  we are likely to reach a similar scenario with the extra move ...a6,  as we managed to develop the bishop to g4 in one go. }
4... Qxd5
{ Well, you shouldn't move the queen too early in the opening – unless it's good 😝  Here, Black's play is justified, as White has already committed a pawn to c3. Therefore, the easy tempo-gain Nc3 is off the table @@StartBracket@@compare to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@  .   Here, in the Alapin, our queen is not so easily chased around but still could be vulnerable in the middle of the board. We'll look closer at White's options on move six, as  5.d4  e6  is the almost universal continuation. We'll also briefly check if White can delay the move d4,  but it does not make a substantial difference. }
5. Na3
{ White almost always plays  5.d4  here, when  5...e6  is our recommendation. White can try to delay the move of the d-pawn, though. The two moves to check are @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Be2  and  5.Na3  , which is the more dangerous of the two.  After  5.Be2  e6  6.O-O  Nf6  White will likely finally play  7.d4  cxd4  , when we transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  e6  6.Be2  cxd4  . This looks very natural, but White could try to delay the d-pawn move even more. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/3q4/3p4/2P2N2/PP2BPPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  7.Na3  comes to mind, but Black is fine after  7...Nbd7  , which covers the weak b6-square in anticipation of Nc4. We see a similar idea after our main move 5.Na3 soon. }
5... e6
{ We play in the same way after 5.d4 and are ready to transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/8/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.d4  e6  6.Na3  , if White continues with the natural move of the d-pawn now.   An important point to remember is that we'd like to answer Nc4 with ...Nbd7. Therefore, playing  5...Nc6  does not fit in with our intentions. }
6. Nc4
{ White is directly aiming at the b6-square.  After  6.d4  Nf6  we'd transpose to a main line of this chapter that usually arises via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  e6  5.Nf3  a6  6.Na3  Nf6  . }
6... Nd7 { The tender b6-square is covered. } 7. a4
{ A way for White to avoid the transposition after  7.d4  Ngf6  , which again leads to a main line of the current chapter. }
7... b6
{ An important move! White was threatening the move a4-a5!, which we can't allow. We need the move ...b6, preparing to fianchetto our c8-bishop.  Black has fine chances in this position, which is still likely to transpose to a main line of the current chapter. It makes little sense for White to delay d2-d4 forever. }
