[White "4) Alapin Setups 2.Nf3 a6 3.c3 and 2.c3"]
[Black "4B | Delayed Alapin with 3.c3 | White plays 5.d4 / 6.c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. c3
{ This 'delayed Alapin' is recommended in many repertoire books, for example, in Christof's Keep It Simple: 1.e4 and Wesley So's Lifetime Repertoire.  As we show in this repertoire, the O'Kelly is by no means easy to play against. If you construct a repertoire for White, you need pragmatic solutions against rare lines. In the case of the O'Kelly, many lines for White are not attractive @@StartBracket@@  3.d4  @@EndBracket@@ or rather sophisticated @@StartBracket@@  3.c4  and  3.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@.  The line  3.c3  is a good solution for White, as it poses problems, but does not require that much work for White, in comparison to the mentioned alternatives. }
3... d5
{ We think this line gives Black the best chances against 3.c3.  The other satisfactory option is  3...e6  , but  4.d4  d5  5.e5  would transpose to a French Defence, which does not fit well with our repertoire concept. }
4. exd5
{ That's White's only challenging move. You sometimes meet  4.e5?!  , which is well answered with  4...Bg4  . This is best compared to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.e5?!  , when we recommend  3...Nc6  4.d4  Bf5  5.Be2  e6  6.O-O  cxd4  7.cxd4  Bg4  , leading to fine play for Black.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.e5?!  Bg4  we are likely to reach a similar scenario with the extra move ...a6,  as we managed to develop the bishop to g4 in one go. }
4... Qxd5
{ Well, you shouldn't move the queen too early in the opening – unless it's good 😝  Here, Black's play is justified, as White has already committed a pawn to c3. Therefore, the easy tempo-gain Nc3 is off the table @@StartBracket@@compare to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@  .   Here, in the Alapin, our queen is not so easily chased around but still could be vulnerable in the middle of the board. We'll look closer at White's options on move six, as  5.d4  e6  is the almost universal continuation. We'll also briefly check if White can delay the move d4,  but it does not make a substantial difference. }
5. d4
{ White's most natural and best move. How to react? Let's have a look:  A@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4  looks active, but after  6.Be2  e6  7.O-O  Nf6  8.h3  Bh5  both  9.Be3  @@StartBracket@@as already covered in Keep It Simple: 1.e4@@EndBracket@@ and  9.c4  lead to an advantage for White.   B@@EndBracket@@  5...Nf6  looks natural, but  6.Be3!  is tough to meet. We don't want to trade on d4,  as after  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  White will play Nc3 next, chasing our queen. On the other hand, White attacks the c5-pawn after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/1p2pppp/p4n2/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , which turns  6...e6  7.dxc5!  into a problem.   C@@EndBracket@@  5...Nc6  6.Be3!  is a similar story to 5...Nf6. We don't want to take on d4,  but c5 is attacked. The line @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Be3  e6  7.dxc5  shows an issue of our position: the vulnerability of the c-pawn. This leads to our idea to start with @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  when  6.Be3  can be answered with  6...Nd7!  , which lends additional support to c5. }
5... e6
{ We think this move gives Black the best prospects, as the alternatives lead to problems @@StartBracket@@see the notes to 5.d4 for more information@@EndBracket@@.  After 5...e6,  White has a wide range of options. It is crucial to study these moves and appreciate their differences, as there is no general setup or concept we could apply. We must address each White option as an independent line and learn a specific response.  Of course, there are some common themes, but it is essential not to confuse our replies. Let's have an overview of White's ideas and discuss some of the key differences.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a critical move. White intends to win a pawn with dxc5,  which we stop with  6...Nd7  , as already discussed in the notes to move  5.   B@@EndBracket@@  6.c4  attacks our queen. We retreat to d8 and get fair chances.   C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is a popular choice for White. Against this move, the most straightforward recipe is  6...cxd4!  , immediately clarifying the central structure. It is the only case of the direct trade on d4,  as we don't mind fighting the IQP after White has committed the bishop to e2.   D@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  looks a bit more active than  6.Be2  , looking towards the kingside. It's crucial NOT to take on d4 early on against this move, as the arising IQP structure is much better for White than the situation after  6.Be2  cxd4!  . The difference between these two versions is discussed in more detail in the notes to these moves.   E@@EndBracket@@  6.Na3  is aimed at exploiting the weak b6-square, jumping to c4 next. We have not yet committed the b8-knight, which proves useful after  6...Nf6  7.Nc4  Nbd7  , when we safely cover our weakness. }
6. c4
{ White gains a bit of time on our queen and clears the c3-square for the knight. Where do we go now? }
6... Qd8
{ This is best. In some cases, replying to c4 with ...Qc6 is an option, but only if White can't favourably reply with d4-d5. Here,  6...Qc6?  7.d5  should certainly be avoided. It's no problem at all to retreat to d8 here, though.   We'll now @@StartBracket@@after  6...Qd8  @@EndBracket@@ examine  7.Nc3  and  7.d5  , leading to entirely different pawn structures. }
7. d5 { Ambitious, but ultimately not dangerous for Black. } 7... exd5 8. cxd5
{ White's d-pawn can be a strength or a weakness. It takes away some squares and is a passed pawn, but it is also isolated and can be attacked multiple times.  Note that ...a6 turns out to be a good move for Black. We stop checks on b5 and prepare ...b5 at a later stage. }
8... Nf6 { A logical move, attacking d5 and developing the kingside. } 9. Nc3
Bd6
{ We prepare kingside castling, again a very natural choice. White only has one move that may pose problems, but it is not easy to find and is rarely played. }
10. Qe2+
{ The only move that poses a challenge. After a slow continuation, we castle kingside and develop quickly. The d5-pawn is more of a weakness than a strength. We can attack it in various ways, like ...b5 and ...Bb7, or ...Nd7-b6. }
10... Qe7
{ This is forced, as  10...Be7?  nets White a huge initiative, at least. The queen move is fine for Black, though. }
11. Bg5
{ Or  11.Qxe7+  Kxe7  , when ...Re8 is coming soon to castle by hand. Keeping the bishop on d6 prevents White's Bf4 move. }
11... Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 Nbd7
{ We have reached an interesting position that offers equal chances. A typical idea for White is the transfer of a knight to c4, which we'll examine now. }
13. Nd2 h6 14. Be3
{ Or  14.Bxf6  Nxf6  15.Nc4  Ke7  , keeping the balance. After  16.a4  , Black must organise with  16...Rd8  , intending ...Kf8,  and either ...Rb8 or ...Bf5. }
14... Be5
{ We wanted to show this instructive move. White's 13.Nd2 prepared the jump to c4 but neglected control of e5. We use this fact to activate our bishop and simultaneously put some pressure on d5. We threaten to take the knight on c3,  removing the defender of the central pawn.  A possible continuation is  15.Bf3  Bxc3  16.bxc3  Ne5  17.c4  b5  when we hold the balance by chipping away at White's pawns. }
*

