{ We think this move gives Black the best prospects, as the alternatives lead to problems @@StartBracket@@see the notes to 5.d4 for more information@@EndBracket@@.  After 5...e6,  White has a wide range of options. It is crucial to study these moves and appreciate their differences, as there is no general setup or concept we could apply. We must address each White option as an independent line and learn a specific response.  Of course, there are some common themes, but it is essential not to confuse our replies. Let's have an overview of White's ideas and discuss some of the key differences.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a critical move. White intends to win a pawn with dxc5,  which we stop with  6...Nd7  , as already discussed in the notes to move  5.   B@@EndBracket@@  6.c4  attacks our queen. We retreat to d8 and get fair chances.   C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is a popular choice for White. Against this move, the most straightforward recipe is  6...cxd4!  , immediately clarifying the central structure. It is the only case of the direct trade on d4,  as we don't mind fighting the IQP after White has committed the bishop to e2.   D@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  looks a bit more active than  6.Be2  , looking towards the kingside. It's crucial NOT to take on d4 early on against this move, as the arising IQP structure is much better for White than the situation after  6.Be2  cxd4!  . The difference between these two versions is discussed in more detail in the notes to these moves.   E@@EndBracket@@  6.Na3  is aimed at exploiting the weak b6-square, jumping to c4 next. We have not yet committed the b8-knight, which proves useful after  6...Nf6  7.Nc4  Nbd7  , when we safely cover our weakness. }
6. Be2
{ Surprisingly, this modest-looking move is White's most popular choice. A closer look reveals that it has a lot more bite than you might think at first glance. The first important decision for us is whether we want to trade on d4 or not. }
6... cxd4
{ Black has to be careful with the early trade on d4. We create an IQP @@StartBracket@@most of the time@@EndBracket@@, but also give White the option to play Nc3 quickly, gaining time on our queen. Against 6.Be2,  we recommend taking on d4. The exclamation mark is a bit strong, but we decided to award the exclam as it is the ONLY case when we advise to take on d4 on move  6.  It is crucial to understand the difference to 6.Bd3,  when we should NOT take on d4. Why? Let's compare:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@6.Be2  cxd4  7.cxd4  Nc6  8.Nc3  Qd6  9.O-O  Nf6   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  cxd4?  7.cxd4  Nc6  8.Nc3  Qd6  9.O-O  Nf6   In variation A @@StartBracket@@we'll get to this position in a minute@@EndBracket@@, White has nothing better than a standard development move, like @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1nqpn2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bg5  or  10.Re1  , while in variation B, the sequence @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1nqpn2/8/3P4/2NB1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne4!  Nxe4  11.Bxe4  is surprisingly strong. The e4-bishop is fantastically placed, and Black has to be careful to survive the next moves. Something like  11...Be7  12.Ne5  Nxe5  13.Bf4!  is even worse than it looks at first.  Long story short: the IQP position with a bishop on e2 is MUCH easier for Black to handle than with a bishop on d3. The difference is so significant that we recommend avoiding the IQP after 6.Bd3 in the first place.  We have established that taking on d4 is our concept against 6.Be2. Should we take it straightaway, or is it possible to delay the move for a while? We suggest taking it immediately for two reasons. The first one is that it is easier to remember if the defining action of a variation is played directly rather than later. The second reason is that waiting too long could prove annoying.  One example is @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  Nf6  7.O-O  Be7?!  , when  8.Ne5!  is surprisingly problematic for Black. White prepares Bf3,  attacking our queen. We can avoid these ideas by taking on d4 immediately. }
7. cxd4
{ White creates the IQP and is happy about gaining a tempo with Nc3 soon. Taking with a piece is entirely harmless, as we achieve the move ...e6-e5 effortlessly.  A@@EndBracket@@  7.Nxd4  e5!  8.Nf3  Qxd1+  9.Bxd1  f6   B@@EndBracket@@  7.Qxd4  Qxd4  8.Nxd4  e5  are both comfortable for Black. We develop quickly and enjoy the extra central e-pawn. }
7... Nc6
{ We'd like to play the knights to their natural squares f6 and c6. Both moves are possible, but we suggest starting with  7...Nc6  , as  7...Nf6  gives White the additional idea  8.Nc3  Qd6  9.Ne5  .   This wouldn't be the end of the world, but we can prevent it by going  7...Nc6  first. }
8. Nc3 Qd6
{ In such a scenario, Black always has the choice between ...Qd8 and ...Qd6. We suggest the more ambitious ...Qd6 here, as a typical drawback of ...Qd6 in other lines is no issue here: we have b5 covered, so the queen can't be attacked by Nb5. }
9. O-O
{ White gets nowhere with  9.d5  exd5  10.Nxd5  Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/1p3ppp/p1nqp3/8/3P4/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ne4  Qd8  , when ...Be7 and ...Nf6 will challenge the e4-knight quickly. }
9... Nf6
{ White has many possible moves after our standard development move. They can play  10.Bg5  ,  10.Re1  or  10.Be3  , for example. Our job is relatively simple, as we'll play ...Be7 and ...O-O in any case. Later, we need to decide if we continue with ...b5 and ...Bb7 or go for a different setup.  We'll have a look at 10.Bg5 and 10.Be3 to illustrate some possibilities. }
10. Be3
{ We examine this move because of a creative idea that White may go for the next move. }
10... Be7 { The normal move to prepare kingside castling. } 11. Nd2
{ A rare but challenging idea. You'll meet a continuation, like  11.Rc1  more frequently, when  11...O-O  12.Qd2  b5  gives us an easy game. We complete development with ...Bb7 soon and have a clear target: the IQP! }
11... O-O { As planned: we castle first and then decide how to continue. } 12.
Nc4
{ The alternative  12.Nde4  Nxe4  13.Nxe4  Qb4  only leads to trades and is harmless for Black. }
12... Qc7 13. Bf3
{ Or  13.Rc1  Rd8  14.Bf3  Nd5  , which looks similar.   13...Rd8  looks natural in this position, but leads to favourable complications for White after  14.d5!  when the weakness of b6 is shown. }
13... Nb4 { We attack c4 and connect our knight to the d5-square. } 14. Ne5
Nbd5
{ The computer slightly prefers White in this position, but Black has fair chances. It's a rather typical struggle with imbalances in which the stronger player @@StartBracket@@or the player who plays better!@@EndBracket@@ is the favourite. White has the slight weakness of the IQP, but active pieces.  Now a fascinating line is  14.Rc1  Nxe3!  15.fxe3  Qd8  , which looks odd at first. We are behind in development and White's pieces look active. However, after our planned move ...Bd6 White's knight is not stable. We have the bishop pair and White has weaknesses on the dark squares, which is a long-term issue for our opponent. }
