{ Black has to be careful with the early trade on d4. We create an IQP @@StartBracket@@most of the time@@EndBracket@@, but also give White the option to play Nc3 quickly, gaining time on our queen. Against 6.Be2,  we recommend taking on d4. The exclamation mark is a bit strong, but we decided to award the exclam as it is the ONLY case when we advise to take on d4 on move  6.  It is crucial to understand the difference to 6.Bd3,  when we should NOT take on d4. Why? Let's compare:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@6.Be2  cxd4  7.cxd4  Nc6  8.Nc3  Qd6  9.O-O  Nf6   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  cxd4?  7.cxd4  Nc6  8.Nc3  Qd6  9.O-O  Nf6   In variation A @@StartBracket@@we'll get to this position in a minute@@EndBracket@@, White has nothing better than a standard development move, like @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1nqpn2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bg5  or  10.Re1  , while in variation B, the sequence @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1nqpn2/8/3P4/2NB1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne4!  Nxe4  11.Bxe4  is surprisingly strong. The e4-bishop is fantastically placed, and Black has to be careful to survive the next moves. Something like  11...Be7  12.Ne5  Nxe5  13.Bf4!  is even worse than it looks at first.  Long story short: the IQP position with a bishop on e2 is MUCH easier for Black to handle than with a bishop on d3. The difference is so significant that we recommend avoiding the IQP after 6.Bd3 in the first place.  We have established that taking on d4 is our concept against 6.Be2. Should we take it straightaway, or is it possible to delay the move for a while? We suggest taking it immediately for two reasons. The first one is that it is easier to remember if the defining action of a variation is played directly rather than later. The second reason is that waiting too long could prove annoying.  One example is @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  Nf6  7.O-O  Be7?!  , when  8.Ne5!  is surprisingly problematic for Black. White prepares Bf3,  attacking our queen. We can avoid these ideas by taking on d4 immediately. }
7. cxd4
{ White creates the IQP and is happy about gaining a tempo with Nc3 soon. Taking with a piece is entirely harmless, as we achieve the move ...e6-e5 effortlessly.  A@@EndBracket@@  7.Nxd4  e5!  8.Nf3  Qxd1+  9.Bxd1  f6   B@@EndBracket@@  7.Qxd4  Qxd4  8.Nxd4  e5  are both comfortable for Black. We develop quickly and enjoy the extra central e-pawn. }
7... Nc6
{ We'd like to play the knights to their natural squares f6 and c6. Both moves are possible, but we suggest starting with  7...Nc6  , as  7...Nf6  gives White the additional idea  8.Nc3  Qd6  9.Ne5  .   This wouldn't be the end of the world, but we can prevent it by going  7...Nc6  first. }
8. Nc3 Qd6
{ In such a scenario, Black always has the choice between ...Qd8 and ...Qd6. We suggest the more ambitious ...Qd6 here, as a typical drawback of ...Qd6 in other lines is no issue here: we have b5 covered, so the queen can't be attacked by Nb5. }
9. O-O
{ White gets nowhere with  9.d5  exd5  10.Nxd5  Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/1p3ppp/p1nqp3/8/3P4/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ne4  Qd8  , when ...Be7 and ...Nf6 will challenge the e4-knight quickly. }
9... Nf6
{ White has many possible moves after our standard development move. They can play  10.Bg5  ,  10.Re1  or  10.Be3  , for example. Our job is relatively simple, as we'll play ...Be7 and ...O-O in any case. Later, we need to decide if we continue with ...b5 and ...Bb7 or go for a different setup.  We'll have a look at 10.Bg5 and 10.Be3 to illustrate some possibilities. }
10. Bg5
{ White's most popular move at this point. White often combines Bg5 and Re1 and may also start with  10.Re1  Be7  11.Bg5  , which would lead to the same positions. }
10... Be7 { White has a wide range of options, again. } 11. Qd2
{ This is played most often, but many moves are regularly played here. In all cases, we can castle quickly and operate with ...Rd8,  ...b5 and often ...Nd5,  offering trades. Here are some examples.  A@@EndBracket@@  11.Bxf6  is harmless. After  11...Bxf6  12.Ne4  Qe7  White has accomplished nothing. We'll play ...O-O and ...Rd8 next.   B@@EndBracket@@  11.Rc1  O-O  12.Qd2  Nd5  or  12...Rd8  works well, too.   C@@EndBracket@@  11.Re1  O-O  12.Rc1  Rd8  , when we have good pressure on d4. }
11... O-O { Again, White has a wide choice. } 12. Rfd1
{ Other rook moves are possible, of course. We'd also answer  12.Rad1  with  12...b5  , but  12...Rd8  or  12...Nd5  would work, too. All in all, we are not under any pressure here and have some leeway. }
12... b5
{ We prepare the queenside fianchetto and gain some space. White has to play actively – if they play too passively, we might easily gain the upper hand, putting pressure on the IQP. }
13. a4 { As mentioned: active play is necessary for White. } 13... bxa4 14.
Rxa4
{ Or  14.Nxa4  Nd5  , which offers more trades and covers the b6-square. We welcome trades, as they make the weakness of the IQP more pronounced. }
14... Bb7
{ It's a good moment to stop the trainable line. We have completed our development and connected rooks, a good moment to take stock.  We assess chances as about equal. White has the IQP, a potential long-term liability. On the other hand, all white pieces are active. We are looking at a fine 'balance of imbalances', so to say.  Our general strategy is to trade more minor pieces and increase pressure on the pawn. We also need to think prophylactically and anticipate possible ideas of our opponent, in particular regarding the pawn-push d4-d5 or other tactical sequences. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Alapin Setups 2.Nf3 a6 3.c3 and 2.c3"]
[Black "4B | Delayed Alapin with 3.c3 | White plays 5.d4 / 6.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. c3
{ This 'delayed Alapin' is recommended in many repertoire books, for example, in Christof's Keep It Simple: 1.e4 and Wesley So's Lifetime Repertoire.  As we show in this repertoire, the O'Kelly is by no means easy to play against. If you construct a repertoire for White, you need pragmatic solutions against rare lines. In the case of the O'Kelly, many lines for White are not attractive @@StartBracket@@  3.d4  @@EndBracket@@ or rather sophisticated @@StartBracket@@  3.c4  and  3.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@.  The line  3.c3  is a good solution for White, as it poses problems, but does not require that much work for White, in comparison to the mentioned alternatives. }
3... d5
{ We think this line gives Black the best chances against 3.c3.  The other satisfactory option is  3...e6  , but  4.d4  d5  5.e5  would transpose to a French Defence, which does not fit well with our repertoire concept. }
4. exd5
{ That's White's only challenging move. You sometimes meet  4.e5?!  , which is well answered with  4...Bg4  . This is best compared to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.e5?!  , when we recommend  3...Nc6  4.d4  Bf5  5.Be2  e6  6.O-O  cxd4  7.cxd4  Bg4  , leading to fine play for Black.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.e5?!  Bg4  we are likely to reach a similar scenario with the extra move ...a6,  as we managed to develop the bishop to g4 in one go. }
4... Qxd5
{ Well, you shouldn't move the queen too early in the opening – unless it's good 😝  Here, Black's play is justified, as White has already committed a pawn to c3. Therefore, the easy tempo-gain Nc3 is off the table @@StartBracket@@compare to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@  .   Here, in the Alapin, our queen is not so easily chased around but still could be vulnerable in the middle of the board. We'll look closer at White's options on move six, as  5.d4  e6  is the almost universal continuation. We'll also briefly check if White can delay the move d4,  but it does not make a substantial difference. }
5. d4
{ White's most natural and best move. How to react? Let's have a look:  A@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4  looks active, but after  6.Be2  e6  7.O-O  Nf6  8.h3  Bh5  both  9.Be3  @@StartBracket@@as already covered in Keep It Simple: 1.e4@@EndBracket@@ and  9.c4  lead to an advantage for White.   B@@EndBracket@@  5...Nf6  looks natural, but  6.Be3!  is tough to meet. We don't want to trade on d4,  as after  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  White will play Nc3 next, chasing our queen. On the other hand, White attacks the c5-pawn after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/1p2pppp/p4n2/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , which turns  6...e6  7.dxc5!  into a problem.   C@@EndBracket@@  5...Nc6  6.Be3!  is a similar story to 5...Nf6. We don't want to take on d4,  but c5 is attacked. The line @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Be3  e6  7.dxc5  shows an issue of our position: the vulnerability of the c-pawn. This leads to our idea to start with @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  when  6.Be3  can be answered with  6...Nd7!  , which lends additional support to c5. }
5... e6
{ We think this move gives Black the best prospects, as the alternatives lead to problems @@StartBracket@@see the notes to 5.d4 for more information@@EndBracket@@.  After 5...e6,  White has a wide range of options. It is crucial to study these moves and appreciate their differences, as there is no general setup or concept we could apply. We must address each White option as an independent line and learn a specific response.  Of course, there are some common themes, but it is essential not to confuse our replies. Let's have an overview of White's ideas and discuss some of the key differences.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a critical move. White intends to win a pawn with dxc5,  which we stop with  6...Nd7  , as already discussed in the notes to move  5.   B@@EndBracket@@  6.c4  attacks our queen. We retreat to d8 and get fair chances.   C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is a popular choice for White. Against this move, the most straightforward recipe is  6...cxd4!  , immediately clarifying the central structure. It is the only case of the direct trade on d4,  as we don't mind fighting the IQP after White has committed the bishop to e2.   D@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  looks a bit more active than  6.Be2  , looking towards the kingside. It's crucial NOT to take on d4 early on against this move, as the arising IQP structure is much better for White than the situation after  6.Be2  cxd4!  . The difference between these two versions is discussed in more detail in the notes to these moves.   E@@EndBracket@@  6.Na3  is aimed at exploiting the weak b6-square, jumping to c4 next. We have not yet committed the b8-knight, which proves useful after  6...Nf6  7.Nc4  Nbd7  , when we safely cover our weakness. }
6. Bd3
{ White develops the bishop and prepares to castle; what could be more natural? Still, this move is less popular and critical than some alternatives.  First of all, we need to answer a key question. To take on d4 or not to take? }
6... Nf6
{ A key decision! We DON'T take on d4 now and on the next moves, but rather continue with kingside development and keep the tension.  Why is taking on d4 a mistake? Against 6.Be2,  we recommend taking on d4. Why not here? Let's compare:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  cxd4  7.cxd4  Nc6  8.Nc3  Qd6  9.O-O  Nf6   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  cxd4?  7.cxd4  Nc6  8.Nc3  Qd6  9.O-O  Nf6   In variation A, White has nothing better than a standard development move, like @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1nqpn2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bg5  or  10.Re1  , while in variation B, the sequence @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1nqpn2/8/3P4/2NB1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne4!  Nxe4  11.Bxe4  is surprisingly strong. The e4-bishop is fantastically placed, and Black has to be careful to survive the next moves. Something like  11...Be7  12.Ne5  Nxe5  13.Bf4!  is even worse than it looks at first.  Long story short: the IQP position with a bishop on e2 is MUCH easier for Black to handle than with a bishop on d3. The difference is so significant that we recommend avoiding the IQP after 6.Bd3 in the first place.   The way to go is completing kingside castling first. We start with  6...Nf6  and want to play ...Be7 and ...O-O next. }
7. O-O { The main line by a mile, and certainly very natural. } 7... Be7
{ This move is, quite surprisingly, an important finesse.  Inferior Alternatives  We already explored that taking on d4 is bad due to  7...cxd4?  8.cxd4  Nc6  9.Nc3  Qd6  10.Ne4!  , which gives White a significant advantage. What are the alternatives?   The move  7...b5?  is too risky for Black. White is much better developed and can attack our queenside structure quickly. We need to catch up on development first.  The move  7...Nc6  looks reasonable, but it turns out that White is better after  8.dxc5  , when  8...Qxc5  9.Nbd2  Be7  10.Nc4  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1pn2/2Pq4/8/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bxc5  9.Qe2  O-O  10.Bg5  Be7  11.Rd1  @@StartBracket@@or similar lines@@EndBracket@@ are better for White.  These variations lead to the conclusion that White's idea to capture on c5 is a serious option, and it's best for Black not to commit the knight to c6 early. After the capture on c5 we want to recapture with the queen and then have the opportunity to retreat to c7.  In this structure, after dxc5,  our knight is well-placed on d7. It covers the crucial square b6 and often has an attractive idea ...Nd7-c5,  attacking White's strong bishop.   This leads, almost due to a process of elimination, to  7...Be7  . White now has some choice. We'll now examine two paths:  A@@EndBracket@@  8.c4  Qd6  9.dxc5  Qxc5  is an excellent line to illustrate the type of position after dxc5,  which can arise in various ways. White could also take directly on move eight or after @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/1p2bppp/p3pn2/2pq4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Re1  O-O  9.dxc5  Qxc5  , which all lead to a similar structure.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/1p2bppp/p3pn2/2pq4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Re1  is White's most popular move, when after  8...O-O  , there is a split again. }
8. c4 { White attacks our queen. Where to go? } 8... Qd6
{ This is the best square. The reasoning is as follows: After White has played c4, we have pressure on d4. Therefore, White will capture on c5. The best place for our queen in this structure is the square c7. The quickest way to accomplish this setup is to recapture on c5 with the queen, ready to drop it back to c7 if necessary. }
9. dxc5 Qxc5
{ This structure, after White has captured on c5, is very common in this variation. Studying many lines for this type of scenario, which can arise in various sequences, is unnecessary. It's more important to know the best setup:  We'd like to play ...O-O, ...Nb8-d7, ...b6 and ...Bb7 to complete our development. Our queen often retreats to c7 if White decides to attack it. Our knight is best on d7, as it still allows the queen to retreat to c7 and might later find a good spot on c5.  Let's have a look at a typical sequence. }
10. Bf4 { A good move. White takes away the c7-square for our queen. } 10... b6
{ The best move order. We quickly get our bishop on the long diagonal. This is better than  10...O-O  11.Nc3  b6?  , when  12.Ne4!  is very strong. }
11. Nc3 Bb7 { Taking control of e4. } 12. Na4
{ We need to check this aggressive move. White tries to hit our weak spot b6 before we are fully coordinated.  After a slow alternative like  12.Qe2  O-O  13.Rad1  Nbd7  we can complete our development and connect rooks. After a sequence like  14.Rfe1  Rad8  15.h3  Qc8  16.Ne4  Nc5  chances are equal. }
12... Qc6
{ The only move. We cover b6 and build up a menacing battery on the long diagonal. }
13. Re1
{ White's most testing move. Currently, they can't move the f3-knight to d4 or e5 due to our mate threat. The move Re1 prepares Bf1, which finally enables the knight to move.  Now we have a choice between two good, but entirely different continuations. We'll suggest a razor-sharp move, but you have a 'Keep it Simple' style alternative. }
13... g5
{ Yes, this shocking move works! Black is behind in development, still it is possible to start an attack.  Before we continue, a word about Black's simple alternative: you may also play  13...Bd6  , which after  14.Bxd6  Qxd6  leads to a calmer position with about equal chances.   It is, however, imprecise to play  13...O-O?  , when  14.Bf1!  Nbd7  15.Nd4  Qc8  16.Nf5  leads to problems. }
14. Bxg5
{ A brave move!  White may also play  14.Bg3  g4  15.Nh4  Nbd7  , which is tough to assess. A crude but potentially deadly idea for Black is ...Rg8-g5-h5 trying to remove White's key defender. }
14... Rg8 15. Bf1
{ White needs to cover g2. After  15.Bxf6  Qxf3  16.Qxf3  Bxf3  Black is in good shape. The careless  17.Bxe7??  Rxg2+  18.Kf1  Rxh2  already leads to a mate. }
15... Nbd7
{ Black has excellent play for the pawn. We can castle queenside next and White has to defend precisely – Black has all the fun here! }
*

