{ White's most natural and best move. How to react? Let's have a look:  A@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4  looks active, but after  6.Be2  e6  7.O-O  Nf6  8.h3  Bh5  both  9.Be3  @@StartBracket@@as already covered in Keep It Simple: 1.e4@@EndBracket@@ and  9.c4  lead to an advantage for White.   B@@EndBracket@@  5...Nf6  looks natural, but  6.Be3!  is tough to meet. We don't want to trade on d4,  as after  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  White will play Nc3 next, chasing our queen. On the other hand, White attacks the c5-pawn after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/1p2pppp/p4n2/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , which turns  6...e6  7.dxc5!  into a problem.   C@@EndBracket@@  5...Nc6  6.Be3!  is a similar story to 5...Nf6. We don't want to take on d4,  but c5 is attacked. The line @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Be3  e6  7.dxc5  shows an issue of our position: the vulnerability of the c-pawn. This leads to our idea to start with @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  when  6.Be3  can be answered with  6...Nd7!  , which lends additional support to c5. }
5... e6
{ We think this move gives Black the best prospects, as the alternatives lead to problems @@StartBracket@@see the notes to 5.d4 for more information@@EndBracket@@.  After 5...e6,  White has a wide range of options. It is crucial to study these moves and appreciate their differences, as there is no general setup or concept we could apply. We must address each White option as an independent line and learn a specific response.  Of course, there are some common themes, but it is essential not to confuse our replies. Let's have an overview of White's ideas and discuss some of the key differences.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a critical move. White intends to win a pawn with dxc5,  which we stop with  6...Nd7  , as already discussed in the notes to move  5.   B@@EndBracket@@  6.c4  attacks our queen. We retreat to d8 and get fair chances.   C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is a popular choice for White. Against this move, the most straightforward recipe is  6...cxd4!  , immediately clarifying the central structure. It is the only case of the direct trade on d4,  as we don't mind fighting the IQP after White has committed the bishop to e2.   D@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  looks a bit more active than  6.Be2  , looking towards the kingside. It's crucial NOT to take on d4 early on against this move, as the arising IQP structure is much better for White than the situation after  6.Be2  cxd4!  . The difference between these two versions is discussed in more detail in the notes to these moves.   E@@EndBracket@@  6.Na3  is aimed at exploiting the weak b6-square, jumping to c4 next. We have not yet committed the b8-knight, which proves useful after  6...Nf6  7.Nc4  Nbd7  , when we safely cover our weakness. }
6. Bd3
{ White develops the bishop and prepares to castle; what could be more natural? Still, this move is less popular and critical than some alternatives.  First of all, we need to answer a key question. To take on d4 or not to take? }
6... Nf6
{ A key decision! We DON'T take on d4 now and on the next moves, but rather continue with kingside development and keep the tension.  Why is taking on d4 a mistake? Against 6.Be2,  we recommend taking on d4. Why not here? Let's compare:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  cxd4  7.cxd4  Nc6  8.Nc3  Qd6  9.O-O  Nf6   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  cxd4?  7.cxd4  Nc6  8.Nc3  Qd6  9.O-O  Nf6   In variation A, White has nothing better than a standard development move, like @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1nqpn2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bg5  or  10.Re1  , while in variation B, the sequence @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1nqpn2/8/3P4/2NB1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne4!  Nxe4  11.Bxe4  is surprisingly strong. The e4-bishop is fantastically placed, and Black has to be careful to survive the next moves. Something like  11...Be7  12.Ne5  Nxe5  13.Bf4!  is even worse than it looks at first.  Long story short: the IQP position with a bishop on e2 is MUCH easier for Black to handle than with a bishop on d3. The difference is so significant that we recommend avoiding the IQP after 6.Bd3 in the first place.   The way to go is completing kingside castling first. We start with  6...Nf6  and want to play ...Be7 and ...O-O next. }
7. O-O { The main line by a mile, and certainly very natural. } 7... Be7
{ This move is, quite surprisingly, an important finesse.  Inferior Alternatives  We already explored that taking on d4 is bad due to  7...cxd4?  8.cxd4  Nc6  9.Nc3  Qd6  10.Ne4!  , which gives White a significant advantage. What are the alternatives?   The move  7...b5?  is too risky for Black. White is much better developed and can attack our queenside structure quickly. We need to catch up on development first.  The move  7...Nc6  looks reasonable, but it turns out that White is better after  8.dxc5  , when  8...Qxc5  9.Nbd2  Be7  10.Nc4  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1pn2/2Pq4/8/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bxc5  9.Qe2  O-O  10.Bg5  Be7  11.Rd1  @@StartBracket@@or similar lines@@EndBracket@@ are better for White.  These variations lead to the conclusion that White's idea to capture on c5 is a serious option, and it's best for Black not to commit the knight to c6 early. After the capture on c5 we want to recapture with the queen and then have the opportunity to retreat to c7.  In this structure, after dxc5,  our knight is well-placed on d7. It covers the crucial square b6 and often has an attractive idea ...Nd7-c5,  attacking White's strong bishop.   This leads, almost due to a process of elimination, to  7...Be7  . White now has some choice. We'll now examine two paths:  A@@EndBracket@@  8.c4  Qd6  9.dxc5  Qxc5  is an excellent line to illustrate the type of position after dxc5,  which can arise in various ways. White could also take directly on move eight or after @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/1p2bppp/p3pn2/2pq4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Re1  O-O  9.dxc5  Qxc5  , which all lead to a similar structure.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/1p2bppp/p3pn2/2pq4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Re1  is White's most popular move, when after  8...O-O  , there is a split again. }
8. Re1
{ This is White's most popular move, which keeps options often. After our natural reply  8...O-O  White can still decide on a course of action. }
8... O-O
{ After our natural move, White has many options. The trickiest one for us is  9.c4  , but we'll have a look at  9.Bg5  , too. }
9. Bg5 { A good development move. } 9... Nbd7
{ Black has alternatives here, but we usually place the knight on d7 after 6.Bd3. Going  9...Nbd7  is a consistent choice. }
10. a4
{ This move is recommended by Stockfish but not an obvious choice for White. We examine it to demonstrate an important idea to be aware of. Now, a natural-looking move is bad for Black, the move 10...b6?. }
10... Rd8
{ The move to avoid is the natural  10...b6?  , because  11.c4  Qd6  12.d5!  is extremely dangerous for Black. We need to delay ...b6 for a moment. }
11. Qe2
{ White does not want to move the b1-knight, as  11.Nbd2  gives us the option  11...cxd4!  , when White can't win a tempo with Nc3 anymore. After  12.cxd4  h6  13.Bh4  b6  our position looks fine. }
11... cxd4
{ We still can't play  11...b6??  due to  12.c4  Qd6  13.d5  . The capture on d4 prevents this idea but allows Nc3 with a tempo on our queen. It turns out that the concrete lines work well for us. }
12. cxd4 h6
{ Inserting this move is very important. We need to kick the bishop away from g5 to open the fifth rank for our queen and allow ...Qd5-h5 later. }
13. Nc3
{ Or  13.Bh4  b6  14.Nc3  Qh5  , which shows a key idea of inserting ...h6. After  15.d5  , we have  15...Nc5  , giving us equal chances. }
13... Qd6 14. Bh4 Nh5
{ The final move to remember. Black has a fine position now, as the following lines show.  A@@EndBracket@@  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  16.Qd2  Nhf6  is comfortable for Black. We play ...Nf8 and ...Bd7 next. After the very natural  17.d5  its best to reply with  17...Nb6!  , and not the tempting  17...Nc5  18.Bc2  when Black appears to need to stabilise the knight with the undesirable  ...a5  .   B@@EndBracket@@  15.Ne4  Qb4  16.Bg3  Nxg3  17.hxg3  Nf6  also looks fine for Black. }
*

