{ After our natural move, White has many options. The trickiest one for us is  9.c4  , but we'll have a look at  9.Bg5  , too. }
9. c4
{ A critical move. It's important to remember that we need to react differently compared to 8.c4. }
9... Qd8
{ It's tough to remember, but here  9...Qd6?!  is worse! After  10.dxc5  Qxc5  11.Bf4  , it is surprisingly tough to coordinate Black's position.  11...b6  12.Nc3  Bb7  13.Na4  or @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/1p2bppp/p3pn2/2q5/2P2B2/3B1N2/PP3PPP/RN1QR1K1 b - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nbd7  12.Nc3  b6  13.Ne4!  are sample lines to illustrate the difficulties.  Why is this different to @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/1p2bppp/p3pn2/2pq4/3P4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8.c4  , when  8...Qd6!  is correct? In this case, we have not castled yet and are one move faster with the organization of the queenside. Note that after  9.dxc5  Qxc5  10.Bf4  we play  10...b6!  and avoid castling. }
10. dxc5
{ This is the principled way to play for White, now that we can't recapture with the queen.  The lines  10.Nc3  cxd4  11.Nxd4  Qc7  or @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1p2bppp/p3pn2/2p5/2PP4/3B1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bf4  Bd6  look less testing. }
10... Nbd7
{ The best place for our knight is c5, so let's try to get there ASAP. } 11. c6
{ White decides to weaken our pawn structure. They can't keep the extra pawn anyway, as  11.b4  a5!  shows.   Of course, White could play  11.Nc3  , but  11...Nxc5  12.Bc2  Qxd1  13.Rxd1  b6  looks fine for Black. White has the better development, but we have no weaknesses. }
11... bxc6
{ Our c-pawn is isolated, but we have the simple plan ...Bb7 and ...c5, when our bishop finds a good spot on the long diagonal. Let's look closely at a natural sequence like the following one. }
12. Bf4 Bb7 13. Nc3 c5
{ This type of pawn formation is well-known and fine for Black. White can't put any pressure on our split queenside pawns, and our pieces are harmoniously placed.  Stockfish now points out a fascinating idea. After the move  14.h3  @@StartBracket@@White wants to secure the bishop on the f4-h2 diagonal to prevent a later ...Nh5 and ...Qc7 idea@@EndBracket@@ it suggests  14...Ra7!?  15.Bc2  Qa8  , which exerts some pressure on the diagonal but also prepares ...Rd8 next, placing the rook on the open file. }
