5... e6
{ We think this move gives Black the best prospects, as the alternatives lead to problems @@StartBracket@@see the notes to 5.d4 for more information@@EndBracket@@.  After 5...e6,  White has a wide range of options. It is crucial to study these moves and appreciate their differences, as there is no general setup or concept we could apply. We must address each White option as an independent line and learn a specific response.  Of course, there are some common themes, but it is essential not to confuse our replies. Let's have an overview of White's ideas and discuss some of the key differences.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a critical move. White intends to win a pawn with dxc5,  which we stop with  6...Nd7  , as already discussed in the notes to move  5.   B@@EndBracket@@  6.c4  attacks our queen. We retreat to d8 and get fair chances.   C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is a popular choice for White. Against this move, the most straightforward recipe is  6...cxd4!  , immediately clarifying the central structure. It is the only case of the direct trade on d4,  as we don't mind fighting the IQP after White has committed the bishop to e2.   D@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  looks a bit more active than  6.Be2  , looking towards the kingside. It's crucial NOT to take on d4 early on against this move, as the arising IQP structure is much better for White than the situation after  6.Be2  cxd4!  . The difference between these two versions is discussed in more detail in the notes to these moves.   E@@EndBracket@@  6.Na3  is aimed at exploiting the weak b6-square, jumping to c4 next. We have not yet committed the b8-knight, which proves useful after  6...Nf6  7.Nc4  Nbd7  , when we safely cover our weakness. }
6. Be3
{ This is White's most promising move. They increase the pressure on c5 and do not yet determine how the King's bishop will be developed. }
6... Nd7
{ We already mentioned this move before. The move 6...Nd7 is an important resource for Black and the reason why we suggest this system against the Alapin. What's the idea of 6...Nd7?  The main point is that White threatened to take on c5,  winning a pawn. We can't play  6...Nf6?  as  7.dxc5  just nets a pawn for White.   On the other hand, the capture on d4 is also undesirable, as  6...cxd4  8.cxd4  Nf6  9.Nc3  wins a useful tempo for White. They also still have the option to develop the king's bishop to d3 in the arising IQP position, a scenario we want to avoid. We can compare this to 6.Bd3,  when we avoid the capture as well.   Looking at the drawbacks of these alternatives,  6...Nd7  emerges as a serious option by the process of elimination. Now, c5 is safely covered and  7.dxc5?!  Qxd1+  8.Kxd1  Bxc5  regains the pawn with a good game.   We'll now examine the moves  7.Be2  ,  7.Nbd2  and  7.c4  . The position after 6...Nd7 is still quite unexplored, but these moves often occur in online games. }
7. c4
{ Yet another case of White playing c4, attacking our queen. Where do we go? }
7... Qc6
{ A difficult move! In other cases of c4,  we suggest retreating to d6,  but here the square c6 is better. The difference between the two moves is not obvious and only becomes clearer if you examine the following sequence:  A@@EndBracket@@  7...Qd6?!  8.Nc3  Ngf6  9.Be2  b6  10.O-O  Bb7  and now  11.dxc5!  is annoying, as  11...Qxd1  12.Rfxd1  Bxc5  13.Nd4  gives White some pressure. The idea of a3 + b4,  paired with Na4,  is tough to meet.   B@@EndBracket@@  7...Qc6!  8.Nc3  Ngf6  9.Be2  b6  10.O-O  Bb7  is our recommendation, when  11.dxc5?!  Bxc5  is already very comfortable for Black. }
8. Nc3
{ The natural move. Black is not bothered by  8.d5  exd5  9.cxd5  Qc7  when we have an easy development with ...Bd6 and ...Ngf6. White's d-pawn may prove to be weak in the long run. }
8... Ngf6 9. Be2 b6
{ We suggest this move, our usual way of developing the bishop. Here, it is also possible to capture on d4,  as  8...cxd4  9.Nxd4  Qxg2  seems fine for Black, but it's messy. Playing the simpler 9...b6 is our choice. }
10. O-O
{ White has some alternatives here, but they don't seem critical.  A@@EndBracket@@  10.dxc5  Bxc5  is very nice for Black already.   B@@EndBracket@@  10.d5  exd5  11.cxd5  Qc7  also looks OK. We'll develop with ...Bd6 and ...O-O,  as we also play in similar cases.   C@@EndBracket@@  10.Ne5  Qc7  11.Bf3  cxd4  12.Bxd4  Bb7  also leads nowhere for White. They could grab material with  12.Bxa8?  but  12...dxe3  13.Nd3  exf3+  14.Nxf2  Ne5  gives Black fantastic play on the dark squares. White is on the ropes here. }
10... Bb7 11. d5 { White's aggressive choice leads to fun complications. }
11... exd5 12. cxd5
{ White can also play  12.Nxd5  , when there is a choice between taking the offered pawn or ignoring the sacrifice. It is similar to  12.cxd5  when the pawn grab leads to the same position.   If you don't want to take d5,   12.Nxd5  Bd6  is a perfectly fine alternative. }
12... Qc7
{ We suggest declining the sacrifice. It is possible to grab the pawn as  12...Nxd5  13.Nxd5  Qxd5  14.Qxd5  Bxd5  15.Rfd1  Nf6  gives White compensation for the pawn, but not more than that.   Our preferred move,  12...Qc7  keeps queens on the board and is more ambitious. Our idea, as usual after White has pushed the d-pawn, is a development scheme with ...Bd6 and ...O-O,  later trying to put more pressure on d5. }
13. Nh4
{ This is still important to study, as you could easily get into trouble after this move. What's best now? }
13... g6
{ We simply stop the knight jump to f5.  It is possible to play  13...Bd6  , but after  14.Nf5  , the only good move is  14...O-O!  , as taking on h2 is far too risky. This is the possible pitfall we need to avoid.   However, the move  13...g6  prevents any inconvenience. We want to play ...Bd6 and ...O-O,  with a fine position.  White could try  14.g3  Bd6  15.Bh6  , when we have the choice between  15...Bf8  , accepting  16.Bf4  Bd6  17.Bh6  , or go for the creative move @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1bqn1p1p/pp1b1npB/2pP4/7N/2N3P1/PP2BP1P/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 2 15@@EndFEN@@  15....O-O-O  , which might shock your opponent! White's pieces on h4 and h6 are oddly placed for the central struggle. The computer calls it 'equal', but it's not boring, for sure! }
