{ A natural development. White may also play  7.Bd3  , but it's considerably less popular. Similar to our approach against 6.Bd3,  we can hold the tension with ...Ngf6,  ...Be7 and ...O-O. }
7... cxd4
{ We like this solution, as taking on d4 is our recipe against 6.Be2, as well. We argue that the IQP structure is more comfortable for Black once White has committed the bishop to the less active e2-square @@StartBracket@@compare to 6.Bd3, when we DON'T exchange on d4@@EndBracket@@.  In the line @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  cxd4  7.cxd4  we play  7...Nc6  , attacking White's weakness on d4. With @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  Nd7  inserted, this is not possible anymore. Due to the somewhat more passive knight, this version is slightly less attractive for Black.  Still, we think that Black obtains fair chances. Let's have a closer look. }
8. cxd4
{ White's usual reply. They are happy to get the IQP and play Nc3 soon, gaining a tempo on our queen.  White can take with a piece, too. A line like  8.Bxd4  Ngf6  9.O-O  Bd6  is quite harmless, though. We'll ultimately complete development with ...b6 and ...Bb7,  similar to other lines in this chapter after White's d-pawn is traded for our c-pawn. }
8... Ngf6
{ We need to get our king out of the middle of the board as soon as possible. }
9. Nc3 Qd6
{ We choose the same retreat square after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p3ppp/p3p3/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  cxd4  7.cxd4  Nc6  8.Nc3  Qd6  , so this move is consistent. }
10. O-O Be7
{ We are getting closer to kingside castling. It's important to avoid  10...b5?  11.d5!  Nxd5  12.Nxd5  Qxd5  13.Qc2  , giving White a crushing attack. We need to develop the bishop first. }
11. Qd2
{ That is the only challenging move. White needs to get the idea of Bf4 on the map to make something out of the development advantage. Against a slower continuation, we'd play ...O-O and ...b5, the idea we employ against 11.Qd2, as well. }
11... b5
{ The most ambitious move. We'd like to develop the bishop to the dream square b7.  An alternative is  11...Nb6  , emphasizing control of d5. In this setup, Black aims to develop the bishop with ...Bd7-c6. }
12. Bf4 { White realizes their idea and pushes our queen to b6. } 12... Qb6
{ Now we have reached a crucial moment. We want to play ...Bb7 next, which adds control to the blockading square d5 and prevents the advance of the d-pawn. The critical move is White's attempt to open the position immediately, exploiting the lead in development. }
13. d5
{ If White avoids this move, we'll play ...Bb7 and ...O-O, reaching a good position versus the IQP. }
13... exd5
{ This looks slightly more precise than  13...Nxd5  , when after  14.Nxd5  exd5  White has other options than  15.Qxd5  , which would transpose to our suggestion. Moves like  15.Rac1  or  15.Rfe1  are not terrible for Black but still worth avoiding. }
14. Nxd5
{ The natural reply. Sophisticated tries like  14.Rac1  Bb4  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/3nbppp/pq3n2/1p1p4/5B2/2N2N2/PP1QBPPP/R4RK1 w kq - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Rfe1  Nc5  lead to nothing special for White, either. }
14... Nxd5 15. Qxd5 Bb7
{ White has a lead in development, but we are in time to coordinate. Now  16.Qf5  Qf6  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/3nbppp/pq6/1p1Q4/5B2/5N2/PP2BPPP/R4RK1 b kq - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  16.Qd4  Bf6  are possible continuations, showing that we have nothing to fear. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Alapin Setups 2.Nf3 a6 3.c3 and 2.c3"]
[Black "4B | Delayed Alapin with 3.c3 | White plays 5.d4 / 6.Be3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. c3
{ This 'delayed Alapin' is recommended in many repertoire books, for example, in Christof's Keep It Simple: 1.e4 and Wesley So's Lifetime Repertoire.  As we show in this repertoire, the O'Kelly is by no means easy to play against. If you construct a repertoire for White, you need pragmatic solutions against rare lines. In the case of the O'Kelly, many lines for White are not attractive @@StartBracket@@  3.d4  @@EndBracket@@ or rather sophisticated @@StartBracket@@  3.c4  and  3.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@.  The line  3.c3  is a good solution for White, as it poses problems, but does not require that much work for White, in comparison to the mentioned alternatives. }
3... d5
{ We think this line gives Black the best chances against 3.c3.  The other satisfactory option is  3...e6  , but  4.d4  d5  5.e5  would transpose to a French Defence, which does not fit well with our repertoire concept. }
4. exd5
{ That's White's only challenging move. You sometimes meet  4.e5?!  , which is well answered with  4...Bg4  . This is best compared to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.e5?!  , when we recommend  3...Nc6  4.d4  Bf5  5.Be2  e6  6.O-O  cxd4  7.cxd4  Bg4  , leading to fine play for Black.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.e5?!  Bg4  we are likely to reach a similar scenario with the extra move ...a6,  as we managed to develop the bishop to g4 in one go. }
4... Qxd5
{ Well, you shouldn't move the queen too early in the opening – unless it's good 😝  Here, Black's play is justified, as White has already committed a pawn to c3. Therefore, the easy tempo-gain Nc3 is off the table @@StartBracket@@compare to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  @@EndBracket@@  .   Here, in the Alapin, our queen is not so easily chased around but still could be vulnerable in the middle of the board. We'll look closer at White's options on move six, as  5.d4  e6  is the almost universal continuation. We'll also briefly check if White can delay the move d4,  but it does not make a substantial difference. }
5. d4
{ White's most natural and best move. How to react? Let's have a look:  A@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4  looks active, but after  6.Be2  e6  7.O-O  Nf6  8.h3  Bh5  both  9.Be3  @@StartBracket@@as already covered in Keep It Simple: 1.e4@@EndBracket@@ and  9.c4  lead to an advantage for White.   B@@EndBracket@@  5...Nf6  looks natural, but  6.Be3!  is tough to meet. We don't want to trade on d4,  as after  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  White will play Nc3 next, chasing our queen. On the other hand, White attacks the c5-pawn after @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/1p2pppp/p4n2/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , which turns  6...e6  7.dxc5!  into a problem.   C@@EndBracket@@  5...Nc6  6.Be3!  is a similar story to 5...Nf6. We don't want to take on d4,  but c5 is attacked. The line @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Be3  e6  7.dxc5  shows an issue of our position: the vulnerability of the c-pawn. This leads to our idea to start with @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/1p2pppp/p7/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  when  6.Be3  can be answered with  6...Nd7!  , which lends additional support to c5. }
5... e6
{ We think this move gives Black the best prospects, as the alternatives lead to problems @@StartBracket@@see the notes to 5.d4 for more information@@EndBracket@@.  After 5...e6,  White has a wide range of options. It is crucial to study these moves and appreciate their differences, as there is no general setup or concept we could apply. We must address each White option as an independent line and learn a specific response.  Of course, there are some common themes, but it is essential not to confuse our replies. Let's have an overview of White's ideas and discuss some of the key differences.  A@@EndBracket@@  6.Be3  is a critical move. White intends to win a pawn with dxc5,  which we stop with  6...Nd7  , as already discussed in the notes to move  5.   B@@EndBracket@@  6.c4  attacks our queen. We retreat to d8 and get fair chances.   C@@EndBracket@@  6.Be2  is a popular choice for White. Against this move, the most straightforward recipe is  6...cxd4!  , immediately clarifying the central structure. It is the only case of the direct trade on d4,  as we don't mind fighting the IQP after White has committed the bishop to e2.   D@@EndBracket@@  6.Bd3  looks a bit more active than  6.Be2  , looking towards the kingside. It's crucial NOT to take on d4 early on against this move, as the arising IQP structure is much better for White than the situation after  6.Be2  cxd4!  . The difference between these two versions is discussed in more detail in the notes to these moves.   E@@EndBracket@@  6.Na3  is aimed at exploiting the weak b6-square, jumping to c4 next. We have not yet committed the b8-knight, which proves useful after  6...Nf6  7.Nc4  Nbd7  , when we safely cover our weakness. }
6. Be3
{ This is White's most promising move. They increase the pressure on c5 and do not yet determine how the King's bishop will be developed. }
6... Nd7
{ We already mentioned this move before. The move 6...Nd7 is an important resource for Black and the reason why we suggest this system against the Alapin. What's the idea of 6...Nd7?  The main point is that White threatened to take on c5,  winning a pawn. We can't play  6...Nf6?  as  7.dxc5  just nets a pawn for White.   On the other hand, the capture on d4 is also undesirable, as  6...cxd4  8.cxd4  Nf6  9.Nc3  wins a useful tempo for White. They also still have the option to develop the king's bishop to d3 in the arising IQP position, a scenario we want to avoid. We can compare this to 6.Bd3,  when we avoid the capture as well.   Looking at the drawbacks of these alternatives,  6...Nd7  emerges as a serious option by the process of elimination. Now, c5 is safely covered and  7.dxc5?!  Qxd1+  8.Kxd1  Bxc5  regains the pawn with a good game.   We'll now examine the moves  7.Be2  ,  7.Nbd2  and  7.c4  . The position after 6...Nd7 is still quite unexplored, but these moves often occur in online games. }
7. Nbd2
{ This is White's most popular reply to our fresh idea 6...Nd7. White develops the knight and might continue with either Nc4 or Bc4 next. In any case, our reply is natural – develop the kingside. }
7... Ngf6 { Alright, that was easy. We need to get our kingside developed. } 8.
Bc4
{ This is White's usual continuation, but it is not challenging for Black.  They could also play  8.c4  when  8...Qc6  9.Be2  b6  is undoubtedly fine for Black. White's knight is poorly placed in this structure, looking at the own c4-pawn. The pawn push c4 should be combined with Nc3,  as in multiple lines of the current chapter.   The move  8.Nc4  is unpopular, as it runs into  8...b5!  with tempo. We usually suggest playing the more restrained ...b6,  but here gaining a tempo is very attractive. }
8... Qc6
{ We have a setup with ...b6 and ...Bb7 in mind, setting up a battery on the long diagonal.  The move  8...Qd6  is not a mistake but less attractive in comparison. }
9. O-O b6
{ The move  9...b5  is also playable but somewhat risky. The sequence  10.Be2  Bb7  11.a4  c4  12.b3  shows a typical problem of the early queenside expansion. }
10. Re1
{ Here,  10.Ne5?!  Nxe5  11.dxe5  Bb7!  already looks slightly better for us. }
10... Bb7
{ It's a good moment to take stock already. White has developed their pieces quickly, but they don't put any pressure on us. We are ready to prepare kingside castling while White has no clear way forward.  A critical struggle will be about the central tension. Both sides need to consider if they want to capture on c5/d4. We must be cautious about the capture, as we are currently behind in development. We should first castle and connect rooks before considering any opening of the position. }
