[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Closed Sicilian and Grand-Prix-Attack after 2.Nc3"]
[Black "Introduction to the Closed Sicilian and Grand Prix"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ White develops their queen's knight first. This move does not yet reveal White's intentions, though. They have some choice of how to proceed afterwards. Here's an overview of possible ideas:  A@@EndBracket@@ Play a setup with g3, which is usually called Closed Sicilian.  B@@EndBracket@@ Play the pawn to f4 next, which is known as the Grand Prix Attack.  C@@EndBracket@@ They can still play Nf3 or Nge2, intending to transpose to an open Sicilian with d2-d4. This approach is common in master-level play but less so in amateur games.  We need to play in a way that makes sense in all three scenarios. }
2... a6
{ Well, if the move ...a6 works against 2.Nf3,  it will undoubtedly work against 2.Nc3,  as well!  Jokes aside, this is the most flexible move for us. If White continues with  3.Nf3  or  3.Nge2  , going for approach C mentioned before, we can still reach a typical O'Kelly position. Here are the common sequences to do that:   3.Nf3  or  3.Nge2  b5  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e6  transposes to the Chapter Tricky Knights. You'll often meet this line if you play higher-level opposition, as they use 2.Nc3 sometimes as a move order device. They might have lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  d6  3.d4  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  Nc6  3.Bb5  in mind, but against other second moves, prefer to switch to an open Sicilian.  Most of the time, White does not have a transposition to an open Sicilian in mind, but rather goes for a setup with g3 @@StartBracket@@Closed Sicilian@@EndBracket@@ or f4 @@StartBracket@@Grand Prix@@EndBracket@@, In both cases, we'll play a quick ...b7-b5 advance and use ...Bb7 to put pressure on White's e-pawn.  From a conceptual point of view, it is instructive to note that we play a quick ...b7-b5 only after White has committed a knight to c3. Lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  a6  3.g3  b5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.Nc3  b5  are examples of this approach. Once a knight has appeared on c3,  the idea b5-b4 gains strength, in particular in reply to a2-a4 by White.  We can compare this to a sequence like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.d3  , when  3...b5?!  does make a lot less sense, as  4.a4  attacks the queenside, and the reply  4...b4  does not attack anything.  Alright, back to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  a6  . We have already learned that  3.f4  and  3.g3  are the major options that don't transpose to a different chapter. In addition, we'll also briefly check  3.a4  , as this move is sometimes met in online games. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Closed Sicilian and Grand-Prix-Attack after 2.Nc3"]
[Black "5A | White stops ...b7-b5 with 3.a4 |"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 a6 3. a4
{ This move is not considered dangerous but is sometimes met in online games. We mainly include it to show what to do when White stops our usual move ...b5 in its tracks. }
3... e6
{ We prepare the move ...d5,  a familiar sight in this chapter.  A good alternative is  3...Nc6  , which still retains ideas involving ...g6.  A general note: we are happy about seeing the move a4 on the board. White has weakened their queenside a bit for little benefit.  Now, after  3...e6  , White has some choice. We don't want to explore this rare line deeply and focus on a popular move in online games, the move  4.Bc4  . }
4. Bc4
{ As we will see, this move is harmless if you know the best reply. White has plenty of alternatives, though. In all cases, it is possible to continue with ...d5 – here are some examples to illustrate.  A@@EndBracket@@  4.f4  d5  5.d3  Nc6  6.Nf3  , when many setups look good.  6...b6  or  6...g6  come to mind.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.g3  d5  5.exd5  exd5  6.Bg2  Nf6  leads to a healthy position, too. We can develop easily.   C@@EndBracket@@  4.Nf3  d5  5.exd5  exd5  6.d4  Nf6  also looks fine for Black. The inclusion of ...a7-a6 and a2-a4 favours Black, as White can't play a disturbing Bb5+ and the queenside weaknesses, like the b4-square, are annoying for White.   Against  4.Nf3  , the move  4...Nc6  is also fine. White could go for  5.d4  cxd4  6.Nxd4  , leading to an open Sicilian Taimanov, in which White has played the strange move a4. These lines are unexplored but certainly fine for Black. }
4... Nf6
{ An important move to remember! We'd like to play ...d5 next, but don't need to be afraid of the reply  5.e5  – let's explore why. }
5. e5
{ A bad move, but it is essential to know why.  Objectively better is  5.d3  , when  5...d5  leads to a good position for Black – but White is not worse, at least. After a natural sequence like  6.exd5  exd5  7.Bb3  Nc6  8.Bg5  Be6  we have a comfortable development, but White has no serious weaknesses and keeps the balance. }
5... d5 { That's the reason why White's pawn advance falls short. } 6. exf6
{ Or  6.exd6  Bxd6  , when Black has better central control and easy development. White has lost time with multiple moves of the e-pawn. }
6... dxc4 7. fxg7 Bxg7 8. Qg4
{ This looks scary at first. White attacks our bishop and one of the c-pawns. }
8... O-O { We can simply give up the pawn and speed up development. } 9. Qxc4
Nc6
{ We have a fantastic position for the pawn. White has difficulty meeting the idea ...Nd4,  which places the knight on a dominant square.  After  10.Qxc5?  Nd4  Black's attack is far too strong already, as we are set to gain more time on the misplaced white queen. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Closed Sicilian and Grand-Prix-Attack after 2.Nc3"]
[Black "5B | Grand Prix with 3.f4 |"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 a6 3. f4
{ The signal move for the Grand Prix Attack. The Grand Prix is one of the openings that benefits from its cool name but is not that dangerous if Black knows what to do.  It earned the name Grand Prix from a series of tournaments in the UK in the 1980s. Players like Mark Hebden and Julian Hodgson used it with great success, winning many events.  Our line 2...a6 is an excellent setup if White has the Grand Prix in mind. The Grand Prix usually involves a bishop development to b5 or c4,  which is clearly off the table after our natural reply  3...b5  . }
3... b5
{ It's also possible to play  3...e6  first and continue with ...b5 on the next move. We usually play a quick ...b5 against a knight on c3. Thus starting with  3...b5  is a bit more consistent and our choice. }
4. Nf3
{ White develops the knight to its natural square. White's general idea in the Grand Prix is to start play on the kingside, where White has more space at the moment.  We seek to play against White's centre, starting with  4...Bb7  . The bishop puts pressure on the e4-pawn. }
4... Bb7
{ White has to worry about ...b5-b4 now, pushing the crucial defender of the e4-pawn away. }
5. d3
{ The e-pawn needed protection. It's important to note that White initially intended to place their bishop outside the pawn chain, to c4 or b5. Our quick queenside expansion has prevented this, which will often catch White players wrong-footed, as they have to play a different setup compared to what they usually get on the board. }
5... e6
{ A good move, giving our bishop some scope. In most cases, we want to play ...d7-d5 soon, hitting at White's centre again. Now, after  5...e6  , White has some choice.  The most common reply is  6.g3  , but this setup leads to a very similar play as we examine via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.g3  , when  3...b5  4.Bg2  Bb7  5.d3  e6  6.f4  is the main line. In this case, we play  6...Be7  , going for ...d5 next. The rationale behind this move order finesse is explained in the notes to this line.  Here, in a very similar spot, we can play in the same way, answering @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.f4  b5  4.Nf3  Bb7  5.d3  e6  6.g3  with  6...Be7  . A transposition to 3.g3 lines is very likely in this case.  We'll now examine a more aggressive option for White, pushing the g-pawn even further. }
6. g4
{ White's most aggressive option, for sure.  As mentioned before, against  6.g3  , we advise you to play  6...Be7  first, delaying the move ...d5 for a while.   A similar answer is possible to  6.Be2  , which you'll also meet from time to time. }
6... b4
{ We recommend this move, planning to meet  7.Ne2  with  7...d5  . There are many alternatives for Black – let's look at why some are dubious, and some are possible, but not our choice.   A@@EndBracket@@  6...d5?!  is questionable due to  7.exd5  exd5  8.Qe2+  , when  8...Be7  9.g5!  takes advantage of the advanced g-pawn. We have no good way to develop our knight.   B@@EndBracket@@  6...Be7?!  7.g5!  is a similar story.   C@@EndBracket@@  6...Nf6  is the sharpest move and the best alternative. After  7.g5  Nh5  8.Ne5  g6  9.Be2  Black can play  9...d6  or  9...f6  , which leads to crazy complications that are not easy to master in practice. Objectively, Black is fine – but we felt it is not an economical solution to a variation as rare as 6.g4. Our solution is simpler to handle. }
7. Ne2 d5
{ We hit White's e-pawn, our normal approach against early f4-systems. We also thought about the move order  7...h5  , but after  8.g5!  White threatens the irritating move g5-g6. We can't play  8...g6?  , as the plan  9.Nh4  , followed by Bg2,  O-O and f4-f5 is crushing. }
8. e5 h5
{ Very important! We must play this preemptive strike on the kingside before White manages to organize their forces. }
9. gxh5
{ The only good move, as  9.g5?  gives up any hope on the kingside after  9...Ne7  . With the kingside locked, our advantage in the centre and queenside becomes even more valuable. }
9... Rxh5 10. Ng3 Rh8
{ Job done, return home! We have reached a fighting position with chances for both sides.  It's important to note that we can still, and often will, castle queenside. It does not matter much that we have moved the pawns on this side of the board. Our king will still be safe, as it is surrounded by many minor pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Closed Sicilian and Grand-Prix-Attack after 2.Nc3"]
[Black "5C | Closed Sicilian with 3.g3 | White plays 6.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 a6 3. g3
{ White opts for the Closed Sicilian. They intend to fianchetto the bishop, which safely protects the e-pawn.  A common idea for White is a later kingside offensive, based on pushing the pawns forward. Often it starts with f2-f4, followed by the g-pawn. We'll see some of these ideas in the lines we are about to examine. }
3... b5
{ Here we go. We are playing multiple pawn moves on the queenside and neglecting development, but White's setup is also slow. Our general idea is playing ...Bb7 next to increase pressure on White's centre. }
4. Bg2 { White's natural continuation after 3.g3. } 4... Bb7
{ We challenge White's fianchettoed bishop and start to put some pressure on the e4-pawn. White usually continues with  5.d3  now, but there are some alternatives. The knight moves to e2 and f3 are possible but likely have little independent value. Let's have a look:  A@@EndBracket@@  5.Nge2  e6  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/1b1ppppp/p7/1pp5/4P3/2N3P1/PPPP1PBP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nge2  e6  6.O-O  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  b4  leads to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.Nc3  , the Tricky Knights chapter.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.Nf3  e6  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  is the same story.  Note that @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/1b1ppppp/p7/1pp5/4P3/2N2NP1/PPPP1PBP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b4?  6.Na4  is bad for Black, as the c5-pawn is attacked. In both cases, White does not need to continue with d2-d4 but may also play d2-d3,  which will be very similar to our main line 5.d3.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.f4  or  5.Nh3  has also been tried. Still, White can hardly do without playing d2-d3 in the long run, so again this will transpose to 5.d3-territory. }
5. d3
{ By far, White's most popular move. As mentioned in the notes to 4...Bb7, the alternatives are mostly transpositional. }
5... e6
{ Finally, we move a centre pawn!  It's important to note that we don't always intend to play ...d5 in the 3.g3 lines. This is different to our approach against the Grand Prix when this is commonplace. We will, however, play based on ...d5 against White's popular continuation  6.f4  .  This makes it easier to remember: If White plays an early f4,  going for ...d5 is a good reply.  Why is ...d5 a good idea versus f4-setups and not so much versus others? We are behind in development. If we play ...d5,  White may capture on d5 to open the game quickly.  This is far less of an issue after f4 is on the board. The pawn move did not help White's development and worsened our opponent's pieces. It blocks the c1-bishop and takes away f4 for a knight.  Think about this line:  6.Nge2  d5?  7.exd5  exd5  8.Nf4  Nf6  9.Qf3  and Black loses the d5-pawn! Once the move f4 is on the board, we don't need to worry about such a scenario.   What options does White have now? We'll examine all three knight moves @@StartBracket@@  6.Nf3  ,  6.Nge2  ,  6.Nh3  @@EndBracket@@ and  6.f4  , the most popular choice. }
6. Nf3
{ White plays a healthy development move. It is not very popular, though. White often starts with 2.Nc3 to play a setup involving f2-f4 and only then Ng1-f3,  building up a pawn advance on the kingside. We still like to cover 6.Nf3 briefly, showing a typical pitfall. Should we reply to the move with  6...d5? }
6... Be7
{ It is much better to avoid  6...d5?  , as  7.exd5  exd5  8.O-O  Nf6  9.Re1+  Be7  10.Nh4  is already crushing. We discussed the crucial timing of ...d5 before – it should be avoided altogether if White plays without pushing the f-pawn.   Instead, we suggest playing based on ...Be7 and ...d6,  keeping some flexibility in the centre. We went for  6...Be7  as the main move order, but starting with  6...d6  also would work fine. }
7. O-O d6
{ Again,  7...d5?  is badly timed due to  8.exd5  exd5  9.Re1  , when  9...Nf6  10.Nh4  is great for White.  Instead, our suggested setup with ...d6 is very flexible. We'll play ...Nf6 and ...O-O next and then decide how to continue. }
8. Be3 Nf6 9. h3
{ White stops a potential ...Ng4 jump.  They could also play  9.e5  dxe5  10.Nxe5  Bxg2  11.Kxg2  O-O  , when chances are equal. We should fight the strong e5-knight with ...Qc7 and try to use the d5-square for our knight in the long run. }
9... O-O
{ A good moment to take stock. We have completed kingside castling and enjoy a harmonious position. There are plenty of possibilities to continue from here, as the play is not concrete.  A good plan worth pointing out is: playing ...Nc6, ...Nd7 and ...Bf6, activating the bishop and controlling the central dark squares. However, there are many possible alternatives. It is also feasible to play ... d6-d5 soon, which has become an option after we have managed kingside castling.  Our play against 6.Nf3 is similar to 6.Nge2, if White plays without a later f2-f4. Going for ...d6 is a flexible setup that works well. }
