[Black "5C | Closed Sicilian with 3.g3 | White plays 6.Nh3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 a6 3. g3
{ White opts for the Closed Sicilian. They intend to fianchetto the bishop, which safely protects the e-pawn.  A common idea for White is a later kingside offensive, based on pushing the pawns forward. Often it starts with f2-f4, followed by the g-pawn. We'll see some of these ideas in the lines we are about to examine. }
3... b5
{ Here we go. We are playing multiple pawn moves on the queenside and neglecting development, but White's setup is also slow. Our general idea is playing ...Bb7 next to increase pressure on White's centre. }
4. Bg2 { White's natural continuation after 3.g3. } 4... Bb7
{ We challenge White's fianchettoed bishop and start to put some pressure on the e4-pawn. White usually continues with  5.d3  now, but there are some alternatives. The knight moves to e2 and f3 are possible but likely have little independent value. Let's have a look:  A@@EndBracket@@  5.Nge2  e6  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  or @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/1b1ppppp/p7/1pp5/4P3/2N3P1/PPPP1PBP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nge2  e6  6.O-O  Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  b4  leads to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.Nc3  , the Tricky Knights chapter.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.Nf3  e6  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  is the same story.  Note that @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/1b1ppppp/p7/1pp5/4P3/2N2NP1/PPPP1PBP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b4?  6.Na4  is bad for Black, as the c5-pawn is attacked. In both cases, White does not need to continue with d2-d4 but may also play d2-d3,  which will be very similar to our main line 5.d3.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.f4  or  5.Nh3  has also been tried. Still, White can hardly do without playing d2-d3 in the long run, so again this will transpose to 5.d3-territory. }
5. d3
{ By far, White's most popular move. As mentioned in the notes to 4...Bb7, the alternatives are mostly transpositional. }
5... e6
{ Finally, we move a centre pawn!  It's important to note that we don't always intend to play ...d5 in the 3.g3 lines. This is different to our approach against the Grand Prix when this is commonplace. We will, however, play based on ...d5 against White's popular continuation  6.f4  .  This makes it easier to remember: If White plays an early f4,  going for ...d5 is a good reply.  Why is ...d5 a good idea versus f4-setups and not so much versus others? We are behind in development. If we play ...d5,  White may capture on d5 to open the game quickly.  This is far less of an issue after f4 is on the board. The pawn move did not help White's development and worsened our opponent's pieces. It blocks the c1-bishop and takes away f4 for a knight.  Think about this line:  6.Nge2  d5?  7.exd5  exd5  8.Nf4  Nf6  9.Qf3  and Black loses the d5-pawn! Once the move f4 is on the board, we don't need to worry about such a scenario.   What options does White have now? We'll examine all three knight moves @@StartBracket@@  6.Nf3  ,  6.Nge2  ,  6.Nh3  @@EndBracket@@ and  6.f4  , the most popular choice. }
6. Nh3
{ An interesting setup for White. They prepare kingside castling but retain the option to play the f-pawn soon. }
6... Be7
{ We recommend this interesting and flexible move.  Again, you need to avoid  6...d5??  7.exd5  exd5  8.Nf4  , when Black's centre collapses. }
7. O-O Nc6
{ It is interesting to compare this position to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/1b1p1ppp/p3p3/1pp5/4P3/2NP2P1/PPP2PBP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nf3  Be7  7.O-O  , when we suggest  7...d6  . In this situation, White's f-pawn is obstructed.   Here, however, White can answer  7...d6  with  8.f4  , which is dangerous. We should be ready for the f-pawn-push.   Let's have a look at what happens after our suggestion  7...Nc6  . }
8. f4
{ Clearly a critical move. An enterprising alternative for White is  8.e5!?  , when  8...Qc7  9.Re1  f5!?  or @@StartFEN@@r3k1nr/1bqpbppp/p1n1p3/1pp1P3/8/2NP2PN/PPP2PBP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bf4  h6  leads to complicated play. We have prepared ...g5 and may still castle to the queenside. }
8... h5
{ Here we go! 'Fight fire with fire' is a good way to describe our counterpunch to 8.f4. }
9. f5 Nf6
{ The point of 8...h5 was twofold:  1@@EndBracket@@ In some cases, we might play ...h4, but this is not the only idea. In fact, we should only play ...h4 if we are sure that the h-file opens and White can't respond with g4. Keeping the pawn on h5 is usually better.  2@@EndBracket@@ We ensure that White can't strengthen their initiative with the push of the g-pawn. }
10. Bf4
{ White connects to the e5-square and prevents our knight from using it. We have other options, though. }
10... c4
{ Just one idea of many.  Instead,  10...b4  11.Na4  e5  12.Be3  Ng4  is an attractive alternative.   As are  10...Qb6  or  10...Ng4  . }
11. d4
{ A bad move – let's figure out why.  A better choice for White would be  11.Nf2  , when  11...Qb6  is a good reply. Pinning the knight sets up the ideas ...h4 and ...Ng4. }
11... Qb6 12. e5
{ Relatively best.  After  12.Ne2?  e5  13.Be3  Ng4  White might as well resign. }
12... Ng4 13. Nf2
{ Now we can't grab d4, as the b7-bishop lacks protection. Any way to address that? }
13... O-O-O
{ Very strong! White's centre is crumbling now. A cool line to illustrate this is  14.Nxg4  hxg4  15.Be3  Nxe5!  , winning the centre pawn. }
