[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Morra Gambit 2.d4 and Wing Gambit 2.b4 / 3.b4"]
[Black "Introduction to Gambits"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ In this chapter we will examine two aggressive options for White against the Sicilian, the Smith-Morra Gambit and the Wing Gambit. Here's a quick overview to start our coverage.  The Smith-Morra Gambit  This Gambit arises after  2.d4  cxd4  3.c3  dxc3  4.Nxc3  and is White's most popular gambit continuation against the Sicilian Defence. It is more or less never played on the professional level but quite frequently seen in online play or at the club level.  Is it a bad opening line for White, then? Well, it's unpopular amongst higher-rated players because Black has a wide range of promising options. White might still get reasonable compensation for the pawn, but it is not easy at all to prove and quite theoretically demanding for White.  At the club level, one attraction for White is that the setup Nc3,  Nf3,  Bc4,  O-O,  Qe2,  Be3/f4 and rooks to d1 and c1 is easy to learn and remember. The bad news for White is that ONLY knowing this setup is not enough. We'll see that White needs to be precise and that 'auto-pilot' play will give us better chances.  Before we continue, we'd like to add that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.d4  cxd4  4.c3  dxc3  5.Nxc3  is an alternative route to the lines suggested in this chapter. The early ...a6 is a good move for Black anyway. Therefore, we only need to learn one answer – it is applicable against both move orders.  The Wing Gambit and Delayed Wing Gambit  The Wing Gambit @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.b4  enjoys a dubious reputation and is less popular than the Smith-Morra. Still, it can prove dangerous for Black if you are unprepared. We are not going to make this mistake and study a reliable antidote in this chapter.  It is important to note that White can play  2.b4  , or decide to go for the pawn sacrifice only after  2.Nf3  a6  3.b4  . Contrary to the case of the Morra above, we need a different reply to these two versions. Fortunately, there are pragmatic choices for Black that give us a good game in both cases, as we will see. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Morra Gambit 2.d4 and Wing Gambit 2.b4 / 3.b4"]
[Black "6A | Morra Gambit with 2.d4 | White plays 9.Bc2 / 10.e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3
{ You sometimes meet  3.Nf3  , when  3...a6!  is a fun way to stay within the realms of our repertoire. }
3... dxc3 4. Nxc3
{ What does White get in return for the pawn? In the Smith-Morra, White's compensation is mainly based on a lead in development. White is already a bit ahead and has an easy plan. They will almost invariably continue with Nf3,  Bc4 and O-O,  getting the kingside developed quickly.  This will increase the lead in development even more, as we still need to make some pawn moves to get the pieces out. We'll talk more about our specific setup in a moment.  Still, one general remark is appropriate here already: White's lead in development is significant, but the position is neither wide open nor can it be opened easily. This means that often White might have more pieces in play at the beginning, but there is no immediate clash in which that may matter. This is a difference to the position types after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  , when being behind in development may prove fatal.   Before we continue, a word about  4.Bc4  , which offers an additional pawn. It's a rare move, as White does not have enough play for two pawns after  4...cxb2  . As mentioned in the paragraph above, there is no direct clash of both sides, so the additional development does not matter much.  We are happy to grab the pawn and will go for the same setup as in the main line 4.Nxc3: we play ...e6,  ...a6,  ...b5 and so on. }
4... a6
{ We want to play ...e6 and ...a6 – it does not matter what move you play first. Let's discuss the merits of Black's setup once both are on the board. }
5. Nf3
{ This natural development move is played almost exclusively.  This position could also arise via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.d4  cxd4  4.c3  dxc3  5.Nxc3  , which occurs from time to time. }
5... e6
{ We complete the first stage of our setup against the Smith-Morra, starting with the moves ...a6 and ...e6. What's next?  The first important point is that we don't hurry with kingside development and castling. There are two reasons. First, it is not easy at all to develop the kingside actively. The move ...Nf6, for example, is not easy to play, as White has e4-e5 in reply. You could stop this by playing ...d6 first, but this means that the f8-bishop will remain passive for a while. Not a bad setup, by any means, but not particularly aggressive, either.  The second, more important point is: We don't need to emphasise kingside development in the first place. Our king is safe on e8, and we have many good options on the queenside, as we will discuss in a moment. The idea is to get in the active moves we can play easily, and only then complete kingside development and castle.  Usually, we'll later develop the f8-bishop to c5 or b4 and then continue with ...Ne7, rather than ...Nf6. This way, we avoid the often disturbing e4-e5 advance.  How do we start the queenside play?  We want to play ...b5 and develop the bishop to b7, but going ...Nc6-a5 is an important idea, too. Note that White will almost always play their bishop to b3, so ...Na5 is an attractive option. We either trade the important bishop or force it to a more passive square.  Once the bishop and knight are out, we can play ...Rc8, too. Let's have a look at some concrete lines now. }
6. Bc4
{ White's standard bishop placement in the Morra. It is played almost all the time. Does White have any good alternatives?  You rarely meet  6.a4?!  . It stops the move ...b5,  but it's very slow and weakens the queenside. We are in good shape against it in various ways, for example, by developing with ...Nc6,  ...Bc5 and ...Nge7.   A better option for White is  6.Bf4  , but it's extremely rare, too. We can choose between still playing with  6...b5  , similar to our main lines, or opting for a setup with ...Nc6 and ...Nge7.   If White does not develop their bishop to c4,  trying to play ...d5 is possible for Black. In any case, we should focus on  6.Bc4  , as this is the move you will be facing almost exclusively. }
6... b5 { Here we go, putting the move ...a6 to good use. } 7. Bb3 Nc6
{ We suggest starting with 7...Nc6,  aiming for a quick ...Na5 to fight White's bishop.  Of course, it's no mistake to start with  7...Bb7  , but the play is somewhat different. The quick ...Nc6-a5 is more direct, as White needs to answer the important question if they want to keep the bishop or lose time. }
8. O-O
{ White's most logical and popular move.  White may also start with a different slow move, like  8.Qe2  , when we can play the same setup, we suggest after 8.O-O. A sample line is  8...Na5  9.Bc2  Bb7  10.O-O  Rc8  11.Rd1  Bc5  , when we'd reach an even better version of our main line. }
8... Na5
{ A rare, but strong move.  More often than not, Black plays  8...Bb7  . This move is no mistake at all and a good alternative. In our mind,  8...Na5  is even stronger, though. White needs to move their bishop again or give up the bishop pair. We need to examine both options. }
9. Bc2
{ The bishop retreat is White's most popular move by a mile. It's an understandable decision, as White went for an ambitious opening setup and generally wants to keep pieces on for a later attack.  A closer look, however, reveals that it is quite unclear what White's target is going to be. Our king is currently safe in the centre, and White has no way to open this part of the board.  Let's have a look at how play will likely unfold. }
9... Bb7
{ The natural spot for our bishop. We also prepare ...Rc8,  using the open file. Now we'll check two moves for White.  The most common one is  10.Qe2  , continuing with the 'usual moves' that are on White's agenda. We'll see that Black is doing fine against it.  A more aggressive alternative for White is  10.e5  , which grabs some space and clears the e4-square for a piece. Knowing the best plan against this concept helps immensely, as the solution is not apparent.  Let's check both moves now. }
10. e5
{ A more aggressive continuation, compared to the more routine  10.Qe2  . With the e-pawn advance, White prepares Ne4 and takes control of the f6-square.  How should we develop our kingside? First, we can make a good move on the other side of the board. }
10... Rc8
{ We don't need to commit to a kingside development yet. Getting the rook on the open file is part of our setup.  In this particular position, the reasoning is a bit more concrete: White's c2-bishop may be vulnerable in some key lines. An important example is  11.Re1?  , when  11...Bxf3!  is a strong move. White can't play  12.Qxf3?  , as  12...b4!  wins a piece!  This means that White has to react to the threat of ...Bxf3,  which also explains the next move. }
11. Ne4
{ A logical follow-up of 10.e5, centralising the knight. As mentioned, alternatives are scarce, as we threatened to capture on f3. Our next move is powerful and important to remember. }
11... Be7
{ A strong move, but its purpose is not obvious at first glance. Let's discuss what the idea is.  The e4-knight is White's best piece. It's nicely centralised and hampers our development. What about  11...Ne7??  12.Nd6#  – oops! We'd love to get rid of the knight, but how?   The first move we checked was  11...f5?!  , but  12.exf6  Nxf6  13.Nfg5  leads to a messy position that is difficult to play for Black.   Then we saw that Stockfish recommends:  11...Be7!  , intending to play ...f5 on the next move. It turns out that White has no great option on move 12 to discourage our planned pawn push. }
12. Re1
{ This looks like a reasonable move. White has no good recipe against our ...f5-idea, anyway. }
12... f5 13. exf6
{ More or less forced.  After  13.Ng3?  Bxf3  14.gxf3  g6  or @@StartFEN@@2rqk1nr/1b1pb1pp/p3p3/np2Pp2/4N3/5N2/PPB2PPP/R1BQR1K1 w k f6 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Nd6+  Bxd6  14.exd6  Bxf3  15.gxf3  Nf6  16.Bxf5  O-O  Black is in fantastic shape. White's pawn structure is a wreck in both cases. }
13... Nxf6
{ Here we should compare this position with the one after @@StartFEN@@2rqkbnr/1b1p1ppp/p3p3/np2P3/4N3/5N2/PPB2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b k - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...f5?!  12.exf6  Nxf6  , when  13.Nfg5!  is best for White. After  13...Nxe4  14.Bxe4  Bxe4  15.Nxe4  White has the awkward thread Qh5+,  which is tough to address.   Now, let's return to the current position. If White goes for the same idea  14.Nfg5  , we have  14...Nxe4  15.Bxe4  Bxe4  16.Nxe4  O-O!  – our move ...Be7 is much more useful than White's Re1.   We have established that 14.Nfg5 is harmless. What should White do instead? Let's not forget that we are a pawn up and have a central pawn advantage. White has to prove something or is just worse for obvious reasons.  Stockfish suggests  14.Ne5  , but  14...Bxe4  15.Bxe4  O-O  is still evaluated as better for Black. White's pieces are still quite active, but it's not enough to compensate for the pawn deficit. The key point to remember is the idea ...f5,  which needs to be prepared with ...Be7,  a very strong concept. }
