{ We have an extra pawn and the bishop pair now. If we don't get checkmated, we'll win!  Jokes aside, the static advantage @@StartBracket@@material and bishop pair@@EndBracket@@ is substantial, but we have no development. We need to be careful, but our analysis points toward Black being in good shape. }
10. Qxb3 Bc5
{ We prefer this move to the more obvious  10...Bb7  , which is not objectively wrong, though. The drawback to  10...Bb7  is that after  11.a4  b4  , we don't threaten the c3-knight, as our bishop on b7 is a liability. This makes the situation more complicated than needed.   After  10...Bc5  , we are ready to play ...Ne7 and ...O-O next. White needs to start some direct action. Otherwise, we will catch up in development and start converting.  We'll check  11.a4  and the shocker  11.Nd5  now, as played by Esserman in blitz. }
