{ This is an excellent idea, but we only need to avoid the pitfall  12...exd5??  13.Qxd5  , when White wins. What's the best reply? }
12... Ne7
{ A cool-headed response. We ignore the d5-knight and continue with our development. As we are on unexplored territory @@StartBracket@@10...Bc5 is almost a novelty – it makes little sense to extend the trainable line even further. Let's check some possible ideas for White now to see how it could continue.  A@@EndBracket@@  13.Qc4  is the engine suggestion and relatively best for White. After  13...d6  14.Nxb4  Bb7  Black is slightly better @@StartBracket@@bishop pair@@EndBracket@@, but at least White restored material equality. They have zero attacking chances, though.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/3pnppp/p3p3/2bN4/Pp2P3/1Q3N2/1P3PPP/R1B1R1K1 w kq - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Bg5?!  is objectively bad, but it's the move that White would love to make work. Against precise play, it is destined to fail, though. After  13...exd5  14.exd5  f6  @@StartBracket@@14...O-O also works@@EndBracket@@ White can try  15.d6  Bxd6  16.Qd5  , but it is refuted by  16...Qc7!  17.Qxa8  O-O  18.Bf4  Bxf4  19.Rxe7  Bb7  20.Qa7  Bd6!  21.Qe3  Bxe7  22.Qxe7  a5  , when Black has a large advantage.  This is an extremely deep computer line that you don't need to memorize to the end. Along the way, White has other ideas that won't work, either. It makes little sense to look at all of them in an opening course, but studying an illustrative line helps to better understand the possibilities of both sides. Here we see that even the most cunning attacking ideas by White fail against best defence. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Morra Gambit 2.d4 and Wing Gambit 2.b4 / 3.b4"]
[Black "6B | Wing Gambit with 2.b4 | White plays 3.d4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. b4
{ The Wing Gambit has a fairly dubious reputation but can be dangerous if you are unprepared. Let's see how to deal with it. The first step is easy. }
2... cxb4
{ We happily take the pawn and accept White's challenge. After our capture, White usually plays the best and most challenging move  3.a3  , but we'll check the less precise move  3.d4  . }
3. d4 { Advancing in the centre looks reasonable, but we have a strong reply. }
3... d5
{ A strong move, immediately attacking White's pawn duo.  White must take on d5 now, as  4.e5?  Nc6  5.a3  Qb6  is much better for Black. We not only enjoy the extra pawn but also have an easy target on d4. Our c8-bishop finds a good spot on f5 next. }
4. exd5
{ Better than advancing, but we will quickly get the pawn back and speed up our development. }
4... Nf6
{ Even stronger than the immediate capture. We'd prefer ...Nxd5 to the queen capture in some cases. }
5. a3
{ This looks like the most interesting try for White. After something like  5.Nf3  Nxd5!  they can't even quickly expel our knight from its great central post. }
5... Qxd5
{ Taking with the knight is also acceptable, after  5...Nxd5  6.axb4  Nxb4  7.c3  Nd5  White is struggling to drum up enough play for the pawn.  Our suggestion looks even easier to handle. White is not quickly attacking our queen due to the pawn on b4,  and our development advantage is serious. We are ready to play ...e5,  ...Nc6 and/or ...Bg4 next, to gain a nice initiative. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Morra Gambit 2.d4 and Wing Gambit 2.b4 / 3.b4"]
[Black "6B | Wing Gambit with 2.b4 | White plays 3.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. b4
{ The Wing Gambit has a fairly dubious reputation but can be dangerous if you are unprepared. Let's see how to deal with it. The first step is easy. }
2... cxb4
{ We happily take the pawn and accept White's challenge. After our capture, White usually plays the best and most challenging move  3.a3  , but we'll check the less precise move  3.d4  . }
3. a3
{ This is White's most popular move. They want to remove the b4-pawn and open files on the queenside. We should not comply and take the pawn but rather speed up our development. }
3... e5
{ We think that Black has two healthy options here. The one we recommend, obviously, and  3...d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.Nf3  e6  . What's the difference, and why did we go for 3...e5?   After  3...e5  , we go for quick development. It looks like White has a narrow path to even stay in the game. They have to know what to do, which is not a given.  In the 3...d5 line, Black is also in good shape, but White's job is more straightforward. They can get by with 'normal moves'.  Let's check what happens after our move. }
4. Nf3
{ This looks best for White.  They can also start with  4.Bb2  , when  4...Nc6  5.Nf3  transposes to our variation.   It is not a given that White will play like that. The most popular move in online play is  4.axb4?  Bxb4  5.c3  Be7  6.d4  Nf6!  , when White is a pawn down and has the worse development. What a great opening result for us. }
4... Nc6
{ The best way to evaluate this position is to compare it with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  : the insertion of ...c5 and the capture on b4 must favour Black. We will be fine by simply developing pieces, like ...Nf6 and preparing kingside castling next. }
5. Bb2
{ This looks like the best try, attacking the e-pawn.  What about  5.Bc4  , playing in the style of the Italian? After  5...Nf6  6.Ng5  d5  7.exd5  b5!  8.Bxb5  Qxd5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/p4ppp/2n2n2/1p1Pp1N1/1pB5/P7/2PP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq b6 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Ba2  Nd4  9.c3  b3!  10.Bxb3  Nxb3  11.Qxb3  Qxd5  Black is much better. }
5... Qb6
{ A strong move that secures Black's advantage. We'll examine  6.Nxe5  now, which is White's most aggressive choice, but it seems to fail against best play. }
6. Nxe5
{ This is not a pawn grab but the start of a sacrificial attack.  Before we figure out the details, a word about  6.Bd3  , which seems to be the objectively better move. After  6...d6  , we keep the extra pawn and are certainly better, but White is not a piece down.   This will happen after  6.Nxe5  but how does Black win a piece now? }
6... bxa3 { We take and force White's reply. } 7. Bc3 a2
{ That's the point! Our c-pawn is doing a marvellous job and has made it all the way to a2. The amazing idea is that now  8.Rxa2  Nxe5  9.Bxe5  Qe6!  is a double attack on the rook and bishop. After  10.Ra5  b6  11.Rd5  f6  Black is winning. }
8. Nxf7
{ This is the way for White to drum up something for the lost material. Our king position will be a bit insecure, but a piece is a piece. }
8... Kxf7 9. Bc4+ Ke8
{ Returning to e8 is best, as placing the king on e7 blocks our pieces. } 10.
Rxa2 { White finally captures our pawn. } 10... Nf6
{ We need to develop, for sure. } 11. O-O Be7 12. Qe2
{ After  12.e5  we have  12...Ne4  . The queen move prepares the push of the e-pawn. }
12... Qc5
{ White does not have enough compensation for the piece. The queen move is strong, planning to swing it to the kingside. The move ...Qh5 can be annoying for White, as they certainly don't want to trade queens.  What about  13.e5?  The pawn advance is refuted by  13...Nd5  now. }
