[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Morra Gambit 2.d4 and Wing Gambit 2.b4 / 3.b4"]
[Black "6C | Delayed Wing Gambit with 3.b4 |"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6
{ After our signature move 2...a6 White can still play in gambit style.  They can play  3.d4  cxd4  4.c3  dxc3  5.Nxc3  and transpose to the Smith-Morra Gambit. We cover the Morra in the current chapter, using the more usual move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d4  cxd4  3.c3  dxc3  4.Nxc3  , when we'll reach the same lines. Our setup involves ...a6 anyway, which makes the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.d4  cxd4  4.c3  purely transpositional.   White, however, can play  3.b4  , a delayed Wing Gambit. This is very rarely seen, but we want to check it briefly. Contrary to the Morra case above, it is not purely transpositional and requires a different response. }
3. b4
{ A Delayed Wing Gambit. It's a very rare line, but we want to check it briefly. The reason is that we need a different antidote than against 2.b4 – therefore, meeting it unprepared would be tricky. }
3... cxb4
{ We take the pawn, just as after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.b4  cxb4  . }
4. a3
{ We need to check this move, but also the central pawn push  4.d4  . Compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.b4  cxb4  3.d4  , the moves Nf3 and ...a6 are inserted, which changes the situation considerably. White's knight move is useful, in particular, if we'd try to open the game quickly.   We have a good solution, though. After  4.d4  , our reply is the funny  4...b5!  , making use of our signature move. This is easy to remember, as we'll answer @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/8/1p2P3/5N2/P1PP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.a3  with  4...b5  , too!   After a sample sequence like  4.d4  b5  5.Bd3  Bb7  6.O-O  e6  7.Re1  Nf6  , we maintain the extra pawn and are ready to strike at White's centre with ...d5. These positions are unexplored and interesting to play. }
4... b5
{ A fun way to use our a-pawn move.  In the regular Wing Gambit @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.b4  cxb4  3.a3  , we play  3...e5  , a setup that is unreachable here.   We need a different approach, and  4...b5  fits the bill nicely. }
5. axb4
{ White gets the pawn back, but we don't mind. We can easily develop with tempo now. }
5... Bb7 { We attack the e-pawn. } 6. d3 Nf6
{ We like Black's position. An important point is that we can sometimes play ...Nc6 and ...e5! next, gaining ground in the centre. Here's a sample line. }
7. Bb2 Nc6 8. c3 e5
{ With a nice position for us. We'll play ...Be7 and ...d5, gaining an advantage in the centre. }
