[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Sidelines on move two and three"]
[Black "Introduction to the Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Hello and welcome to the final chapter of the course. In this chapter, we will examine White's sidelines, odds and ends, so to say. This includes sidelines on the second move and after  2.Nf3  a6  .   One option for White is playing in gambit style, employing the Morra @@StartBracket@@  2.d4  @@EndBracket@@ or Wing Gambit @@StartBracket@@  2.b4  @@EndBracket@@ – these gambits are examined in a dedicated chapter. Let's see what else White could try. As you may imagine, there are many possible ways for White to play. Let's make an overview about what we need to cover.  A@@EndBracket@@  2.Bc4  White develops their bishop, but it will be quickly attacked by ...a6 and ...b5 or ...e6 and ...d5. White may also play  2.Nf3  a6  3.Bc4  , which has no independent value – the move ...a6 is helpful for our plans in any case. We discuss both move orders via 2.Bc4 in the current chapter.   B@@EndBracket@@  2.b3  is an interesting sideline for White. A combination of the moves ...a6 and ...e6 is frequently seen in our repertoire – it works well here, too. We can answer @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.b3  in the same way, our suggested setup works well in this move order, too.   C@@EndBracket@@ The move  2.f4  is similar to the Grand Prix @@StartBracket@@  2.Nc3  a6  3.f4  @@EndBracket@@ but has some independent value. We suggest the move @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4PP2/8/PPPP2PP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d5!  , which exploits White's omission of Nc3. We often sacrifice a pawn but get excellent play in return.   D@@EndBracket@@ White may play  2.c4  . The line  2.Nf3  a6  3.c4  is one of the best replies to the O'Kelly and is covered in a dedicated chapter. If White plays the c-pawn even earlier, we are not committed to ...a6 yet. This gives us some additional options that we explore in the current chapter.   E@@EndBracket@@ The move  2.Ne2  has little independent value. We play  2...a6  , when  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5!  transposes to the Open Variation of the O'Kelly. An alternative for White is  3.Nbc3  , but after  3...b5  the most likely outcome is  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e6  , when we reach the Tricky Knights chapter about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.Nc3  , leading to the same position after  3...b5  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e6  .   F@@EndBracket@@  2.g3  is well met with  2...d5!  when we get a good game immediately.   G@@EndBracket@@  2.d3  leads to a closed game. White often combines it with a quick f4. A combination of ...Nc6 and ...d5 is our recommendation.   H@@EndBracket@@ Finally, White may try something offbeat after  2.Nf3  a6  . We cover almost all these ideas via different move orders, like the gambits @@StartBracket@@dedicated chapter@@EndBracket@@ or 3.Bc4/3.b3,  which we examine via 2.Bc4/2.b3. The only lines we need to examine more closely are @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.g3  and  3.d3  . These lines are very similar and will usually lead to the same positions.  These are White's rare options that warrant coverage. Other moves are even more exotic and can be dealt with by applying general principles. }
2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6
{ The signature move of the O'Kelly. White has many options, most of which are covered in dedicated chapters. These are:  ➤  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  – Open Variation   ➤  3.Nc3  – Tricky Knights   ➤  3.c4  Maroczy Style   ➤  3.c3  Alapin   ➤  3.b4  the Wing Gambit and  3.d4  cxd4  4.c3  the Morra Gambit are examined in a dedicated chapter on White's Gambits.   What is left to cover? Some moves transpose to lines we cover via different move orders in the current chapter, like the following.  A@@EndBracket@@  3.b3  is rarely played. We'll answer with  3...Nc6  4.Bb2  e6  , which transposes to our coverage of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.b3  in the current chapter.  B@@EndBracket@@  3.Bc4  is answered with  3...e6  , which we cover via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bc4  a6  3.Nf3  e6  , leading to the same position.   Finally, there is  3.g3  and  3.d3  , which signals White's intention to play a King's Indian Reversed/Attack setup. Both moves will often lead to the same position. We'll cover the move order  3.g3  as a trainable line and explain how the same positions arise from  3.d3  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Sidelines on move two and three"]
[Black "7A | Sideline 3.g3 |"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White quite frequently starts with the move  2.Nf3  and only after  2...a6  decides to opt for the Alapin. }
2... a6 3. g3
{ White opts for a slow setup involving a kingside fianchetto. They usually continue with Bg2,  O-O and the move d3,  completing a formation usually called the Kings Indian Attack or KIA.  White can also start with the move  3.d3  and continue with 4.g3 etc., leading to the same position. The KIA is more of a setup than a concrete sequence of moves. Players who play 3.d3 or 3.g3 against 2...a6 will usually play in the same way against other second moves, like 2...e6,  2...d6 or 2...Nc6 – they follow their intended system approach, more or less regardless of Black's second move.  Let's discuss our strategy against  3.g3  . First of all, it is crucial to understand that the move  3...b5?!  is wrong. We like to play an early ...b5 if White has already committed a knight to the c3-square. Two typical examples are @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nc3  a6  3.g3  b5!  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.Nc3  b5!  which share the same idea: if White plays a4 to attack our b-pawn, the advance ...b4 hits the knight with a gain of tempo. Without the target on c3,  the b-pawn push is dubious.   What about playing ...e6 and ...d5? This pawn formation is a common approach in our repertoire, but it has a substantial practical drawback against 3.g3. After a sequence like  3.g3  e6  4.Bg2  Nc6  5.d3  d5  6.Nbd2  Nf6  7.O-O  Be7  8.e5  Nd7  , we reach the type of position that White aims for when choosing the KIA. White establishes a space advantage in the centre and later wants to start an attack on the kingside.  Black seeks counterplay on the queenside in this structure, but the move ...a6 does not help much. Often, you'd like to play ...b5 and ...a5,  going for a pawn storm. These positions are difficult to play for Black in practice and are exactly what White was aiming for. We suggest a different solution – let's have a look. }
3... Nc6 { We develop our knight first. } 4. Bg2
{ White's natural reply, continuing with their setup. } 4... Nf6
{ An important move order detail. We attack the e-pawn, forcing a decision. Now the reply  5.d3  is almost always played, but there are some rare alternatives for White. As mentioned, White is often operating on 'auto-pilot' mode after they have decided on a KIA. }
5. d3
{ White usually responds with this move, staying in line with their intended setup. The position after 5.d3 will also occur frequently after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.d3  Nc6  4.g3  Nf6  5.Bg2  , a natural sequence. We mentioned that White has more or less unexplored alternatives to 5.d3 – let's have a brief look to illustrate.  A@@EndBracket@@  5.Qe2  covers the pawn and may support e4-e5. Good replies are  5...d6  or  5...e5  , stopping this idea in its tracks. We can develop the kingside with ...g6 or ...Be7; both are possible.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.Nc3  can be answered in various ways. A creative way is  5...d6  6.d4  Bg4  , pinning the knight.   C@@EndBracket@@  5.e5  is a yet untested engine suggestion. The point is  5...Ng4  6.c3!?  , sacrificing the e-pawn. This idea would never occur to a human player, which is probably why it was never tested in practice. White gets good compensation after  6...Ngxe5  7.Nxe5  Nxe5  8.d4  , which we suggest avoiding.  A more practical response is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1ppppp/p1n5/2p1P3/6n1/2P2NP1/PP1P1PBP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d6  , attacking the e-pawn. After  7.exd6  exd6  , we regain the option to play the knight back to f6 later. These lines are rare and unexplored but always interesting and complex to play for both sides.  In practice, you will almost always meet 5.d3,  which we'll return to now. }
5... g6
{ We suggest going for the kingside fianchetto. This setup is also possible to reach by playing  5...d6  first and ...g6 next. Let's discuss our strategy after the next natural moves. }
6. O-O d6
{ There is no need to allow  6...Bg7  7.e5  . We need both ...g6 and ...d6 anyway. }
7. Re1
{ Attention: White may answer  7...Bg7  with  8.e5  now, opening the position while we are still not castled. }
7... e5
{ The cleanest solution. We close the centre and continue with ...Bg7 and ...O-O, finally getting our king out of the middle. Now it's worth checking if White can open the centre quickly. }
8. c3 Bg7 9. d4
{ We must check this direct line. Slow play like  9.Nbd2  O-O  10.a4  Rb8  is comfortable for Black. We have a space advantage, after all. Playing on the queenside @@StartBracket@@...b5@@EndBracket@@ is an option, as is preparing ...d6-d5 in the long run. }
9... cxd4 10. cxd4 Bg4
{ A good point to remember. We use this pin to fight for control of d4 and have obtained equal chances. There are many different ideas now, like  11.d5  Nd4  , or @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1p3pbp/p1np1np1/4p3/3PP1b1/5NP1/PP3PBP/RNBQR1K1 w kq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.dxe5  dxe5  , when White simplifies the position but can't claim any advantage. It looks like we might be even quicker in exploiting the d4-square, compared to White trying the same with d5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Sidelines on move two and three"]
[Black "7B | Sideline 2.c4 |"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c4
{ White combines the moves e4 and c4,  maybe trying to reach a Maroczy Bind setup after a future d2-d4 move. This approach is similar to  2.Nf3  a6  3.c4  , when White follows the same idea. In this line, we play  3...Nc6  , increasing control of the centre.   Here, after  2.c4  is on the board, we recommend playing  2...Nc6  , as well. }
2... Nc6
{ White has weakened the d4-square, which makes this move very logical.  It is possible to play  2...a6!?  , by the way. White's best is likely  3.Nf3  , when we'd transpose to the chapter on @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.c4  . However, this line is considered one of the best against the O'Kelly, and we must be precise to gain fair chances.   After  2...Nc6  , however, we have already equalized. }
3. Nc3
{ After  3.Nf3  , we have the strong reply  3...e5!  , which gives us good chances.  This is best compared to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.c4  Nc6  4.Nc3  e5  , which we cover in a different chapter.  We are fine with this blocked central structure, seeing that a later ...g6,  ...Bg7,  ...Nge7 and ...f5 plan works well. }
3... g6
{ White has weakened the d4-square. We want to increase our control of it, preventing White's possible d2-d4 idea. }
4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2
{ Black has a wide range of ideas in this structure. One decision is about our g8-knight. You can develop it to f6, often followed by a later ...Ne8-c7-e6 tour – it's about the d4-square!  A different idea is playing ...e6 and ...Nge7, which is just as good. However, the position is still closed, so there is no particular rush about this decision. Given that we play ...a6 so often in our repertoire, our choice is no surprise. }
5... a6
{ Why not? The pawn lever ...b5 is a standard idea in this structure; let's prepare it immediately. }
6. Nge2
{ This is White's most popular reply. They don't perceive ...b5 as a threat yet and continue developing pieces.  The alternative is  6.a4  when ...b5 is stopped for a while. We'd still be happy about it, as White gives up on any a3 + b4 ideas they might have had. We'd continue with  6...Nf6  and ...O-O next. Keep the idea ...Ne8-c7 in mind. We might have ...Ne6-d4,  but the c7-knight can support ...b5,  too. }
6... b5
{ We don't even need to prepare for this move!  There is nothing wrong with the more conventional  6...Rb8  though. We'd either play ...b5 next or, after  7.a4  Nf6  , transpose to the line 6.a4,  which we discussed in the notes to the sixth move. }
7. cxb5
{ We need to check the pawn grab, of course.  White could also play the more solid  7.d3  when  7...Rb8  covers our pawn and supports queenside play. Next, we'll develop the kingside and are happy about our prospects. White will likely start playing on the kingside @@StartBracket@@O-O,  f2-f4@@EndBracket@@, but we have already begun our offensive on the other side of the board. }
7... axb5 8. Nxb5 Ba6
{ Developing with a gain of tempo is always fun. Now White is under severe pressure. }
9. Nec3
{ The only playable move.  After  9.Nbc3?  we are much better with  9...Bd3  10.O-O  Nb4  or @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/3pppbp/b1n3p1/2p5/4P3/2N3P1/PP1PNPBP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nb4  10.O-O  Bd3  , leading to the same position. White can hardly move any of their pieces. We threaten ...Bc2,  on top of everything. }
9... Bxc3
{ We suggest this forcing move. It looks odd to give up the bishop, but the following line is convincing. It is not the only good move, though. We'd also have excellent compensation for the pawn after other moves, as White has multiple weaknesses. }
10. Nxc3 Nb4
{ That's the idea of the capture: We now threaten the deadly ...Nd3+, forcing White's reply. }
11. Bf1 Bd3
{ A nice move, threatening ...Nc2+! White has to allow our knight to invade on d3. After  12.Bxd3  Nxd3+  White has to move the king and suffers long-term problems on the light squares. We can support our d3-knight with ...c4 or ...Qc8-a6. }
