[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Sidelines on move two and three"]
[Black "7C | Sideline 2.f4 | White plays 4.c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. f4
{ The move 2.f4 is an early version of the Grand Prix Attack.  Nowadays, White prefers the move order  2.Nc3  and f4 on the next move. We recommend @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  a6  3.f4  b5  , as covered in a dedicated chapter.  Why does White usually prefer 2.Nc3? We'll see right away. }
2... d5
{ After theoreticians established this move as the best reply, 2.f4 returned to obscurity again. Fans of the white f4 setup changed their move order subsequently, starting with 2.Nc3 first. This leads to the modern version of the Grand Prix, which we cover in a dedicated chapter. }
3. exd5
{ This is by far the most popular move and requires some knowledge.  Once in a while, White plays  3.d3  , when you can trade twice or play the more combative  3...Nc6  , leading to a line that we cover in the current chapter via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d3  Nc6  3.f4  d5  .   White may also play  3.Bb5+  , when  3...Bd7  4.Bxd7+  Qxd7  is a sound reply.   We should avoid  3.Bb5  Nc6?!  4.Bxc6+  , allowing damage to our structure.   Surprisingly, the move  3.e5?  is played frequently in online Blitz. We have an excellent position, using a natural setup starting with  3...Bf5  , followed by ...Nc6 and ...e6. The situation is comparable to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c3  d5  3.e5?!  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  d5  4.e5?!  , when we manage to develop our light-squared bishop actively and often manage to put pressure on White's overexpanded centre. }
3... Nf6
{ This is much better than talking on d5 with the queen. We would like to comfortably recapture with the knight on d5,  avoiding any time loss due to queen moves. The only 'drawback' is that we often need to sacrifice a pawn for excellent compensation. White can hold their pawn now by playing the immediate  4.c4  or giving a check on b5 first.  After something like  4.Nc3  Nxd5  we regain the pawn comfortably and have the better chances: White's f4-move only created weaknesses for no benefit. }
4. c4
{ White immediately covers the pawn, even before the bishop is developed to b5. }
4... e6
{ We need to get rid of the d5-pawn and speed up our development. The following sample sequence is not forced but rather natural. The only point worth noting is that we would advise castling kingside in this line. Let's have a look at some moves. }
5. dxe6 Bxe6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be2 Bd6 8. d3 Qc7 9. g3 O-O
{ This looks better than O-O-O. With queenside castling, we are one move quicker with centralizing the rooks, but the king will be weaker in the long run. Now we play rooks to e8 and d8 and exert more than enough pressure to compensate for the pawn. White has multiple long-term weaknesses that are beyond repair. }
*

