1. e4 c5 2. d3
{ White chooses a slow setup. They are not after opening the game quickly but prefer a closed game. }
2... Nc6
{ Our knight is best on c6, a good move to start with. After White's reply, we'll know a bit more about their intentions. }
3. f4
{ Most of the time, White plays this move, expanding on the kingside. There are plenty of alternatives, of course. In such a 'non-contact' position, many moves are possible. Here's a quick look:  A@@EndBracket@@  3.Nf3  is similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.g3  Nc6  4.Bg2  Nf6  5.d3  , which we cover in the current chapter. We could continue in the same fashion here but skip the early move ...a6 in favour of quicker development. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.d3  Nc6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.g3  g6  5.Bg2  Bg7  is a possible line.   B@@EndBracket@@  3.g3  can be answered with  3...d5  . It is similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.g3  d5  , as the current chapter covers.   There is nothing wrong about  3.g3  Nf6  , either. }
3... d5
{ We like this straightforward play. It's played in the same spirit as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.f4  d5  when we hit White's centre right after the f-pawn move.   As stated before, Black has many satisfactory alternatives here, like  3...e6  ,  3...g6  or  3...Nf6  . }
4. Be2
{ It looks like this move or  4.Nf3  is best for White. In both cases, we recommend not to trade on e4 but keep the tension.  White's alternatives look bad, like  4.e5?  Bf5  @@StartBracket@@an even worse version of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.f4  d5  3.e5?!  @@EndBracket@@ or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/2pp4/4PP2/3P4/PPP3PP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.exd5  Qxd5  when White's f-pawn move is useless and only helped with creating weaknesses. }
4... e6
{ We keep the tension in the centre.  Playing  4...dxe4  5.dxe4  Qxd1+  6.Bxd1  is possible but unambitious. Our suggestion keeps the queens on the board and is more combative. It's good to remember the following setup: we want to play ...Bd6 and ...Nge7 next, a flexible way to prepare kingside castling. }
5. Nf3 Bd6
{ The start of the mentioned setup. If White plays e4-e5, we drop the bishop back to c7. }
6. O-O
{ White could play  6.e5  Bc7  7.O-O  Nge7  , leading to the same position. }
6... Nge7 7. e5
{ An alternative for White is  7.c3  when  7...O-O  8.e5  Bc7  9.d4  could lead to the line we are about to examine.  We could also play the interesting @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp2nppp/2nbp3/2pp4/4PP2/2PP1N2/PP2B1PP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...f6!?  , stopping White's pawn advance. }
7... Bc7
{ Our bishop is well-placed on c7. It supports play against e5 @@StartBracket@@...f6 is on the agenda@@EndBracket@@ and d4, as shown in the following line. }
8. c3 O-O 9. d4
{ A natural move, but it has a tactical drawback.  White should probably play a slow move like  9.Kh1  when  9...f6  is the way to go. We attack White's centre and prepare a later ...Bd7-e8-g6/h5 manoeuvre to activate our bishop. }
9... cxd4 10. cxd4 Nf5
{ We have a fantastic position, as White has no way to save the d4-pawn! } 11.
Nc3
{ After  11.Kh1  Bb6  White can't cover the pawn, while after 11.Nc3,  a standard tactic strikes! }
11... Ncxd4 { Or  11...Nfxd4  , it makes no difference. } 12. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ And we won the centre pawn for nothing. White can't capture our knight, as  13.Qxd4  Bb6  wins the queen. }
13. Qxd4 Bb6 { Game over! } *

