1. e4 c5 2. b3
{ White chooses a rare setup based on a queenside fianchetto. In our repertoire, they can play  2.b3  or  2.Nf3  a6  3.b3  to employ this idea.  It is possible to answer both versions differently, as, after 2.b3,  we are not committed to ...a6 yet, which gives Black more options. However, this approach is rather uneconomical, given how rare b3-setups are.  Therefore, we suggest employing an antidote that works for both versions. It is based on the moves ...a6 @@StartBracket@@after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.b3  we have already played it, of course@@EndBracket@@, ...e6 and ...Nc6. The move ...a6 is useful, as it prevents a possible Bb5 development. }
2... a6
{ We play our signature move right away. As mentioned, we'd like to play the three moves ...a6, ...e6 and ...Nc6. There is no optimal move order, but we suggest starting with ...a6. This ensures we never have to worry about Bb5, for starters. }
3. Bb2 Nc6
{ After this natural move, we need to check two different setups that White may employ.  A@@EndBracket@@ They can develop the kingside with  4.Nf3  , which is the main move. The resulting position may also arise via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.b3  Nc6  4.Bb2  .   B@@EndBracket@@ The more aggressive-looking  4.f4  is possible, too. The early f-pawn advances are often well met by ...e6 and ...d5 – this is one of these cases. }
4. Nf3
{ White prefers a healthy development over the slower move  4.f4  – a good decision. }
4... e6 { We complete the already described setup of ...a6, ...Nc6 and ...e6. }
5. c4
{ This looks best. White stops our ...d5-idea, which we would have happily employed after a slow move like  5.Be2  or  5.g3  .   What about  5.d4  instead? We have a strong reply, using a typical idea in the b3-lines. After  5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  Qf6!  we are in good shape, planning ...Bc5 next. The unprotected b2-bishop is a severe issue, more or less forcing White to close the diagonal with the ugly move c2-c3 soon.   White's main move  5.c4  is stronger. White intends first to develop the knight to c3 and later play d2-d4,  reaching a Maroczy Bind. This is a similar approach to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c4  , which we examine in a dedicated chapter. }
5... Qc7
{ A tricky move! We hope for  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Qe5!  , which is shockingly strong for us! We threaten ...Bb4+ and attack the e-pawn with a check! }
6. Nc3
{ White avoids the potential disaster of  6.d4?  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Qe5!  when we win instantly. This has @@StartBracket@@or could have!@@EndBracket@@ happened in hundreds of online games – it's easy to fall into this trap! }
6... Nf6 7. d4
{ White finally opens the centre.  They could continue delaying the move, of course. Something slow like  7.Be2  is possible when bot  7...Bd6!?  or  7...Nd4  are creative replies. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ White has managed to build the Maroczy Bind, as intended after 5.c4. The Maroczy has a good reputation, but we have no problems at all in this particular case. }
8... Bc5
{ Very important! We can develop this bishop actively and attack White's centralized knight. White has nothing better than taking on c6 now. }
9. Nxc6
{ That's best.  The move  9.Nc2  is far too passive, as the sample line  9...O-O  10.Be2  Qf4!  shows. White's b2-bishop is not well-placed here. }
9... dxc6
{ The cleanest solution. We'll manage ...e5 next to improve the scope of our light-squared bishop. }
10. Be2 e5
{ Black is already slightly better, as White has to be careful about the weak d4-square. We have easy moves like ...O-O, ...Rd8 and ...Be6. Sneaking the bishop to d4 is an obvious idea, too. }
