[Black "7F | Sideline 2.g3 |"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. g3
{ White's idea is to play a Closed Sicilian setup but avoid the move Nc3 to be more flexible on the queenside and in the centre. Quite frequently, White intends to play a pawn to c3 to support a later d4 pawn push to occupy the centre. These are valid ideas, but there is a concrete drawback of 2.g3. }
2... d5
{ We suggest playing this move in response to 2.g3. Black should use this opportunity to free their position immediately and, in many cases, even gain a space advantage. }
3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nf3 Bg4
{ A natural move, pinning White's knight.  Black has a good alternative in  4...Nc6  here; it is of equal strength. }
5. Bg2
{ Now we have reached an important moment. Black's next move is not difficult, but you might forget to insert it in a quick time control game. }
5... Qe6+
{ We have to play this check, forcing White to make an undesirable move. } 6.
Kf1
{ The alternative  6.Qe2  Qxe2+  7.Kxe2  Nc6  is comfortable for Black, too. }
6... Nc6
{ We develop the knight and increase control of the e5-square. This way, we can quickly play ...Qd7 and ...e6, enabling kingside development. }
7. h3 Bh5 8. d3 Qd7
{ We are now ready to develop the kingside, playing ...e6 and ...Nf6. Chances are about equal in this unconventional position: White's king makes an odd impression on f1, though – in practice, Black seems easier to play. }
