{ Why not? The move ...a6 is often helpful anyway, and White now always has to reckon with ...b5 at any moment. We'll see that we still need to be careful with the correct timing for this pawn push, as the line  3.Nf3  b5?!  4.Bd5  shows. We should play ...e6 first, taking away the d5-square.  Often, we are just content with controlling the b5-square, which is useful on its own. After playing ...e6 and ...d5,  White's bishop often would like to move to b5,  which is now prevented.  There are many possible lines, but our setup will be similar in all cases. We'll play ...e6 and ...d5,  gaining a good tempo on the bishop. We should only play ...b5 after ...e6 is already on the board.   We'll now examine  3.Nf3  as our main move, and after  3...e6  have a split between White playing  4.a4  and avoiding a4.   White could also start with moves like  3.a4  ,  3.a3  or  3.d3  , but the knight development to f3 is very natural, so we'll likely transpose to lines that we cover via  3.Nf3  . Here are some examples to illustrate these transpositions.  A@@EndBracket@@  3.a4  e6  4.Nf3  d5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/2B1P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  e6  4.a4  d5   B@@EndBracket@@  3.a3  e6  4.Nf3  d5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/2B1P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  e6  4.a3  d5   C@@EndBracket@@  3.d3  e6  4.Nf3  d5  is a similar story. We get to play ...d5 easily. }
3. Nf3
{ The position after  3.Nf3  may also arise after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  a6  3.Bc4  . Now we need to be precise. }
3... e6
{ An important move order finesse. After  3...b5?!  4.Bd5  , we need to play  4...Ra7  , which disrupts Black's coordination.   It's better to play  3...e6  first. Now White can't answer ...b5 with Bd5 anymore and needs to consider if they want to play the a-pawn or not. }
4. a4
{ White stops ...b5,  but pushing the b-pawn was not the only idea of going ...a6. The control over b5 is useful, too. What about the other a-pawn move,  4.a3?  We have two good options.  A@@EndBracket@@ Playing  4...d5  , similarly to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/2p5/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.a4  d5  , gives Black an easy game.  B@@EndBracket@@ It's also fine to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/2p5/2B1P3/P4N2/1PPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...b5  5.Ba2  Bb7  , attacking the e-pawn. The choice between the two setups is a matter of taste. }
4... d5 5. exd5 exd5
{ Without the insertion of ...a6 and ...a4, White's move would be Bb5+. Now they don't have a good square for the bishop at all. }
6. Be2
{ After  6.Ba2?!  we have the annoying queen check  6...Qe7+  , when White has no desirable reply. Moving the king is bad, while  7.Qe2  Qxe2+  leaves White somewhat uncoordinated. }
6... Nf6
{ Our position is comfortable, and we have some flexibility regarding our move order. The knight should be developed to the natural squares f6 and c6, bishop to d6 and kingside castling. }
7. O-O Bd6 { Or  7...Nc6  , which is equally good. } 8. d4 cxd4
{ There is nothing wrong about  8...O-O  or  8...Nc6  , either. } 9. Nxd4 O-O
{ We have reached a perfect moment to take stock. We have an isolated queen pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@, a very common pawn structure. In this particular case, we can be happy about our chances.  White has lost some time with their bishop @@StartBracket@@Bc4-e2@@EndBracket@@ and spent a tempo on playing a2-a4. This move is not desirable for White, as it does not improve White's position at all.  On the other hand, Black's move ...a6 is helpful and commonly seen in IQP structures. We like to control the square b5, which helps prepare ...Qc7 or give our bishop a square on a7 in some cases.  Our general strategy aims for active piece play and control of the e-file. We'd like to avoid trades, as they make it easier for White to put some pressure on our d-pawn. }
